INSERT INTO `Answers` VALUES (90,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3E@Konradx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EOOP may be flawed and it certainly is no silver bullet but it makes large-scale applications much simpler because itx27s a great way to reduce dependenciesx3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat is the dogma. I am not seeing what makes OOP significantly better in this regard than procedural programming of old. Whenever I make a procedure call I am isolating myself from the specifics of the implementation.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 19:11:06'),(90,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EI believe youx27d need to perform a separate query to accomplish that unfortionately.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI was able to accomplish this at my previous position using some help from this page:\n\nx3Ca href=x22http://aspnet.4guysfromrolla.com/articles/031506-1.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EPaging in DotNet 2.0x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThey also have it pulling a row count seperately.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 01:05:10'),(120,'aa9279','x3Cpx3EWell, if it support Python, you might be able to run Django using a FastCGI setup, as described here: x3Ca href=x22https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/dev/howto/deployment/fastcgi/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EFastCGI Docsx3C/ax3E. If it supports mod_python (which I guess itx27s what you mean), then sure, you can install it using the steps listed here: x3Ca href=x22https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.1/howto/deployment/modpython/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EModPython docsx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 04:29:17'),(120,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EI vaguely remember having a similar sounding problem with the DB2 for as/400 oledb driver when trying to set up a linked server from sql 2005 to the as/400. It was a permissions issue and I eventually found that only sql server accounts (not windows) could use the linked server because (i think) then the driver was loading using the credentials of the sql instead of impersonated ones. If it works when x22run asx22 admin then it gotta be permissions. x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 07:02:42'),(120,'mlowried','x3Cpx3ESome advantages of LINQ over sprocs:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EType safetyx3C/strongx3E: I think we all understand this.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EAbstractionx3C/strongx3E: This is especially true with x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb386964.aspxx22x3ELINQ-to-Entitiesx3C/ax3E.  This abstraction also allows the framework to add additional improvements that you can easily take advantage of.  x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc163329.aspxx22x3EPLINQx3C/ax3E is an example of adding multi-threading support to LINQ.  Code changes are minimal to add this support.  It would be MUCH harder to do this data access code that simply calls sprocs.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EDebugging supportx3C/strongx3E: I can use any .NET debugger to debug the queries.  With sprocs, you cannot easily debug the SQL and that experience is largely tied to your database vendor (MS SQL Server provides a query analyzer, but often that isnx27t enough).x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EVendor agnosticx3C/strongx3E: LINQ works with lots of databases and the number of supported databases will only increase.  Sprocs are not always portable between databases, either because of varying syntax or feature support (if the database supports sprocs at all).x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EDeploymentx3C/strongx3E: Others have mentioned this already, but itx27s easier to deploy a single assembly than to deploy a set of sprocs.  This also ties in with #4.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EEasierx3C/strongx3E: You donx27t have to learn T-SQL to do data access, nor do you have to learn the data access API (e.g. ADO.NET) necessary for calling the sprocs.  This is related to #3 and #4.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESome disadvantages of LINQ vs sprocs:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3ENetwork trafficx3C/strongx3E: sprocs need only serialize sproc-name and argument data over the wire while LINQ sends the entire query.  This can get really bad if the queries are very complex.  However, LINQx27s abstraction allows Microsoft to improve this over time.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3ELess flexiblex3C/strongx3E: Sprocs can take full advantage of a databasex27s featureset.  LINQ tends to be more generic in itx27s support.  This is common in any kind of language abstraction (e.g. C# vs assembler).x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3ERecompilingx3C/strongx3E: If you need to make changes to the way you do data access, you need to recompile, version, and redeploy your assembly.  Sprocs can x3Cemx3Esometimesx3C/emx3E allow a DBA to tune the data access routine without a need to redeploy anything.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESecurity and manageability are something that people argue about too.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3ESecurityx3C/strongx3E: For example, you can protect your sensitive data by restricting access to the tables directly, and put ACLs on the sprocs.  With LINQ, however, you can still restrict direct access  to tables and instead put ACLs on updatable table x3Cemx3Eviewsx3C/emx3E to achieve a similar end (assuming your database supports updatable views).  x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EManageabilityx3C/strongx3E: Using views also gives you the advantage of shielding your application non-breaking from schema changes (like table normalization).  You can update the view without requiring your data access code to change.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI used to be a big sproc guy, but Ix27m starting to lean towards LINQ as a better alternative in general.  If there are some areas where sprocs are clearly better, then Ix27ll probably still write a sproc but access it using LINQ. :)x3C/px3E',165,0,'2008-08-27 00:04:51'),(180,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EYou can change the location the project compliers and saves the dcu/unit/exe to in Project/Options under the Directories/Conditionals is that what you are looking for? x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI bevile there is also some settings for the DBE in the Tools menu, but I dont have them install at the moment (or i cant find them)x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 19:37:05'),(180,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EActually, by colllapsing the colums you already summed them, so the dimension doesnx27t matter at all for your example. Did I miss something or did you?x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 22:58:07'),(260,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EThis might be a reference to x3Ca href=x22http://rspec.info/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERSpecx3C/ax3E, which is a really clever way of developing tests as a series of requirements. Ix27m still getting used to it, but itx27s been very handy in both defining what I need to do and then ensuring I do it.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-27 03:12:14'),(260,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EOne solution is the system function defined in stdlib.h x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint system(const char *string);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/clibrary/cstdlib/system.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esystem api examplex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 02:59:56'),(330,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EOR:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT foo FROM bar WHERE baz BETWEEN 1 AND 3\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-20 17:05:32'),(330,'achancelier6','x3Cpx3EWhatever your [things] are need to be written outside of VBScript.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn VB6, x3Ca href=x22http://www.vb-helper.com/howto_custom_collection_with_for_each.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eyou can write a Custom Collection classx3C/ax3E, then youx27ll need to compile to an ActiveX DLL and register it on your webserver to access it.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 17:42:15'),(470,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EUsing the x27%x27 character Ix27ve searched our database using something like the following:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT name FROM TblNames WHERE name LIKE x27%overflowx27\n\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EUsing this form or query can be slow at times but we only use it for the occasional manual search.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 18:24:29'),(470,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EI had to do this for a project before. One of the major difficulties I had was explaining what I was trying to do to other people. I spent a ton of time trying to do this in SQL, but I found the pivot function woefully inadequate. I do not remember the exact reason why it was, but it is too simplistic for most applications, and it isnx27t full implemented in MS SQL 2000. I wound up writing a pivot function in .NET. Ix27ll post it here in hopes it helps someone, someday. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E x27x27x27 x26lt;summaryx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 Pivots a data table from rows to columnsx3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;/summaryx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;param name=x22dtOriginalx22x26gt;The data table to be transformedx26lt;/paramx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;param name=x22strKeyColumnx22x26gt;The name of the column that identifies each rowx26lt;/paramx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;param name=x22strNameColumnx22x26gt;The name of the column with the values to be transformed from rows to columnsx26lt;/paramx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;param name=x22strValueColumnx22x26gt;The name of the column with the values to pivot into the new columnsx26lt;/paramx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;returnsx26gt;The transformed data tablex26lt;/returnsx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x27x27x27 x26lt;remarksx26gt;x26lt;/remarksx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    Public Shared Function PivotTable(ByVal dtOriginal As DataTable, ByVal strKeyColumn As String, ByVal strNameColumn As String, ByVal strValueColumn As String) As DataTablex3Cbrx3E        Dim dtReturn As DataTablex3Cbrx3E        Dim drReturn As DataRowx3Cbrx3E        Dim strLastKey As String = String.Emptyx3Cbrx3E        Dim blnFirstRow As Boolean = Truex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E        x27 copy the original data table and remove the name and value columnsx3Cbrx3E        dtReturn = dtOriginal.Clonex3Cbrx3E        dtReturn.Columns.Remove(strNameColumn)x3Cbrx3E        dtReturn.Columns.Remove(strValueColumn)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E        x27 create a new row for the new data tablex3Cbrx3E        drReturn = dtReturn.NewRowx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E        x27 Fill the new data table with data from the original tablex3Cbrx3E        For Each drOriginal As DataRow In dtOriginal.Rowsx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E            x27 Determine if a new row needs to be startedx3Cbrx3E            If drOriginal(strKeyColumn).ToString x26lt;x26gt; strLastKey Thenx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E                x27 If this is not the first row, the previous row needs to be added to the new data tablex3Cbrx3E                If Not blnFirstRow Thenx3Cbrx3E                    dtReturn.Rows.Add(drReturn)x3Cbrx3E                End Ifx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E                blnFirstRow = Falsex3Cbrx3E                drReturn = dtReturn.NewRowx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E                x27 Add all non-pivot column values to the new rowx3Cbrx3E                For Each dcOriginal As DataColumn In dtOriginal.Columnsx3Cbrx3E                    If dcOriginal.ColumnName x26lt;x26gt; strNameColumn AndAlso dcOriginal.ColumnName x26lt;x26gt; strValueColumn Thenx3Cbrx3E                        drReturn(dcOriginal.ColumnName.ToLower) = drOriginal(dcOriginal.ColumnName.ToLower)x3Cbrx3E                    End Ifx3Cbrx3E                Nextx3Cbrx3E                strLastKey = drOriginal(strKeyColumn).ToStringx3Cbrx3E            End Ifx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E            x27 Add new columns if needed and then assign the pivot values to the proper columnx3Cbrx3E            If Not dtReturn.Columns.Contains(drOriginal(strNameColumn).ToString) Thenx3Cbrx3E                dtReturn.Columns.Add(drOriginal(strNameColumn).ToString, drOriginal(strValueColumn).GetType)x3Cbrx3E            End Ifx3Cbrx3E            drReturn(drOriginal(strNameColumn).ToString) = drOriginal(strValueColumn)x3Cbrx3E        Nextx3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E        x27 Add the final row to the new data tablex3Cbrx3E        dtReturn.Rows.Add(drReturn)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E        x27 Return the transformed data tablex3Cbrx3E        Return dtReturnx3Cbrx3E    End Functionx3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 19:16:32'),(470,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3ENot sure how credible x3Ca href=x22http://www.builderau.com.au/program/windows/soa/Getting-started-with-Windows-Server-2008-Core-edition/0,339024644,339288700,00.htmx22x3Ethis source isx3C/ax3E, but:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThe Windows Server 2008 Core edition can:x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Culx3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the file server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the Hyper-V virtualization server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the Directory Services role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the DHCP server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the IIS Web server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the DNS server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun the print server role.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3C/ulx3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EThe Windows Server 2008 Core edition cannot:x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Culx3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun a SQL Server.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun an Exchange Server.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun Internet Explorer.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun Windows Explorer.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EHost a remote desktop session.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERun MMC snap-in consoles locally.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\n  x3C/ulx3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',16,0,'2008-08-04 20:38:03'),(580,'aa9279','x3Cpx3EWex27ve been using it for a project here at work that needed to run on Linux but reuse some .NET libraries that we built in Managed C++.  Ix27ve been very surprised at how well it has worked out.  Our main executable is being written in C# and we can just reference our Managed C++ binaries with no issue.  The only difference in the C# code between Windows and Linux is RS232 serial port code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe only big issue I can think of happened about a month ago.  The Linux build had a memory leak that wasnx27t seen on the Windows build.  After doing some manual debugging (the basic profilers for Mono on Linux didnx27t help much), we were able to narrow the issue down to a specific chunk of code.  We ended up patching a workaround, but I still need to find some time to go back and figure out what the root cause of the leak was.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-20 23:23:30'),(580,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EThis is more or less the perfect use case for x3Ca href=x22http://svk.bestpractical.com/view/HomePagex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESVKx3C/ax3E.  SVK is a command line front end for subversion that works with an entire local copy of the repository.  So your commits, updates, etc. work on the local repository and you can then sync with a master.  I would generally recommend SVK over plain subversion anyway as it makes a lot of things nicer.  No .svn folders, better branching and merging, better conflict resolution.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-05 12:22:05'),(580,'hbuxcy1c','x3Ch2x3Elolcode:x3C/h2x3E\n\nx3Cpx3Esorry I couldnx27t resist xDx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EHAI\nCAN HAS STDIO?\nI HAS A VAR\nI HAS A INT\nI HAS A CHEEZBURGER\nI HAS A FACTORIALNUM\nIM IN YR LOOP\n    UP VAR!!1\n    TIEMZD INT!![CHEEZBURGER]\n    UP FACTORIALNUM!!1\n    IZ VAR BIGGER THAN FACTORIALNUM? GTFO\nIM OUTTA YR LOOP\nU SEEZ INT\nKTHXBYE\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',124,0,'2008-08-23 08:40:15'),(580,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EI am currently x22manuallyx22 doing it through a prebuild-exec Task, using my x3Ca href=x22http://www.stum.de/various-tools/cmdtools/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ecmdnetsvnrevx3C/ax3E tool, but if someone knows a better ccnet-integrated way of doing it, ix27d be happy to hear :-)x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 15:41:37'),(650,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EOne feature of the DataSet is that if you can call multiple select statements in your stored procedures, the DataSet will have one DataTable for each.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 17:15:53'),(650,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EThere is an x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=C243A5AE-4BD1-4E3D-94B8-5A0F62BF7796x26amp;displaylang=enx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eexpress version on SSMSx3C/ax3E that has considerably fewer features but still has the basics.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-07 23:25:57'),(650,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EHave you ever created a window using WinAPI?x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMore times than I care to remember.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThen you should know that you define a class (RegisterClass), create an instance of it (CreateWindow), call virtual methods (WndProc) and base-class methods (DefWindowProc) and so on. WinAPI even takes the nomenclature from SmallTalk OOP, calling the methods “messages” (Window Messages).x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen youx27ll also know that it does no message dispatch of its own, which is a big gaping void. It also has crappy subclassing.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EHandles may not be inheritable but then, therex27s final in Java. They donx27t lack a class, they are a placeholder for the class: Thatx27s what the word “handle” means. Looking at architectures like MFC or .NET WinForms itx27s immediately obvious that except for the syntax, nothing much is different from the WinAPI.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETheyx27re not inheritable either in interface or implementation, minimally substitutable, and theyx27re not substantially different from what procedural coders have been doing since forever.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIs this really it?  The best bits of OOP are just... traditional procedural code?  x3Cemx3EThatx27sx3C/emx3E the big deal?x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 21:13:26'),(650,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EI use it, especially since the hosted Version of FugBugz x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3180/anyone-soloing-using-fogbugz#3581x22x3Eis free for up to 2 peoplex3C/ax3E. I found it a lot nicer than paper as Ix27m working on multiple projects, and my paper tends to get rather messy once you start making annotations or if you want to re-organize and shuffle tasks around, mark them as complete only to see that they are not complete after all...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPlus, the Visual Studio integration is really neat, something paper just cannot compete with. Also, if you lay the project to rest for 6 months and come back, all your tasks and notes are still there, whereas with paper you may need to search all the old documents and notes again, if you did not discard it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBut that is just the point of view from someone who is not really good at staying organized :-) If you are a really tidy and organized person, paper may work better for you than it does for me.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBonus suggestion: Run Fogbugz on a second PC (or a small Laptop like the eeePC) so that you always have it at your fingertips. The main problem with Task tracking programs - be it FogBugz, Outlook, Excel or just notepad - is that they take up screen space, and my two monitors are usually full with Visual Studio, e-Mail, Web Browsers, some Notepads etc.x3C/px3E',35,0,'2008-08-06 12:52:51'),(650,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EYou can strip out the tags with regular expressions.  Just make sure that your expressions will not filter tags that were actually text.  If the text had x22\\bx22 in the body of text, it would appear as \\b in the RTF stream.   In other words, you would match on x22\\bx22 but not x22\\bx22.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou could probably take a short cut and filter out the header RTF tags.  Look for the first occurrence of x22\\viewkind4x22 in the input.  Then read ahead to the first space character.  You would remove all of the characters from the start of the text up to and including that space character.  That would strip out the RTF header information (fonts, colors, etc).x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 20:51:54'),(810,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EEncrypting the session value will have zero effect. The session cookie is already an arbitrary value, encrypting it will just generate another arbitrary value that can be sniffed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe only real solution is HTTPS. If you donx27t want to do SSL on your whole site (maybe you have performance concerns), you might be able to get away with only SSL protecting the sensitive areas. To do that, first make sure your login page is HTTPS. When a user logs in, set a secure cookie (meaning the browser will only transmit it over an SSL link) in addition to the regular session cookie. Then, when a user visits one of your x22sensitivex22 areas, redirect them to HTTPS, and check for the presence of that secure cookie. A real user will have it, a session hijacker will not.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEDITx3C/strongx3E: This answer was originally written in 2008. Itx27s 2016 now, and therex27s no reason not to have SSL across your entire site. No more plaintext HTTP!x3C/px3E',200,0,'2008-08-22 21:11:46'),(930,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EYes, you are right to lock at the VSZ.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3Eps ux3C/codex3E will give you the VSZ and RSS, which are the virtual memory size and resident set size.  The RSS is how much physical memory has been allocated to the process, and the VSZ is the virtual memory size of the process.  If you have several copies of a program running, a lot of the memory in the VSZ will be shared between those processes.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 12:21:07'),(1010,'idevey11','x3Cpx3ELINQ is not about SQL. LINQ is about being apply functional programming paradigmns on objects.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELINQ to SQL is an ORM built ontop of the LINQ foundation, but LINQ is much more. I donx27t use LINQ to SQL, yet I use LINQ all the time.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETake the task of finding the intersection of two lists:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBefore LINQ, this tasks requires writing a nested foreach that iterates the small list once for every item in the big list O(N*M), and takes about 10 lines of code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eforeach (int number in list1)\n{\n    foreach (int number2 in list2)\n    {\n        if (number2 == number)\n        {\n            returnList.add(number2);\n        }\n    }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUsing LINQ, it does the same thing in one line of code:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evar results = list1.Intersect(list2);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYoux27ll notice that doesnx27t look like LINQ, yet it is. You donx27t need to use the expression syntax if you donx27t want to.x3C/px3E',39,0,'2008-08-22 01:59:00'),(1010,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EIn short, those values after the % tell x3Ccodex3Eprintfx3C/codex3E how to interpret (or output) all of the variables coming later.  In your example, x3Ccodex3Eradiusx3C/codex3E is interpreted as a float (this the x27fx27), and the x3Ccodex3E10.1x3C/codex3E gives information about how many decimal places to use when printing it out.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESee x3Ca href=x22http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/clibrary/cstdio/printf.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethis linkx3C/ax3E for more details about all of the modifiers you can use with printf.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 17:51:18'),(1040,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3Efrom x3Ca href=x22http://www.timocracy.com/articles/2008/02/21/calling-invoking-rails-rake-tasks-from-within-ruby-for-testing-try-2x22x3Etimocracy.comx3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Erequire x27rakex27\n\nrequire x27rake/rdoctaskx27\n\nrequire x27rake/testtaskx27\n\nrequire x27tasks/railsx27\n\n\n\ndef capture_stdout\n\n  s = StringIO.new\n\n  oldstdout = $stdout\n\n  $stdout = s\n\n  yield\n\n  s.string\n\nensure\n\n  $stdout = oldstdout\n\nend\n\n\n\nRake.application.rake_require x27../../lib/tasks/metric_fetcherx27\n\nresults = capture_stdout {Rake.application[x27metric_fetcherx27].invoke}\n\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',37,0,'2008-08-06 19:24:00'),(1180,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EI use it as well and quite frankly wouldnx27t want to work without it.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve always had some kind of issue tracker available for the projects I work on and thus am quite used to updating it. With FB6 the process is now even better.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ESince FB also integrates with Subversion, the source control tool I use for my projects, the process is really good and I have two-way links between the two systems now. I can click on a case number in the Subversion logs and go to the case in FB, or see the revisions bound to a case inside FB.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-06 14:05:25'),(1180,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EThis isnx27t inherently dangerous, but the moment you pass any user-provided data into the function, itx27s ripe for a code injection exploit. Thatx27s worrisome, and something Ix27d avoid. I think a better approach would be to only expose the functionality you x3Cemx3Eneedx3C/emx3E, and nothing more.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 21:24:41'),(1300,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://google.com/analyticsx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGoogle Analyticsx3C/ax3E is free (up to 50,000 hits per month I think) and is easy to setup with just a little javascript snippet to insert into your header or footer and has great detailed reports, with some very nice graphs.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 18:25:01'),(1300,'srm4902','x3Cpx3ESo, you intend to modify the data being dropped based on the drop target?  I donx27t think this is possible; after all, you populate the data when the drag is initiated.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 00:42:23'),(1610,'aa9279','x3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3EAnd if it matters at all, apache@localhost is not the name of the user account that I use to get into the database. I donx27t have any user accounts with the name apache in them at all for that matter.x3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf it is saying x27apache@localhostx27 the username is not getting passed correctly to the MySQL connection. x27apachex27 is normally the user that runs the httpd process (at least on Redhat-based systems) and if no username is passed during the connection MySQL uses whomever is calling for the connection.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you do the connection right in your script, not in a called file, do you get the same error?x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-06 04:05:34'),(1760,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EI heavily prefer x3Ca href=x22http://www.cakephp.org/x22x3ECakePHPx3C/ax3E for PHP, x3Ca href=x22http://www.djangoproject.com/x22x3EDjangox3C/ax3E for Python, x3Ca href=x22http://www.rubyonrails.org/x22x3ERailsx3C/ax3E for Ruby.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn terms of front-end, if youx27re looking for a desktop-esque end user experience you should look into x3Ca href=x22http://www.extjs.com/x22x3EExtJSx3C/ax3E or x3Ca href=x22http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/x22x3EYUIx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-23 22:21:47'),(1760,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EThatx27s an interesting route OJ.\nWex27re looking at the feasability of a non-reversable method (still making sure we donx27t explicitly retrieve the data to decrypt) e.g. just store a Hash to compare on a submissionx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 14:06:03'),(1970,'ajan8','x3Cpx3ECheck out Googlex27s Testing blog: x3Ca href=x22http://googletesting.blogspot.com/x22x3Ehttp://googletesting.blogspot.com/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELots of interesting articles on testing code.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-24 19:42:39'),(1970,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EThe x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms679347%28VS.85%29.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EFlashWindowExx3C/ax3E function which controls the flashing takes a x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms679348%28VS.85%29.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EFLASHWINFOx3C/ax3E struct which has a uCount field to control how many times it flashes.  Also, a possible value for the dwFlags field is FLASHW_STOP to cause the flashing to stop.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: Forgot was a C# tagged question ... so x3Ca href=x22http://www.pinvoke.net/default.aspx/user32.FlashWindowExx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EP/Invoke goodness found herex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-27 08:02:17'),(1970,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EIf you want to perform more complicated operations, like reading the output of the external program, you may be better served by the x3Ca href=x22http://man.he.net/man3/popenx22x3Epopenx3C/ax3E system call. For example, to programmatically access a directory listing (this is a somewhat silly example, but useful x3Cemx3Easx3C/emx3E an example), you could write something like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#include x26lt;stdio.hx26gt;\n\nint main()\n{\n  int entry = 1;\n  char line[200];\n  FILE* output = popen(x22/usr/bin/ls -1 /usr/manx22, x22rx22);\n  while ( fgets(line, 199, output) )\n  {\n    printf(x22%5d: %sx22, entry++, line);\n  }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eto give output like thisx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E1: cat1\n2: cat1b\n3: cat1c\n4: cat1f\n5: cat1m\n6: cat1s\n...\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',11,0,'2008-08-20 05:52:59'),(2120,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EItx27s common practice to do this, especially to be able to include .h in the files that need it. Of course the performance is affected but try not to think about this problem until it arises :).x3Cbr /x3E\nItx27s better to start with the files separated and after that try to merge the .hx27s that are commonly used together to improve performance if you really need to. It all comes down to dependencies between files and this is very specific to each project.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 18:25:31'),(2120,'itrowla','x3Cpx3EBear in mind that the EntLib documentation specifically steers you towards the ASP.NET cache for ASP.NET applications. Thatx27s probably the strongest recommendation towards using it here. Plus the EntLib cache doesnx27t have dependencies, which for me is a big reason not to use it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI donx27t think therex27s a technical limitation as such on shipping System.Web as part of your app, though itx27s slightly odd that theyx27ve put that notice in on the .NET 3.5 page. Hanselman actually says he started out being creeped out by this notion, but became convinced. Also if you read the comments, he says that the block has too many moving parts and the ASP.NET Cache is much more lightweght.x3Cbr /x3E\nI think this is exactly the kind of problem that x3Ca href=x22http://blogs.msdn.com/velocity/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVelocityx3C/ax3E is going to solve, but thatx27s only a preview for now :-(  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27d say use Web.Caching and see how you get on. If you put some kind of abstraction layer over the top of it, youx27ve always got the option to swap it out for the EntLib block later on if you find problems.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-22 13:37:44'),(2120,'kgrenkovu','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EI want to add a rule that checks for\n  the presence of a folder.jpg file in\n  each directory, but to add this would\n  make the code substantially more messy\n  in itx27s current state..x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis doesnx27t look bad.  In fact your current code does it very nicely, and Sven mentioned a good way to do it as well:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EGet a list of all the filesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECheck for x22requiredx22 filesx3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou would just have have add to your dictionary a list of required files:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Echecker = {\n  ...\n  x27requiredx27: [x27filex27, x27listx27, x27for_requiredx27]\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs far as there being a better/extensible way to do this?  I am not exactly sure.  I could only really think of a way to possibly drop the x22multiplex22 regular expressions and build off of Svenx27s idea for using a delimiter.  So my strategy would be defining a dictionary as follows (and Ix27m sorry I donx27t know Python syntax and Ix27m a tad to lazy to look it up but it should make sense.  The /regex/ is shorthand for a regex):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Echeck_dict = {\n  x27delimx27    : /\\-/,\n  x27partsx27    : [ x27Show Namex27, x27Episode Namex27, x27Episode Numberx27 ],\n  x27patternsx27 : [/valid name/, /valid episode name/, /valid number/ ],\n  x27requiredx27 : [x27listx27, x27ofx27, x27filesx27],\n  x27ignoredx27  : [x27.*x27, x27hidden.txtx27],\n  x27start_dirx27: x27/path/to/dir/to/test/x27\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3ESplit the filename based on the delimiter.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECheck each of the parts.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBecause its an ordered list you can determine what parts are missing and if a section doesnx27t match any pattern it is malformed.  Here the x3Ccodex3Epartsx3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3Epatternsx3C/codex3E have a 1 to 1 ratio.  Two arrays instead of a dictionary enforces the order.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIgnored and required files can be listed.  The x3Ccodex3E.x3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3E..x3C/codex3E files should probably be ignored automatically.  The user should be allowed to input x22globsx22 which can be shell expanded.  Ix27m thinking here of x3Ccodex3Esvn:ignorex3C/codex3E properties, but globbing is natural for listing files.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHere x3Ccodex3Estart_dirx3C/codex3E would be default to the current directory but if you wanted a single file to run automated testing of a bunch of directories this would be useful.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe real loose end here is the path template and along the same lines what path is required for x22valid filesx22.  I really couldnx27t come up with a solid idea without writing one large regular expression and taking groups from it... to build a template.  It felt a lot like writing a TextMate language grammar.  But that starts to stray on the ease of use.  The real problem was that the path template was not composed of x3Ccodex3Epartsx3C/codex3E, which makes sense but adds complexity.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIs this strategy in tune with what you were thinking of?x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 02:02:01'),(2300,'sdally1','x3Cpx3EYoux27re doing this in c/c++... so you have an array of array of array... you donx27t have to visualize 20 dimensions since that isnx27t how the data is laid out in memory, for a 2 dimensional:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E[1] --x26gt; [1,2,3,4,5,6,...]\n[2] --x26gt; [1,2,3,4,5,6,...]\n[3] --x26gt; [1,2,3,4,5,6,...]\n[4] --x26gt; [1,2,3,4,5,6,...]\n[5] --x26gt; [1,2,3,4,5,6,...]\n .           .\n .           .\n .           .\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eso, why canx27t you iterate across the first one summing itx27s contents? If you are trying to find the size, then x3Ccodex3Esizeof(array)/sizeof(int)x3C/codex3E is a risky approach. You must know the dimension to be able to process this data, and set the memory up, so you know the depth of recursion to sum. Here is some pseudo code of what it seems you should do, x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Esum( n_matrix, depth )\n  running_total = 0\n  if depth = 0 then\n    foreach element in the array\n      running_total += elm\n  else \n     foreach element in the array\n       running_total += sum( elm , depth-1 )\n  return running_total\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:29:03'),(2530,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EToad Data Modeller from Quest does a nice job on this and is reasonably priced.  Embarcadero E/R studio is good too, as Bruce mentioned.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 03:40:47'),(2540,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EWhen I learned this in grade school (in Canada) it was referred to as BEDMAS:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EBx3C/strongx3Erackets x3Cbrx3E\n\nx3Cstrongx3EEx3C/strongx3Exponents x3Cbrx3E\n\nx3Cstrongx3EDx3C/strongx3Eivision x3Cbrx3E\n\nx3Cstrongx3EMx3C/strongx3Eultiplication x3Cbrx3E\n\nx3Cstrongx3EAx3C/strongx3Eddition x3Cbrx3E\n\nx3Cstrongx3ESx3C/strongx3Eubtractionx3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EJust for those from this part of the world...x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-06 19:11:01'),(2540,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EThe ISDATE() would take care of the rows which were not formatted properly if it were indeed being executed first.  However, if you look at the execution plan youx27ll probably find that the DATEDIFF predicate is being applied first - thus the cause of your pain.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re using SQL Server Management Studio hit x3Ckbdx3ECTRLx3C/kbdx3E+x3Ckbdx3ELx3C/kbdx3E to view the estimated execution plan for a particular query.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERemember, SQL isnx27t a procedural language and short circuiting logic may work, but only if youx27re careful in how you apply it.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 18:32:32'),(2550,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EDeleting the executable doesnx27t do the job. Thatx27s the problem. Also I could not identify any projectfile, whose datetime was the same as the later linked executable. That lets me conclude, that the x27creation datex27 is an information taken from within some project-file.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe project has 400000 lines, so a full build is no option. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 21:12:57'),(2550,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EIf your code uses lot of functions that operate on those attributes (name/height/weight), then using class could be a good option.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 19:42:51'),(2630,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EI think Silverlight and XAML is preferable to ActionScript, and though Ix27m not familiar with ActionScript IDEx27s, I am familiar with VS2008 and Expression Web/Blend, and they are very good development environments and getting better all the time.  I would go with Silverlight, and I think the key to getting users to install the plug-in is to have a good plug-in detect page that explains what SL is and why they need it.  For an example of this, go to x3Ca href=x22http://memorabilia.hardrock.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://memorabilia.hardrock.com/x3C/ax3E and try it with your SL plug-in disabled.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 23:52:34'),(2630,'idevey11','x3Cpx3ETwo Things I do:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EI blog about it - this allows me to go back and search my own blog.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWe use the code snippet feature in Visual Studio.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECheers.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 15:33:56'),(2630,'prihak','x3Cpx3EYes your ideas will help.x3Cbr /x3E\nLean on option 1 if there are no reads happening while your loading.x3Cbr /x3E\nLean on option 2 if you destination table is being queried during your processing.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E@Andrewx3Cbr /x3E\nQuestion.  Your inserting in chunks of 300.  What is the total amount your inserting?  SQL server should be able to handle 300 plain old inserts very fast.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 16:56:59'),(2630,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EWhen you say you donx27t know how many dimensions there are, how exactly are you defining the data structures?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAt some point, someone needs to create this array, and to do that, they need to know the dimensions of the array. You can force the creator to pass in this data along with the array.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUnless the question is to define such a data structure...x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:13:50'),(2750,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EKilling other processes is not a healthy thing to do. If your scenario involves something like uninstallation, you could use the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa365240%28VS.85%29.aspxx22x3Ex3Cstrongx3Ex3Ccodex3EMoveFileExx3C/codex3Ex3C/strongx3E API functionx3C/ax3E to mark the file for deletion upon next reboot.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf it appears that you really need to delete a file in use by another process, Ix27d recommend re-considering the actual problem before considering any solutions.x3C/px3E',32,0,'2008-08-04 10:01:52'),(2780,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EOn a Mac, the document root is what you see in the window that appears after you double click on the main hard drive icon on your desktop. The temp folder needs to be in there for a browser to find the CSS file as you have it written in your code. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EActually, you could also write the code like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;link href=x22file:///temp/test.cssx22 rel=x22stylesheetx22 type=x22text/cssx22 /x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 08:28:01'),(2780,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EThanks adeel825 x26amp; Michael Stum. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMy problem is, though, ix27m in a big corporation and do not have access to log in as the domain admin nor to view the active directory, so i guess my solution is to try and get that level of access.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 02:26:09'),(2780,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3ESetting up a DB connection is usually quite heavy. A lot of things are going on backstage x3Cstrongx3E(DNS resolution/TCP connection/Handshake/Authentication/Actual Query)x3C/strongx3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve had an issue once with some weird DNS configuration that made every TCP connection took a few seconds before going up. My login procedure (because of a complex architecture) took 3 different DB connections to complete. With that issue, it was taking forever to log-in. We then refactored the code to make it go through one connection only.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 20:59:49'),(2780,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EIts a programming paradigm.. Designed to make it easier for us mere mortals to break down a problem into smaller, workable pieces..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you dont find it useful.. Donx27t use it, donx27t pay for training and be happy.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI on the other hand do find it useful, so I will :)x3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-23 19:14:09'),(2780,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EBecause in most cases youx27ve got to sort your results first. For example, when you search on Google, x3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com.au/search?hl=enx26amp;safe=offx26amp;q=googlex26amp;start=1000x26amp;sa=Nx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eyou can view only up to 100 pages of resultsx3C/ax3E. They donx27t bother sorting by page-rank beyond 1000 websites for given keyword (or combination of keywords).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EPagination is fast. Sorting is slow.x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E',17,0,'2008-08-27 09:26:17'),(2840,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EGx27day,x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMost places where I have worked have folowed this practice. Ix27ve actually written coding standards for BAE (Aust.) along with the reasons why instead of just carving something in stone with no real justification.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EConcerning your question about source files, itx27s not so much time to compile but more an issue of being able to find the relevant code snippet in the first place. Not everyone is using an IDE. And knowing that you just look for MyClass.h and MyClass.cpp really saves time compared to running x22grep MyClass *.(h|cpp)x22 over a bunch of files and then filtering out the #include MyClass.h statements...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMind you there are work-arounds for the impact of large numbers of source files on compile times. See Large Scale C++ Software Design by John Lakos for an interesting discussion.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou might also like to read Code Complete by Steve McConnell for an excellent chapter on coding guidelines. Actualy, this book is a great read that I keep coming back to regularlyx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Echeers,\nRobx3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-26 18:31:52'),(2840,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EAny semi-decent algorithm will end up with a strong chance of generating a NULL value somewhere in the resulting ciphertext.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhy not do something like x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Base64x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ebase-64 encodex3C/ax3E your resulting binary blob before persisting to the DB? (x3Ca href=x22http://synesis.com.au/software/b64.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esample implementation in C++x3C/ax3E).x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 13:49:56'),(2900,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3E@Seanx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EHowever, factoring out common finctionality into a base class, then reusing that in other descendant classes is a deeply elegant thing, IMHO!x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBut x22proceduralx22 developers have been doing that for decades anyway.  The syntax and terminology might differ, but the effect is identical.  There is more to OOP than x22reusing common functionality in a base classx22, and I might even go so far as to say that that is hard to describe as OOP at all; calling the same function from different bits of code is a technique as old as the subprocedure itself.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-23 19:08:58'),(2900,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EI want to give you this message from x22Code Completex22:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EInheritance - subclasses - tends to\n  work against the primary technical\n  imperative you have as a programmer,\n  which is to manage complexity.For the sake of controlling complexity, you should maintain a heavy bias against inheritance.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',8,0,'2008-08-24 01:56:07'),(2900,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EI do all my database creation as DDL and then wrap that DDL into a schema maintainence class. I may do various things to create the DDL in the first place but fundamentally I do all the schema maint in code. This also means that if one needs to do non DDL things that donx27t map well to SQL you can write procedural logic and run it between lumps of DDL/DML.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMy dbs then have a table which defines the current version so one can code a relatively straightforward set of tests:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EDoes the DB exist? If not create it.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EIs the DB the current version? If not then run the methods, in sequence, that bring the schema up to date (you may want to prompt the user to confirm and - ideally - do backups at this point).x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor a single user app I just run this in place, for a web app we currently to lock the user out if the versions donx27t match and have a stand alone schema maint app we run. For multi-user it will depend on the particular environment.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe advantage? Well I have a very high level of confidence that the schema for the apps that use this methodology is consistent across all instances of those applications. Its not perfect, there are issues, but it works...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are some issues when developing in a team environment but thatx27s more or less a given anyway!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMurphx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 19:38:22'),(2970,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EIx27m guessing that because you want to set it for all users, that youx27re on some kind of shared computer, which is probably running under a domain?x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EHERE BE DRAGONSx3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ELetx27s say Joe and Jane regularly log onto the computer, then they will each have x27registriesx27.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYoux27ll then install your app, and the installer will employ giant hacks and disgusting things to set items under HKCU for them.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ETHEN, bob will come along and log on (he, and 500 other people have accounts in the domain and so can do this). Hex27s never used this computer before, so he has no registry. The first time he logs in, windows creates him one, but he wonx27t have your setting. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYour app then falls over or behaves incorrectly, and bob complains loudly about those crappy products from raynixon incorporated.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe correct answer is to just have some default settings in your app, which can write them to the registry if it doesnx27t find them. Itx27s general good practice that your app should never depend on the registry, and should create things as needed, for any registry entry, not just HKCU, anywayx3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-04 01:17:33'),(2970,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EIn C++ you can use the streaming operator to simplify things:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#if defined _DEBUG\n\nclass Trace\n{\npublic:\n   static Trace x26amp;GetTrace () { static Trace trace; return trace; }\n   Trace x26amp;operator x26lt;x26lt; (int value) { /* output int */ return *this; }\n   Trace x26amp;operator x26lt;x26lt; (short value) { /* output short */ return *this; }\n   Trace x26amp;operator x26lt;x26lt; (Trace x26amp;(*function)(Trace x26amp;trace)) { return function (*this); }\n   static Trace x26amp;Endl (Trace x26amp;trace) { /* write newline and flush output */ return trace; }\n   // and so on\n};\n\n#define TRACE(message) Trace::GetTrace () x26lt;x26lt; message x26lt;x26lt; Trace::Endl\n\n#else\n#define TRACE(message)\n#endif\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eand use it like:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evoid Function (int param1, short param2)\n{\n   TRACE (x22param1 = x22 x26lt;x26lt; param1 x26lt;x26lt; x22, param2 = x22 x26lt;x26lt; param2);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can then implement customised trace output for classes in much the same way you would do it for outputting to x3Ccodex3Estd::coutx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 17:24:41'),(2970,'srm4902','x3CPx3EYou should take a look at the UNPIVOT clause.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Ex3CSTRONGx3EUpdate1x3C/STRONGx3E: GateKiller, strangely enough I read an article (about something unrelated) about it this morning and Ix27m trying to jog my memory where I saw it again, had some decent looking examples too. Itx27ll come back to me Ix27m sure.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Ex3CSTRONGx3EUpdate2x3C/STRONGx3E: Found it: x3CA href=x22http://weblogs.sqlteam.com/jeffs/archive/2008/04/23/unpivot.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://weblogs.sqlteam.com/jeffs/archive/2008/04/23/unpivot.aspxx3C/Ax3Ex3C/Px3E',5,0,'2008-08-06 18:39:09'),(2970,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EIx27ve used x3Ca href=x22http://wtr.rubyforge.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWATIRx3C/ax3E, which is pretty good. I liked it because itx27s Ruby and allows for testing interactivity, available elements and source code parsing. I havenx27t used it for a while but I assume itx27s gotten better.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s supposedly being ported to Firefox and Safari, but thatx27s been happening for a while now.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 23:55:38'),(3230,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3EYoux27ll also want to make sure that your SSH system is well secured to prevent people from logging in x3Cemx3Easx3C/emx3E your Capistrano bot.  Ix27d suggest restricting access to password-protected key pairs.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEncrypting the .yml file on the server is useless since you have to give the bot the key, which would be stored . . . on the same server.  Encrypting it on your machine is probably a good idea.  Capistrano can decrypt it before sending.x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-20 20:41:15'),(3230,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EIf you have 2 users hitting it at the same time they will get the same id. Why didnx27t you use an id table with an identity instead, insert into that and use that as the unique (which is guaranteed) id, this will also perform much fasterx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cblockquotex3E\n    x3Cpx3Esp_getNextID x3C/px3E\n  x3C/blockquotex3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Enever ever prefix procs with sp_, this has performance implication because the optimizer first checks the master DB to see if that proc exists there and then th local DB, also if MS decide to create a sp_getNextID in a service pack yours will never get executedx3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 19:05:58'),(3260,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EThe only legitimate use of inheritance is to define a particular case of a base class like, for example, when inherit from Shape to derive Circle. To check this look at the relation in opposite direction: is a Shape a generalization of Circle? If the answer is yes then it is ok to use inheritance.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo if you have a class for which there can not be any particular cases that specialize its behavior it should be sealed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso due to LSP (Liskov Substitution Principle) one can use derived class where base class is expected and this is actually imposes the greatest impact from use of inheritance: code using base class x3Cemx3Emay be given an inherited class and it still has to work as expectedx3C/emx3E. In order to protect external code when there is no obvious need for subclasses you seal the class and its clients can rely that its behavior will not be changed. Otherwise external code needs to be explicitly designed to expect possible changes in behavior in subclasses.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA more concrete example would be Singleton pattern. You need to seal singleton to ensure one can not break the x22singletonnessx22.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-24 16:34:27'),(3260,'scurraghy','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eman 3 printf\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eon a Linux system will give you all the information you need.  You can also find these manual pages online, for example at x3Ca href=x22http://linux.die.net/man/3/printfx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://linux.die.net/man/3/printfx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-20 17:48:14'),(3470,'rdowdellz','x3Cpx3EWhat source control system are you using? x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAlmost all of them have some form of $ Id $ tag that gets expanded when the file is checked in.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI usually use some form of hackery to display this as the version number.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe other alternative is use to use the date as the build number: 080803-1448x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-03 22:46:33'),(3530,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EI donx27t mean this to sound snarky, but it doesnx27t matter.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESeriously.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELook at the things that are important: your project, your code, your job, your personal life. None of them are going to have their success rest on whether or not you use the x22thisx22 keyword to qualify access to fields. The this keyword will not help you ship on time. Itx27s not going to reduce bugs, itx27s not going to have any appreciable effect on code quality or maintainability. Itx27s not going to get you a raise, or allow you to spend less time at the office. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s really just a style issue. If you like x22thisx22, then use it. If you donx27t, then donx27t. If you need it to get correct semantics then use it. The truth is, every programmer has his own unique programing style. That style reflects that particular programmerx27s notions of what the x22most aesthetically pleasing codex22 should look like. By definition, any other programmer who reads your code is going to have a different programing style. That means there is always going to be something you did that the other guy doesnx27t like, or would have done differently. At some point some guy is going to read your code and grumble about something. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI wouldnx27t fret over it. I would just make sure the code is as aesthetically pleasing as possible according to your own tastes. If you ask 10 programmers how to format code, you are going to get about 15 different opinions. A better thing to focus on is how the code is factored. Are things abstracted right? Did I pick meaningful names for things? Is there a lot of code duplication? Are there ways I can simplify stuff? Getting those things right, I think, will have the greatest positive impact on your project, your code, your job, and your life. Coincidentally, it will probably also cause the other guy to grumble the least. If your code works, is easy to read, and is well factored, the other guy isnx27t going to be scrutinizing how you initialize fields. Hex27s just going to use your code, marvel at itx27s greatness, and then move on to something else.x3C/px3E',187,0,'2008-08-23 00:42:19'),(3530,'srm9547','x3Cpx3ETry x3Ca href=x22http://seattlerb.rubyforge.org/ruby2ruby/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eruby2rubyx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 08:24:49'),(4080,'aillidges','x3Cpx3Egive your form an x3Ccodex3Eidx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ethenx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Edocument.getElementById(x27formidx27).submit();\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you are loading Javascript into a x3Ccodex3Edivx3C/codex3E via x3Ccodex3EinnerHTMLx3C/codex3E, it wonx27t run...just FYI.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-29 06:43:46'),(4080,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EI found x3Ca href=x22http://unfuddle.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://unfuddle.comx3C/ax3E saved me messing about with installing SVN or git. You can get a free account in there and use either of those - plus you can use your OpenID there.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen you avoid having to mess about setting it up right and focus on how youx27re going to use it!x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 00:39:40'),(4080,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EIn PHP 5 you can use x3Ca href=x22http://www.php.net/manual/en/ref.soap.phpx22x3ESoapClientx3C/ax3E on the WSDL to call the web service functions. x3Ca href=x22http://www.php.net/manual/en/soapclient.construct.phpx22x3EFor examplex3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E$client = new SoapClient(x22some.wsdlx22);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eand $client is now an object which has class methods as defined in some.wsdl. So if there was a method called getTime in the WSDL then you would just call:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E$result = $client-x26gt;getTime();\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd the result of that would (obviously) be in the $result variable. You can use the __getFunctions method to return a list of all the available methods.x3C/px3E',80,0,'2008-08-23 22:54:21'),(4110,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EIf you have a company buying it, Toad from Quest Software has this kind of management functionality built in.  Itx27s basically a two-click operation to compare two schemas and generate a sync script from one to the other.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThey have editions for most of the popular databases, including of course Sql Server.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-03 04:22:03'),(4170,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3ENone of the APIs for the more x27Wordx27 like online editors seem to have any x27editx27 functionality, just download and upload. This is obviously due to the complexity of the documents being stored.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWith Google Docs API you can get a document, edit it, and then re-upload it (you may need to delete the previous version as well I think). Zoho seems to provide an x27updatex27 method which combines the two operations.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHave you looked at the Google Notebook API instead? This might provide more granular access to the data in the x27notex27 due to its structured approach to storing the data.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 12:11:08'),(4230,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EI think the best thing to do here would be one/both of two things:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3ERethink the design, if its too complex, find a less-complex way.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EStop trying to visualise it.. :P Just store the dimensions in question that you need to sum, then do them one at a time. Once you have the base code, then look at improving the efficiency of your algorithm.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:04:34'),(4230,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3ESubversion, CVS and all other source control systems are not good for Word documents and other office files (such as Excel spread sheets), since the files themselves are stored in a binary format. That means that you can never go back and annotate (or blame, or whatever you want to call it), or do diffs between documents.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are revision control systems for Word documents out there, unfortunately I do not know any good ones. We use such control systems for Excel at my work, and unfortunately they all cost money.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe good thing is that they make life a lot easier, especially if you ever have to do an audit or due diligence.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 14:07:28'),(4230,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EYou can modify the userx27s personal.xls file, stored in the excel startup directory (varies between Office versions). If you have lots of users though, that can be fiddly.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAn alternative way to get over your problem is to store the macro in a template (.xlt) file. Then when the users opens it they canx27t save it back over the original file, but have to specify a new filename to save it as. The disadvantage of this method is that you then get multiple copies of your original code all over the place with each saved file. If you modify the original .xlt and someone reruns the old macro in a previously-saved .xls file then things can get out of step.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 12:13:04'),(4230,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EIsnx27t it also a factor which order you set up the colors?x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ELike if you use Dillie-Os idea you need to mix the colors as much as possible. \n\n0 64 128 256 is from one to the next. but 0 256 64 128 in a wheel would be more x22apartx22x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EDoes this make sense?x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-02 22:16:07'),(4230,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EI think you need to use x3Ccodex3Edisplay: blockx3C/codex3E on your images. When images are x3Ccodex3Einlinex3C/codex3E therex27s a little extra space for the line spacing.x3C/px3E',16,0,'2008-08-22 14:14:24'),(4230,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EWith the x22Built inx22 stuff, you canx27t, as using 1.0.* or 1.0.0.* will replace the revision and build numbers with a coded date/timestamp, which is usually also a good way. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor more info, see the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn2.microsoft.com/en-us/library/c405shex%28vs.80%29.aspxx22x3EAssembly Linkerx3C/ax3E Documentation in the /v tag.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for automatically incrementing numbers, use the AssemblyInfo Task:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://code.msdn.microsoft.com/AssemblyInfoTaskversx22x3EAssemblyInfo Taskx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis can be configured to automatically increment the build number.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are 2 Gotchas:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EEach of the 4 numbers in the Version string is limited to 65535. This is a Windows Limitation and unlikely to get fixed.\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://blogs.msdn.com/msbuild/archive/2007/01/03/why-are-build-numbers-limited-to-65535.aspxx22x3EWhy are build numbers limited to 65535?x3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EUsing with with Subversion requires a small change:\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.andrewconnell.com/blog/archive/2006/08/29/4078.aspxx22x3EUsing MSBuild to generate assembly version info at build time (including SubVersion fix)x3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERetrieving the Version number is then quite easy:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EVersion v = Assembly.GetExecutingAssembly().GetName().Version;\nstring About = string.Format(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, @x22YourApp Version {0}.{1}.{2} (r{3})x22, v.Major, v.Minor, v.Build, v.Revision);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Chrx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd, to clarify: In .net or at least in C#, the build is actually the THIRD number, not the fourth one as some people (for example Delphi Developers who are used to Major.Minor.Release.Build) might expect.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn .net, itx27s Major.Minor.Build.Revision.x3C/px3E',69,0,'2008-08-03 15:41:38'),(4320,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EIf itx27s not in the dictionary, probably not.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 21:05:34'),(4320,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EAs for a practical example of how TDD/unit-testing can be applied, I really liked the \nx3Ca href=x22http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0131016490x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETDD - Practical Guide by David Astelsx3C/ax3E book. While itx27s focussed on Java, and uses an older version of JUnit and EasyMock in the example code, it gave me a really good idea on how to use unit testing/TDD on an actual project.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-27 17:12:22'),(4430,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3E@adeel - I think x3Ca href=x22http://injenuity.com/archives/64x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethis blog entryx3C/ax3E can give you some details at least about one user that has tried x3Ca href=x22http://www.dimdim.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDimDimx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 02:34:38'),(4430,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3ESome time ago I wrote a quick and dirty exe that would update the version #x27s in an assemblyinfo.{cs/vb} - I also have used rxfind.exe (a simple and powerful regex-based search replace tool) to do the update from a command line as part of the build process.  A couple of other helpfule hints:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Colx3E\n\nx3Clix3Eseparate the assemblyinfo into product parts (company name, version, etc.) and assembly specific parts (assembly name etc.).  See x3Ca href=x22http://blog.darrenstokes.com/2007/12/17/ease-versioning-multiple-assemblies-by-splitting-up-assemblyinfo/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EAlso - i use subversion, so I found it helpful to set the build number to subversion revision number thereby making it really easy to always get back to the codebase that generated the assembly (e.g. 1.4.100.1502 was built from revision 1502).x3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/olx3E',0,0,'2008-08-04 23:51:49'),(4430,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EI am looking for many answers to learn about new tools and consolidate this knowledge in a one question/thread, so I doubt there will be 1 true answer to this question.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EMy answer to my own question is that we use:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3EFindbugs to look for common errors bad/coding - run from maven, and also integrates easily into Eclipsex3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3ECobertura for our coverage reports - run from mavenx3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EHudson also has a task-scanner plugin that will display a count of your TODO and FIXMEs, as well as show where they are in the source files.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAll are integrated with Maven 1.x in our case and tied into Hudson, which runs our builds on check-in as well as extra things nightly and weekly. Hudson trend graphs our JUnit tests, coverage, findbugs, as well as open tasks. There is also a Hudson plugin that reports and graphs our compile warnings. We also have several performance tests with their own graphs of performance and memory use over time using the Hudson plots plugin as well.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 18:53:12'),(4610,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EI have written a NAnt build file that handles parsing SVN information and creating properties. I then use those property values for a variety of build tasks, including setting the label on the build. I use this target combined with the SVN Revision Labeller mentioned by lubos hasko with great results.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;target name=x22svninfox22 description=x22get the svn checkout informationx22x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22svn.infotempfilex22 value=x22${build.directory}\\svninfo.txtx22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;exec program=x22${svn.executable}x22 output=x22${svn.infotempfile}x22x26gt;x3Cbrx3E        x26lt;arg value=x22infox22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;/execx26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;loadfile file=x22${svn.infotempfile}x22 property=x22svn.infox22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;delete file=x22${svn.infotempfile}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22matchx22 value=x22x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;regex pattern=x22URL: (?x27matchx27.*)x22 input=x22${svn.info}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22svn.info.urlx22 value=x22${match}x22/x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;regex pattern=x22Repository Root: (?x27matchx27.*)x22 input=x22${svn.info}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22svn.info.repositoryrootx22 value=x22${match}x22/x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;regex pattern=x22Revision: (?x27matchx27\\d+)x22 input=x22${svn.info}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22svn.info.revisionx22 value=x22${match}x22/x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;regex pattern=x22Last Changed Author: (?x27matchx27\\w+)x22 input=x22${svn.info}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;property name=x22svn.info.lastchangedauthorx22 value=x22${match}x22/x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E    x26lt;echo message=x22URL: ${svn.info.url}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;echo message=x22Repository Root: ${svn.info.repositoryroot}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;echo message=x22Revision: ${svn.info.revision}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3E    x26lt;echo message=x22Last Changed Author: ${svn.info.lastchangedauthor}x22 /x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex26lt;/targetx26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',3,0,'2008-08-04 17:43:54'),(4610,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EXcode uses template files for file and project templates and does variable expansion in both at creation time.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EXcode 3.0 templates can be found in [Dev Installation]/Library/Xcode/, likely /Developer/Library/Xcode. If you want to modify these templates or add your own, use the following directories to save your new/modified templates so that they are not wiped out by future Developer Tool upgrades:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EFile templates:\n~/Library/Developer/Shared/Xcode/File\nTemplates/ x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETarget templates:\n~/Library/Developer/Shared/Xcode/Target\nTemplates/ x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EProject templates:\n~/Library/Developer/Shared/Xcode/Project\nTemplates/x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think that you can also use the /Library/Developer/Shared/Xcode/[File|Target|Project] Templates/ directory for templates shared by all users.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you just want to change the x3Cstrongx3EMyCompanyNamex3C/strongx3E in the templates, the following command line will do the trick:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Edefaults write com.apple.Xcode PBXCustomTemplateMacroDefinitions x27{ x22ORGANIZATIONNAMEx22 = x22NewCompanyNamex22;}x27\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA  good tutorial on writing file templates is x3Ca href=x22http://www.macresearch.org/custom_xcode_templatesx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E [MacResearch.org].x3C/px3E',31,0,'2008-08-29 05:44:41'),(4630,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EI agree with you in that it is quite an annoyance to me (I also copy and paste my address into the second input).x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThat being said, for less savvy users, it is probably a good idea. Watching my mother type is affirmation that many users do not look at the screen when they type (when shex27s using her laptop she resembles Linus from Peanuts when hex27s playing the piano).  If itx27s important for you to have the userx27s correct email address then I would say having a confirmation input is a very good idea (one of these days Ix27ll probably type my email address wrong in the first box and paste it wrong into the second box and then feel like a complete idiot).x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-07 19:58:31'),(4850,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EThis is all starting to sound a bit like x3Ca href=x22http://thedailywtf.com/Articles/SUSBSTITUTE_CODE.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EYesterdayx27s TDWTFx3C/ax3E. :-)x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:16:26'),(4850,'mlowried','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EUpdate:x3C/strongx3E I have found a 3rd party COM library called x3Ca href=x22http://www.dimastr.com/redemption/x22x3EOutlook Redemptionx3C/ax3E which is working fine for me at the moment. If you use it via COM-Interop in .NET, donx27t forget to release every COM object after you are done with it, otherwise your application crashes randomly.x3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-21 17:27:06'),(4850,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EMy first thought on this is x22how generate N vectors in a space that maximize distance from each other.x22 You can see that the RGB (or any other scale you use that forms a basis in color space) are just vectors. Take a look at x3Ca href=x22http://mathworld.wolfram.com/topics/RandomPointPicking.htmlx22x3ERandom Point Pickingx3C/ax3E. Hope this is a good start for you! Once you have a set of vectors that are maximized a part, you can save them in a hash table or something for later, and just perform random rotations on them to get all the colors you desire that are maximally apart from each other!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEdit:x3C/strongx3E Thinking about this problem more, it would be better to map the colors in a linear manor, possibly (0,0,0) --x3E (255,255,255) lexicographically, and then distribute them evenly. I really donx27t know how well this will work, but it should since, lets say:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3En = 10\nwe know we have 16777216 colors (256^3). We can use x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/561/using-combinations-of-sets-as-test-data#794x22x3Ebuckles algorithm 515x3C/ax3E to find the lexicographically indexed color.x3Cimg src=x22http://i.stack.imgur.com/gEuCs.gifx22 alt=x22\\frac {\\binom {256^3} {3}} {n} * ix22x3E. Youx27ll probably have to edit the algorithm to avoid overflow and probably add some minor speed improvements.x3C/px3E',21,0,'2008-08-02 23:03:52'),(4850,'sdally1','x3Cpx3E@Jeffx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3ERelative to straight procedural programming, the first fundamental tenet of OOP is the notion of information hiding and encapsulation. This idea leads to the notion of the class that seperates the interface from implementation.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhich has the more hidden implementation: C++x27s iostreams, or Cx27s FILE*s?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think the use of opaque context objects (HANDLEs in Win32, FILE*s in C, to name two well-known examples--hell, HANDLEs live on the other side of the kernel-mode barrier, and it really doesnx27t get much more encapsulated than that) is found in procedural code too; Ix27m struggling to see how this is something particular to OOP.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI suppose that may be a part of why Ix27m struggling to see the benefits: the parts that are obviously good are not specific to OOP, whereas the parts that are specific to OOP are not obviously good! (this is not to say that they are necessarily bad, but rather that I have not seen the evidence that they are widely-applicable and consistently beneficial).x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-23 19:54:57'),(4870,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EI enabled compression following similar articles to those posted above. The key to accessing the ViewState before the application sends it was overriding this method;x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprotected override void SavePageStateToPersistenceMedium(object viewState)x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can call the base method within this override and then add whatever additional logic you require to handle the ViewState.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-05 14:07:51'),(4880,'enewberryf','x3CPx3EAcceptable? Depends who you ask and what your requirements are. Is this app an internal one-off used by you and a few other people? Maybe this is good enough. If itx27s meant to be a production ready enterprise application that will grow and be maintained over the years, then you probably want to invest more effort up-front to build a maintainable app.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3ESeparation of Concerns is a key design technique for building maintainable apps. By mixing presentation, business, and data access logic all together, you can end up with a very fragile difficult to change application architecture.x3C/Px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 06:49:53'),(4880,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EProgramming WPF by Chris Sells and Ian Griffiths is an excellent way to learn WPF.  5 star rated on Amazon with 50+ reviews.  x3Ca href=x22http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0596510373x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.amazon.com/Programming-WPF-Chris-Sells/dp/0596510373x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 17:03:38'),(5260,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3E@Jeffx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI actually think this is an interesting question. Ix27m not sure how useful it is, but it is a valid question.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E@Edx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECan you provide a little more info on this question? You said the dimension of the array is dynamic, but is the number of elements dynamic as well?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: Ix27m going to try and answer the question anyways. I canx27t give you the code off the top of my head (it would take a while to get it right without any compiler here on this PC), but I can point you in the right direction ...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELetx27s use 8 dimensions (0-7) with indexes 0 to 3 as an example. You care about only 1,2 and 6. This means you have two arrays. First, x3Ccodex3Earray_care[4][4][4]x3C/codex3E for 1,2, and 6. The x3Ccodex3Earray_care[4][4][4]x3C/codex3E will hold the end result.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENext, we want to iterate in a very specific way. We have the array x3Ccodex3Einput[4][4][4][4][4][4][4][4]x3C/codex3E to parse through, and we care about dimensions 1, 2, and 6.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWe need to define some temporary indexes:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint dim[8] = {0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0};\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWe also need to store the order in which we want to increase the indexes:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint increase_index_order[8] = {7,5,4,3,0,6,2,1};\nint i = 0;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis order is important for doing what you requested.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDefine a termination flag:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ebool terminate=false;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow we can create our loop:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhile (terminate)\n{\narray_care[dim[1]][dim[2]][dim[6]] += input[dim[0]][dim[1]][dim[2]][dim[3]][dim[4]][dim[5]][dim[6]][dim[7]];\n\nwhile ((dim[increase_index_order[i]] = 3) x26amp;x26amp; (i x26lt; 8))\n{\ndim[increase_index_order[i]]=0;\ni++;\n}\n\nif (i x26lt; 8) {\ndim[increase_index_order[i]]++; i=0;\n} else {\nterminate=true;\n}\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat should work for 8 dimensions, caring about 3 dimensions. It would take a bit more time to make it dynamic, and I donx27t have the time. Hope this helps. I apologize, but I havenx27t learned the code markups yet. :(x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 23:32:36'),(5260,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EThatx27s definitely a good way to do it.  But you if you happen to be using a database that supports LINQ to SQL, it can be a lot more fun.  It can look something like this:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EMyDB db = new MyDB(x22Data Source=...x22);x3Cbrx3Evar q = from db.MyTablex3Cbrx3E        select c;x3Cbrx3Eforeach (var c in q)x3Cbrx3E  Console.WriteLine(c.MyField.ToString());x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',9,0,'2008-08-04 08:45:05'),(5260,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EItx27s a x22Structured Storagex22 document. Ix27ve successfully used x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeproject.com/KB/files/structstor.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EAndrew Peacex27s codex3C/ax3E to read these in the past, even under .NET (using C++/CLI) - itx27s clean and fairly easy to understand. Basically, you need to figure out which records you need, and query for those - it gets a little bit hairy, since different versions of Outlook and different types of messages will result in different records... x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-21 22:25:08'),(5460,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EI fully agree with x3Ca href=x22#11712x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EOrion Edwardsx3C/ax3E, and it is usually the way I approach the problem; but lately Ix27ve been starting to see some patterns(!) to the madness.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor more complex tasks I usually use something like an x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpreter_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Einterpreterx3C/ax3E (or a x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Estrategyx3C/ax3E) that uses some x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Builder_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ebuilderx3C/ax3E (or x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factory_method_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Efactoryx3C/ax3E) to create each part of the data.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor streaming data, the entire parser would look something like an x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adapter_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eadapterx3C/ax3E, adapting from a stream object to an object stream (which usually is just a queue).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor your example there would probably be one builder for the complete data structure (from head to EOF) which internally uses builders for the internal data elements (fed by the interpreter). Once the EOF is encountered an object would be emitted.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, objects created in a switch statement in some factory function is probably the simplest way for many lesser tasks. Also, I like keeping my data-objects immutable as you never know when someone shoves concurrency down your throat :)x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-24 20:03:41'),(5690,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EIt looks like you could use a combination of GetHTML and SetHTML to get the current contents, append your html and reinsert everything into the editor. Although it does say x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3ENote that when using this method, you will lose any listener that you may have previously registered on the editor.EditorDocument.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope that helps!x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-24 23:17:43'),(5880,'achancelier6','x3Cpx3Emaybe you should take the approach of defaulting to: x22the filename is correctx22 and work from there