 totally impractical, but then again it might be a helpful different direction.  If you know how the readings can fail, and there is a certain interval between peaks given such failures, why not do gradient descent at each interval.  If the descent brings you back to an area youx27ve searched before, you can abandon it.  Depending upon the shape of the sampled surface, this also might help you find peaks faster than search.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 15:38:37'),(6890,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EI have only really used PL/pgSQL, but that was because I needed a few stored procedures relatively fast and didnx27t want to add extra modules to the server.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELonger term, I would probably use PL/Perl or PL/Python, as I use perl for quick scripting and have been looking at python for a while now.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOne thing I have found is that there is a lack of good documentation for that on the PostgreSQL site. The manuals were thorough as a reference, but did not work well as a tutorial to help show people how it should be done.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat, combined with a very good debugging environment, meant that my first experience of writing procedures involved looking at weird syntax errors for a long time.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf someone knows of a good site with tutorials etc for PostgreSQL programming, I would love to get a link to it.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-06 18:26:08'),(7190,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3ETurn that into a spec:x3Cbr /x3E\n-that objects need to implement an interface in order to be allowed into the collection\nSomething like x3Ccodex3EArrayListx26lt;ICloneablex26gt;()x3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen you can be assured that you always do a deep copy - the interface should have a method that is guaranteed to return a deep copy.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think thatx27s the best you can do.  x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-27 13:52:49'),(7440,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EAs a student Ix27d recommend forgetting about what youx27re programming and focusing on the software process itself. Understand how to analyse a problem and ask the right questions; learn every design pattern you can and actually x3Cstrongx3Eapply them allx3C/strongx3E to gain a real understanding and appreciation of object-oriented design; write tests and then code only as much as you need to in order to make the tests pass. I think the best way to really learn is to just code as much as you can - the language and the domain arenx27t important, browse x3Ca href=x22http://www.sourceforge.netx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esourceforgex3C/ax3E and x3Ca href=x22http://www.freshmeat.netx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Efreshmeatx3C/ax3E for any interesting-sounding projects and get involved. Whatx27s important is understanding the fundamentals of software engineering.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd yes, this includes C. Or Assembler. This is the easiest way to get a good understanding of how your computer works and what your high-level code is actually doing.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFinally, never stop learning - Service-oriented architecture, inversion of control, domain-specific languages, business process management are all showing huge benefits so theyx27re important to be aware of - But by the time you finish studying and join the workforce who knows what the next big thing will be?x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 17:40:51'),(7440,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EI know I find OOP useful pretty much solely on a syntactical sugar basis (encapsulation, operator overloading, typechecking). As to the benefits of OOP... I donx27t know. I donx27t think itx27s x3Cemx3Eworsex3C/emx3E than procedural stuff. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOn the lighter side, my OOP lecturer said that OOP is important because otherwise the x22code would have too many loopsx22. Yeah. Sometimes itx27s depressing that I pay $500 per paper. :(x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-29 05:30:38'),(7470,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3E10.1fx3C/strongx3E means you want to display a x3Cstrongx3Efx3C/strongx3Eloat with x3Cstrongx3E1x3C/strongx3E decimal and the displayed number should be x3Cstrongx3E10x3C/strongx3E characters long.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 17:50:37'),(7540,'prihak','x3Cpx3EThe same rule applies here, but it notes a few exceptions where it is allowed Like so:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EInheritance treesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EClasses that are only used within a x3Cstrongx3Everyx3C/strongx3E limited scopex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ESome Utilities are simply placed in a general x27utils.hx27x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:30:11'),(7540,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NAntx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ENAntx3C/ax3Ex3C/strongx3E and x3Cstrongx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSBuildx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSBuildx3C/ax3Ex3C/strongx3E are the most popular tools to automate your build in x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.NET_Frameworkx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E.NETx3C/ax3E, and you can find a discussion on there of the pros/cons of each in the Stack Overflow question x3Cemx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/16550x22x3EBest .NET build toolx3C/ax3Ex3C/emx3E.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-24 00:52:43'),(7720,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EValidation should be captured separately from getters or setters in a validation method.  That way if the validation needs to be reused across multiple components, it is available.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen the setter is called, such a validation service should be utilized to sanitize input into the object.  That way you know all information stored in an object is valid at all times.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou donx27t need any kind of validation for the getter, because information on the object is already trusted to be valid.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EDonx27t save your validation until a database update!! It is better to x3Cstrongx3Efail fastx3C/strongx3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-05 23:55:52'),(7720,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIt really depends on the namespaces and classes that you are using from the .NET framework.  I had interest in converting one of my windows services to run on my email server, which is Suse, but we ran into several hard roadblocks with APIs that had not been completely implemented.  There is a chart somewhere on the Mono website that lists all of the classes and their level of completion.  If your application is covered, then go for it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELike any other application, do prototyping and testing before you make a full commitment, of course.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother problem we ran into is licensed software: if you are referencing someone elsex27s DLL, you canx27t code your way around incompatibilities that are buried in that assembly.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 22:21:50'),(7720,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EThe following regex should do the job (Perl regex syntax):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E/(10\\.\\d+\\/\\d+)/\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou could do some additional sanity checking by opening the urlsx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ehttp://hdl.handle.net/x26lt;doix26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eandx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ehttp://dx.doi.org/x26lt;doix26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewhere  is the candidate doi,x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eand testing that you a) get a 200 OK http status, and b) the returned page is not the x22DOI not foundx22 page for the service.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-27 10:51:20'),(7880,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EThe biggest thing youx27ll probably want to learn is the differences between Windows and non-Windows programmers.  They approach fundamental things differently.  Knowing the difference will be key to successfully managing the project.  If you listen to the stack overflow podcast, and Jeff and Joel have multiple discussions on this topic.  Understanding the details of the underlying technology is mostly irrelevant and youx27ll never know it well enough to go toe to toe with someone who works in it day in and day out.  You can probably pick it up as you go.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 18:27:46'),(7940,'sspindlerw','x3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3ECustomizing csproj files to autogenerate AssemblyInfo.csx3C/strongx3E x3Cbrx3E\n\n  x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeproject.com/KB/dotnet/Customizing_csproj_files.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.codeproject.com/KB/dotnet/Customizing_csproj_files.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\n  \n\n  x3Cpx3EEvery time we create a new C# project,\n\n  Visual Studio puts there the\n\n  AssemblyInfo.cs file for us. The file\n\n  defines the assembly meta-data like\n\n  its version, configuration, or\n\n  producer.x3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EFound the above technique to auto-gen AssemblyInfo.cs using MSBuild. Will post sample shortly.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 17:22:31'),(8050,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EBecause you always want to be handed a reference to the class and not to a derived one for various reasons:x3Cbr /x3E\ni. invariants that you have in some other part of your codex3Cbr /x3E\nii. securityx3Cbr /x3E\netcx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, because itx27s a safe bet with regards to backward compatibility - youx27ll never be able to close that class for inheritance if itx27s release unsealed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOr maybe you didnx27t have enough time to test the interface that the class exposes to be sure that you can allow others to inherit from it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOr maybe therex27s no point (that you see now) in having a subclass.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOr you donx27t want bug reports when people try to subclass and donx27t manage to get all the nitty-gritty details - cut support costs.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-24 01:43:24'),(8140,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EIx27ve done quite a few projects using Community Server. If youx27re okay with the out-of-the-box functionality, or you donx27t mind sticking to the version you start with, I think youx27ll be very happy.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe times Ix27ve run into headaches using CS is when the client wants functionality CS does not provide, but also insists on keeping the ability to upgrade to the latest version whenever Telligent releases an update. You can mostly support that by making all of your changes either in a separate project or by only modifying aspx/ascx files (no codebehinds). Some kind of merge is going to be required though no matter how well you plan it out.x3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-08 03:08:54'),(8790,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EMost rich text editors let you specify whether or not to disable the browserx27s spellchecker (as answered by others), with the exception of those running in Safari.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere is currently no way to programmatically disable the Safari spellchecker (as there is in FF and IE7+), so most rich text editors choose to let Safari do its own thing by leaving the browser in control of the context menu.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 01:50:09'),(8790,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3ERex, I suspect a good place to start looking is solutions that x3Cstrongx3Ecompress the ViewStatex3C/strongx3E -- theyx27re grabbing ViewState on the server before itx27s sent down to the client and gzipping it. Thatx27s exactly where you want to be.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.hanselman.com/blog/CommentView,guid,febce059-7e7c-439e-af3d-c53d250b3e9c.aspxx22x3EScott Hanselman on ViewState Compressionx3C/ax3E (2005)x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.bloggingdeveloper.com/post/How-To-Compress-ViewState-in-ASPNET-20-ViewState-Compression-with-SystemIOCompression.aspxx22x3EViewState Compression with System.IO.Compressionx3C/ax3E (2007)x3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E',7,0,'2008-08-04 12:04:41'),(8790,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EI agree with Justin, while most technical folks will use the copy, paste method, for the less savvy users it is a good practice.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOne more thing that I would add is that the second field should have the auto-complete feature disabled.  This ensures that there is human input from either method on at least one of the fields.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-07 20:02:00'),(8800,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EThere are so many itx27s crazy.  Crazy good, I guess.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EFor the conservative types (me), x3Ca href=x22http://www.nunit.org/x22x3Ex3Cstrongx3ENUnitx3C/strongx3Ex3C/ax3E is still available and still more than capable.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EFor the Microsoft-types, x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/vstudio/default.aspxx22x3Ex3Cstrongx3EMSTestx3C/strongx3Ex3C/ax3E is adequate, but slow and clunky compared to Nunit.  It also lacks code coverage without paying the big bucks for the pricey versions of Visual Studio.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETherex27s also x3Ca href=x22http://www.mbunit.com/About.aspxx22x3Ex3Cstrongx3EMbUnitx3C/strongx3Ex3C/ax3E.  Itx27s like NUnit, but has nifty features like RowTest (run the same test with different parameters) and Rollback (put the database back like you found it after a test) x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EAnd finally, x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/xunitx22x3Ex3Cstrongx3ExUnit.netx3C/strongx3Ex3C/ax3E is the trendy option with some attitude.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EOh, and x3Ca href=x22http://testdriven.net/x22x3Ex3Cstrongx3ETestDriven.NETx3C/strongx3Ex3C/ax3E will give you IDE integration for both Nunit and MBunit.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m sure theyx27re all just fine.  Ix27d steer away from MSTest though, unless you just enjoy the convenience of having everything in one IDE out of the box.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.hanselminutes.com/default.aspx?showID=130x22x3EScott Hanselmanx3C/ax3E has a podcast on this very topic.x3C/px3E',47,0,'2008-08-05 06:15:24'),(8940,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EIx27ve read somewhere the human eye canx27t distinguish between less than 4 values apart. so This is something to keep in mind. The following algorithm does not compensate for this.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m not sure this is exactly what you want, but this is one way to randomly generate non-repeating color values:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3E(beware, inconsistent pseudo-code ahead)x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E//colors entered as 0-255 [R, G, B]x3Cbrx3Ecolors = []; //holds final colors to be usedx3Cbrx3Erand = new Random();x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E//assumes n is less than 16,777,216x3Cbrx3ErandomGen(int n){x3Cbrx3E   while (len(colors) x26lt; n){x3Cbrx3E      //generate a random number between 0,255 for each colorx3Cbrx3E      newRed = rand.next(256);x3Cbrx3E      newGreen = rand.next(256);x3Cbrx3E      newBlue = rand.next(256);x3Cbrx3E      temp = [newRed, newGreen, newBlue];x3Cbrx3E      //only adds new colors to the arrayx3Cbrx3E      if temp not in colors {x3Cbrx3E         colors.append(temp);x3Cbrx3E      }x3Cbrx3E   }x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOne way you could optimize this for better visibility would be to compare the distance between each new color and all the colors in the array:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efor item in color{x3Cbrx3E   itemSq = (item[0]^2 + item[1]^2 + item[2]^2])^(.5);x3Cbrx3E   tempSq = (temp[0]^2 + temp[1]^2 + temp[2]^2])^(.5);x3Cbrx3E   dist = itemSq - tempSq;x3Cbrx3E   dist = abs(dist);x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3E//NUMBER can be your chosen distance apart.x3Cbrx3Eif dist x26lt; NUMBER and temp not in colors {x3Cbrx3E   colors.append(temp);x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EBut this approach would significantly slow down your algorithm.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother way would be to scrap the randomness and systematically go through every 4 values and add a color to an array in the above example.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-01 23:36:46'),(8940,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EItx27s called x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_compositingx22x3Ealpha blendingx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn psuedocode, assuming the background color (blend) always has 255 alpha. Also assumes alpha is 0-255.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ealpha=argb.alpha()x3Cbrx3Er = (alpha/255)*argb.r() + (1 - alpha/255)*blend.r()x3Cbrx3Eg = (alpha/255)*argb.g() + (1 - alpha/255)*blend.g()x3Cbrx3Eb = (alpha/255)*argb.b() + (1 - alpha/255)*blend.b()x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3Enote: you probably need to be a bit (more) careful about floating-point/int math and rounding issues, depending on language. Cast intermediates accordinglyx3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEdited to add:x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you donx27t have a background color with an alpha of 255, the algebra gets alot more complicated. Ix27ve done it before and itx27s a fun exercise left to the reader (if you really need to know, ask another question :). x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn other words, what color C blends into some background the same as blending A, then blending B. This is sort of like calculating A+B (which isnx27t the same as B+A).x3C/px3E',15,0,'2008-08-06 00:16:03'),(8950,'achancelier6','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EHANDLEs (and the rest of the WinAPI) is OOP! x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAre they, though?  Theyx27re not inheritable, theyx27re certainly not substitutable, they lack well-defined classes... I think they fall a long way short of x22OOPx22.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 20:31:57'),(8950,'hschade12','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.easymaths.com/What_on_earth_is_Bodmas.htmx22x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.easymaths.com/What_on_earth_is_Bodmas.htmx22x3Ehttp://www.easymaths.com/What_on_earth_is_Bodmas.htmx3C/ax3Ex3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EWhat do you think the answer to 2 + 3 x 5 is?x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EIs it (2 + 3) x 5 = 5 x 5 = 25 ?x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Eor 2 + (3 x 5) = 2 + 15 = 17 ?x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EBODMAS can come to the rescue and give us rules to follow so that we always get the right answer:x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3E(B)rackets (O)rder (D)ivision (M)ultiplication (A)ddition (S)ubtractionx3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EAccording to BODMAS, multiplication should always be done before addition, therefore 17 is actually the correct answer according to BODMAS and will also be the answer which your calculator will give if you type in 2 + 3 x 5 .x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhy it is useful in programming? No idea, but i assume itx27s because you can get rid of some brackets? I am a quite defensive programmer, so my lines can look like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eresult = (((i + 4) - (a + b)) * MAGIC_NUMBER) - ANOTHER_MAGIC_NUMBER;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewith BODMAS you can make this a bit clearer:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eresult = (i + 4 - (a + b)) * MAGIC_NUMBER - ANOTHER_MAGIC_NUMBER;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think ix27d still use the first variant - more brackets, but that way i do not have to learn yet another rule and i run into less risk of forgetting it and causing those weird hard to debug errors?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EJust guessing at that part though.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMike Stone EDIT: Fixed math as Gaius points outx3C/px3E',21,0,'2008-08-06 18:57:01'),(8950,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EI used to use NUnit, but I switched to MbUnit since it has more features.  I love RowTest.  It lets you parametrize your tests.  NUnit does have a litter bit better tool support though.  I am using ReSharper to run MbUnit Tests.  Ix27ve had problems with TestDriven.NET running my SetUp methods for MbUnit.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 01:03:00'),(8950,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EWe access Informix from .NET and use multiple connections.  Unless wex27re starting a transaction on each connection, it often is handled in the connection pool.  I know thatx27s very brand-specific, but most(?) database systemsx27 cilent access will pool connections to the best of its ability.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs an aside, we did have a problem with connection count because of cross-database connections.  Informix supports synonyms, so we synonymed the common offenders and the multiple connections were handled server-side, saving a lot in transfer time, connection creation overhead, and (the real crux of our situtation) license fees.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 21:02:28'),(8970,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EIx27ve started using x3Ca href=x22http://www.linqpad.net/x22x3ELinqPadx3C/ax3E. In addition to being more lightweight than SSMS, you can also practice writing LINQ queries- way more fun than boring old TSQL!x3C/px3E',39,0,'2008-08-08 00:31:12'),(8970,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EThe SAS guys at work have mentioned x3Ca href=x22http://www.r-project.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-29 05:32:52'),(8970,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3ELook into  build tool x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NAntx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ENAntx3C/ax3E or x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSBuildx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSBuildx3C/ax3E. I believe MSBuild is the build tool for Visualx26nbsp;Studiox26nbsp;2005 and later. I am, however, a fan of NAnt...x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-24 00:43:02'),(8970,'idevey11','x3Cpx3Ex3CPx3EOk, in terms of reading material, this is the pick of the books out there: x3CA href=x22http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0672328917x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWindows Presentation Foundation Unleashedx3C/Ax3E.x3C/Px3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3CPx3EFor blogs, there are a lot of blogs andx26nbsp;articles on x3CA href=x22http://windowsclient.net/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWindowsClient.netx3C/Ax3E, and therex27s an excellent blog all about data binding in WPF by x3CA href=x22http://www.beacosta.com/blog/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBeatriz Costax3C/Ax3E. Also take a look at x3CA href=x22http://learnwpf.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELearnWPF.comx3C/Ax3E and x3CA href=x22http://www.drwpf.com/blog/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EAsk Dr. WPFx3C/Ax3E.x3C/Px3Ex3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-27 12:03:48'),(8970,'sdally1','x3Cpx3EVery roughly and from memory since I donx27t have code on this laptop:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eusing (OleDBConnection conn = new OleDbConnection())\n{\n  conn.ConnectionString = x22Whatever connection stringx22;\n\n  using (OleDbCommand cmd = new OleDbCommand())\n  {\n    cmd.Connection = conn;\n    cmd.CommandText = x22Select * from CoolTablex22;\n\n    using (OleDbDataReader dr = cmd.ExecuteReader())\n    {\n      while (dr.Read())\n      {\n        // do something like Console.WriteLine(dr[x22column namex22] as String);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',15,0,'2008-08-04 05:07:14'),(9240,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EI agree with emailing, the wiki and the blog. Emailing is the most useful. If you canx27t use GMail and youx27re on windows, install a desktop search utility (Windows search, Google Desktop, Copernic, etc)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI also like to jot it into a textfile and save it in my documents folder. Whatever desktop search utility you use will be able to find it easily. e.g.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E//print spool stop.notes.txt\nIf the printer spooler stops, start it again by \n- Services x26gt; Provision Networks x26gt; Restart Service\n\ntags: printer provision no printer spooler cannot print remote desktop\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 15:51:02'),(9240,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EBecause you want the x3Cemx3Ecapabilityx3C/emx3E of being able to distribute the layers onto different physical tiers (I always use x22tierx22 for physical, and x22layerx22 for logical), you should think twice before just putting everything into one class because youx27ve got major refactorings to do if or when you do need to start distributing.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 13:45:20'),(9410,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EYou have basically two options. Either you write a simple script that will start and parse output fromx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Esvn.exe info --revision HEADx3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eto obtain revision number (then generating AssemblyInfo.cs is pretty much straight forward) or just use plugin for CCNET. Here it is:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3ESVN Revision Labellerx3C/strongx3E is a plugin for\n  CruiseControl.NET that allows you to\n  generate CruiseControl labels for your\n  builds, based upon the revision number\n  of your Subversion working copy. This\n  can be customised with a prefix and/or\n  major/minor version numbers.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/svnrevisionlabeller/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://code.google.com/p/svnrevisionlabeller/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI prefer the first option because itx27s only roughly 20 lines of code:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eusing System;\nusing System.Diagnostics;\n\nnamespace SvnRevisionNumberParserSample\n{\n    class Program\n    {\n        static void Main()\n        {\n            Process p = Process.Start(new ProcessStartInfo()\n                {\n                    FileName = @x22C:\\Program Files\\SlikSvn\\bin\\svn.exex22, // path to your svn.exe\n                    UseShellExecute = false,\n                    RedirectStandardOutput = true,\n                    Arguments = x22info --revision HEADx22,\n                    WorkingDirectory = @x22C:\\MyProjectx22 // path to your svn working copy\n                });\n\n            // command x22svn.exe info --revision HEADx22 will produce a few lines of output\n            p.WaitForExit();\n\n            // our line starts with x22Revision: x22\n            while (!p.StandardOutput.EndOfStream)\n            {\n                string line = p.StandardOutput.ReadLine();\n                if (line.StartsWith(x22Revision: x22))\n                {\n                    string revision = line.Substring(x22Revision: x22.Length);\n                    Console.WriteLine(revision); // show revision number on screen                       \n                    break;\n                }\n            }\n\n            Console.Read();\n        }\n    }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',13,0,'2008-08-04 15:56:42'),(9650,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EWhat I found works best is to really learn CSS. I mean x3Cstrongx3Ereallyx3C/strongx3E learn CSS.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt can be a confusing language to learn, but if you read enough about it and practice, eventually youx27ll learn the best way to do things.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe key is to do it enough that it comes natural. CSS can be very elegant if you know what you want to do before you start and you have enough experience to do it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGranted, it is also a major PITA to do sometimes, but even cross-browser issues arenx27t so bad if you x3Cstrongx3Ereallyx3C/strongx3E practice at it and learn what works and what doesnx27t, and how to get around problems.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAll it takes is practice and in time you can become good at it.x3C/px3E',33,0,'2008-08-25 03:47:41'),(9650,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EFor Windows work:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.scootersoftware.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBeyond Comparex3C/ax3E - great diffing tool, works well with files and folders.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.launchy.net/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELaunchyx3C/ax3E - lets me start programs without moving my hands from the keyboard.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 06:57:55'),(10190,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EIf you select only the columns you want in the linq query, and then call .ToList() on the query, it will be immedietly executed, and will only bring back the columns you are interested in. For example if you do this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evar q = from p in dataContext.products select p.ProductName;\nvar results = q.ToList();\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou will get back a list of product names stored in results, and when the query executes on the server it will only bring back the ProductName column.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-27 02:11:03'),(10190,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EHaskell:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eones = 1 : ones\nintegers   = head ones     : zipWith (+) integers   (tail ones)\nfactorials = head integers : zipWith (*) factorials (tail integers)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',12,0,'2008-08-23 08:20:56'),(10190,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EI second the blog about it technique...even Jeff said thatx27s a x3Ca href=x22http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/000021.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Emajor reason he blogs.x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, regarding the wiki idea, if you set one up at work, be sure to encourage your coworkers to do the same.  When someone finds something of interest they can just write a little x22articlex22 explaining what it is and how to do it... that way, not only are your own things easily available and quickly searchable, but youx27ll often find out things you never knew from other people in your group.  That way it benefits x3Cemx3Eeveryonex3C/emx3E not just you.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 15:48:29'),(10190,'tplumsteadj','x3CPx3EIf you are talking about MS SQL Server tables, I like the diagram support in SQL Server Management Studio. You just drag the tables from the explorer onto the canvas, and they are laid out for you along with lines for relationships. Youx27ll have to do some adjusting by hand for the best looking diagrams, but it is a decent way to get diagrams.x3C/Px3E',0,0,'2008-08-07 03:29:21'),(10580,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EIx27ve taken to hand-coding all of my DDL (creates/alter/delete) statements, adding them to my .sln as text files, and using normal versioning (using subversion, but any revision control should work). This way, I not only get the benefit of versioning, but updating live from dev/stage is the same process for code and database - tags, branches and so on work all the same.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOtherwise, I agree redgate is expensive if you donx27t have a company buying it for you. If you can get a company to buy it for you though, it really is worth it!x3C/px3E',17,0,'2008-08-03 03:51:09'),(10610,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/8656/C-Script-The-Missing-Puzzle-Piecex22x3EOleg Shilox27s C# Script solution (at The Code Projectx3C/ax3E) really is a great introduction to providing script abilities in your application.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA different approach would be to consider a language that is specifically built for scripting, such as x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IronRubyx22x3EIronRubyx3C/ax3E, x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IronPythonx22x3EIronPythonx3C/ax3E, or x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lua_%28programming_language%29x22x3ELuax3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIronPython and IronRuby are both available today.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor a guide to embedding IronPython read\nx3Ca href=x22http://blogs.msdn.com/b/jmstall/archive/2005/09/01/howto-embed-ironpython.aspxx22x3EHow to embed IronPython script support in your existing app in 10 easy stepsx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELua is a scripting language commonly used in games. There is a Lua compiler for .NET, available from CodePlex -- x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/Nuax22x3Ehttp://www.codeplex.com/Nuax3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat codebase is a great read if you want to learn about building a compiler in .NET.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA different angle altogether is to try x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_PowerShellx22x3EPowerShellx3C/ax3E. There are numerous examples of embedding PowerShell into an application -- herex27s a thorough project on the topic: \nx3Ca href=x22http://code.msdn.microsoft.com/PowerShellTunnel/Wiki/View.aspx?title=PowerShellTunnel%20Referencex22x3EPowershell Tunnelx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',28,0,'2008-08-02 05:49:46'),(10680,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3EThe problem with Silverlight, is that therex27s still a lot of people who donx27t have it installed.  Also, Ix22m not sure how well your existing .Net developers will be able to leverage their existing skills if they are only familiar with more traditional server-side .Net coding. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhat are your reasons for pushing Silverlight over Flex? If you have to ask the SOFlow community for reasons, it seems odd that you would be so willing to push it.x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-21 23:43:22'),(10810,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EMake sure to read x3Ca href=x22http://blogs.lessthandot.com/index.php/DataMgmt/DataDesign/only-in-a-database-can-you-get-1000-imprx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EOnly In A Database Can You Get 1000% + Improvement By Changing A Few Lines Of Codex3C/ax3E so that you are sure that the optimizer can utilize the index effectively when messing with datesx3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-22 19:21:21'),(10810,'prihak','x3CPx3EI like x3CA href=x22http://www.testdriven.net/overview.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETestDriven.NETx3C/Ax3E (even though I use ReSharper) and Ix27m pretty happy with x3CA href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/xunitx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EXUnit.netx3C/Ax3E. It uses Facts instead of Tests which many people dislike but I like the difference in terminology. Itx27s useful to think of a collection of automatically provable Facts about your software and see which ones you violate when you make a change.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EBe aware that x3CA href=x22http://blogs.msdn.com/buckh/archive/2007/03/27/orcas-unit-testing-to-be-available-in-visual-studio-professional.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVisual Studio 2008 Professional (and above) now comes with integrated Unit Testingx3C/Ax3E (it used to be available only with the Team System Editions) and may be suitable for your needs. x3C/Px3E',2,0,'2008-08-05 06:07:50'),(10810,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EAnother way of waiting for a thread to finish is using an x3Ccodex3EAutoResetEventx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprivate readonly AutoResetEvent mWaitForThread = new AutoResetEvent(false);\n\nprivate void Blah()\n{\n    ThreadStart tStart = new ThreadStart(MyMethod);\n    Thread t = new Thread(tStart);\n    t.Start();\n\n    //... (any other things)\n    mWaitForThread.WaitOne();\n}\n\nprivate void MyMethod()\n{\n     //... (execute any other action)\n     mWaitForThread.Set();\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 16:54:56'),(10810,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EIn theory, something like x3Ccodex3Eeval (x27function(){x27 + code + x27}()x27);x3C/codex3E could work (that syntax fails though).  Even if that did work, it would still be sort of ghetto to be calling an eval through a select x3Ccodex3Eonchangex3C/codex3E.  Another solution would be to somehow get Rails to inject the x3Ccodex3Eonsubmitx3C/codex3E code into the x3Ccodex3Eonchangex3C/codex3E field of the select tag, but Ix27m not sure if therex27s a way to do that.  ActionView has link_to_remote, but therex27s no obvious helper to generate the same code in the x3Ccodex3Eonchangex3C/codex3E field.x3C/px3E',-1,0,'2008-08-29 10:18:14'),(10860,'dperrenl','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect * from TABLE where field IN (1,2,3)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can also conveniently combine this with a subquery that only returns one field:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E    select * from TABLE where field IN (SELECT boom FROM anotherTable)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',7,0,'2008-08-20 16:59:58'),(10870,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EOh, one big hack I employed years ago, is that Windows wonx27t let you x3Cemx3Edeletex3C/emx3E files, but it does let you x3Cemx3Emovex3C/emx3E them.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPseudo-sort-of-code:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Emv %WINDIR%\\System32\\mfc42.dll %WINDIR\\System32\\mfc42.dll.old\nInstall new mfc42.dll\nTell user to save work and restart applications\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen the applications restarted (note we didnx27t need to reboot the machine), they loaded the new x3Ccodex3Emfc42.dllx3C/codex3E, and all was well. That, coupled with x3Ccodex3EPendingFileOperationsx3C/codex3E to delete the old one the next time the whole system restarted, worked pretty well.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-04 10:14:42'),(10870,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3ETherex27s a x3Ca href=x22http://shaver.off.net/diary/2008/05/25/fsyncers-and-curveballs/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethorough discussion of thisx3C/ax3E that explains all of the fsync related problems that affected pre-3.0 versions of FF.  In general, I have not seen the behaviour since then either, and really it shouldnx27t be a problem at all if your system isnx27t also doing IO intensive tasks.  Firebug/Venkman make for nice debuggers, but they would be painful for figuring out these kinds of problems for someone elsex27s code, IMO.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI also wish that there was an easy way to look at CPU utilization in Firefox by tab, though, as I often find myself with FF eating 100% CPU, but no clue which part is causing the problem.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 07:47:03'),(10880,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EDataGrid was an ASP.NET 1.1 control, still supported. GridView arrived in 2.0, made certain tasks simpler added different databinding features:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis link has a comparison of DataGrid and GridView features -x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/05yye6k9(v=vs.100).aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttps://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/05yye6k9(v=vs.100).aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',38,0,'2008-08-07 05:06:22'),(10990,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3Eselect * from TABLE where field in (1, 2, 3)x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 17:00:01'),(11060,'aillidges','x3Cpx3Eif youx27re a java progammer, check out the x3Ca href=x22http://struts.apache.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EStrutsx3C/ax3E framework by the Apache folks.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 22:48:20'),(11060,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EYes, the x3Cstrongx3EOpenGL Extension Wrangler Libraryx3C/strongx3E (GLEW) is a painless way to use OpenGL extensions on Windows. Herex27s how to get started on it:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIdentify the OpenGL extension and the extension APIs you wish to use. OpenGL extensions are listed in the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opengl.org/registry/x22x3EOpenGL Extension Registryx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECheck if your graphic card supports the extensions you wish to use. Download and install the latest drivers and SDKs for your graphics card.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERecent versions of x3Ca href=x22http://developer.nvidia.com/object/sdk_home.htmlx22x3ENVIDIA OpenGL SDKx3C/ax3E ship with GLEW. If youx27re using this, then you donx27t need to do some of the following steps.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDownload x3Ca href=x22http://glew.sourceforge.net/x22x3EGLEWx3C/ax3E and unzip it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdd the GLEW x3Cstrongx3Ebinx3C/strongx3E path to your Windows x3Cstrongx3EPATHx3C/strongx3E environment variable. Alternatively, you can also place the x3Cstrongx3Eglew32.dllx3C/strongx3E in a directory where Windows picks up its DLLs.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdd the GLEW x3Cstrongx3Eincludex3C/strongx3E path to your compilerx27s include directory list.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdd the GLEW x3Cstrongx3Elibx3C/strongx3E path to your compilerx27s library directory list.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EInstruct your compiler to use x3Cstrongx3Eglew32.libx3C/strongx3E during linking. If youx27re using Visual C++ compilers then one way to do this is by adding the following line to your code:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#pragma comment(lib, x22glew32.libx22)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdd a x3Ccodex3E#include x26lt;GL/glew.hx26gt;x3C/codex3E line to your code. Ensure that this is placed above the includes of other GL header files. (You may actually not need the GL header files includes if you include x3Ccodex3Eglew.hx3C/codex3E.)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EInitialize GLEW using x3Ccodex3EglewInit()x3C/codex3E after youx27ve initialized GLUT or GL. If it fails, then something is wrong with your setup.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eif (GLEW_OK != glewInit())\n{\n    // GLEW failed!\n    exit(1);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECheck if the extension(s) you wish to use are now available through GLEW. You do this by checking a boolean variable named x3Cstrongx3EGLEWx3Cemx3E_your_extension_namex3C/emx3Ex3C/strongx3E which is exposed by GLEW.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EExample:x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eif (!GLEW_EXT_framebuffer_object)\n{\n    exit(1);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThatx27s it! You can now use the OpenGL extension calls in your code just as if they existed naturally for Windows.x3C/px3E',29,0,'2008-08-20 07:19:50'),(11060,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EWe use x3Ca href=x22http://watin.sourceforge.net/x22x3EWatinx3C/ax3E at my place of employment, we are a .net shop so this solution made a lot of sense.  We actually started with Watir (the original ruby implementation) and switched after.  Itx27s been a pretty good solution for us so farx3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-21 22:46:18'),(11060,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EI pretty much only use x3Cstrongx3Ethisx3C/strongx3E when referencing a type property from inside the same type.  As another user mentioned, I also underscore local fields so they are noticeable without needing x3Cstrongx3Ethisx3C/strongx3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 23:29:51'),(11200,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EIx27ve seen plenty of people type their email address wrong and Ix27ve also looked through user databases full of invalid email address.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe way I see it youx27ve got two options.  Use a second box to confirm the input, or send an authentication/activation email.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EBoth are annoyances so you get to choose which you think will annoy your users less.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EMost would argue that having to find an email and click on a link is more annoying, but it avoids the copy/paste a bad address issue, and it allows you to do things like delete or roll back users if they donx27t activate after say 48 hours.x3C/px3E',15,0,'2008-08-07 20:36:19'),(11330,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EYou should use the interface only if you need it, e.g., if your list is casted to an IList implementation other than List. This is true when, for example, you use NHibernate, which casts ILists into an NHibernate bag object when retrieving data.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf List is the only implementation that you will ever use for a certain collection, feel free to declare it as a concrete List implementation.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 03:20:22'),(11430,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EShort of a formal mathematical proof (which I imagine would be difficult), the proof of the pudding is in the unit tests. You have to find a way to wrap the converted C# snippets, compile the and run them under a similar environment, then compare the output against the original. Unless youx27re rigorous in your testing, therex27s no way you can be confident of the result.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 14:44:32'),(11430,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EI work on windows mobile full time and have never really come across a good Windows Mobile scripting implementation unfortunately.  For some reason MS has never seen the need for it.  For example, even though you can actually get a command console on WM, it does not support running batch files, even though all the commands are still there and it would be relatively easy.  There is definitely not a VBScript engine Ix27ve ever heard of nor JScript.  There is x3Ca href=x22http://pythonce.sourceforge.net/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EPythonCEx3C/ax3E but the WM specific support is minimal and you donx27t get access to a lot of WM only things.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, Ix27ve done a lot of work with a company called x3Ca href=x22http://soti.net/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESOTIx3C/ax3E which has a product called MobiControl that does incorporate a basic scripting engine. Though most of the commands are specific to their system and actually have to be run from a desktop-side management console.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGiven all of the times I have tried to find a good scripting engine for WM myself you would think I wouldx27ve just written one ;)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo, sorry, but the basic answer is x3Cemx3Enox3C/emx3E, there is not a scripting engine available for VB in the context that you specified.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-26 22:53:07'),(11430,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3ESee, this is the problem with SO-- every answer so far has made a valid point and should be considered the final answer. Let me try to sum up:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25450/abstraction-away-from-css#25457x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECSS is goodx3C/ax3E! x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25450/abstraction-away-from-css#25462x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETo expand furtherx3C/ax3E, there is a learning curve but once you learn it many things will be much easier.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3E(Some) Browser inconsistencies x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25450/abstraction-away-from-css#25471x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eare solvablex3C/ax3E generically.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3E(Some of your) x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25450/abstraction-away-from-css#25467x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVariable and calculatedx3C/ax3E field functionality can be taken care of through whatever templating engine you use.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think a combination of all these certianly solves a large sum of problems (although to be fair deeply learning CSS is not an option for everyone; some people just donx27t use it enough to justify the time).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are some problems none of the above points cover (certain types of calculated fields would require writing a JS library for, me thinks) but itx27s certainly a good start.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-25 04:50:44'),(11430,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EYou can, but you will allways compare the document versions with Word itself.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI havenx27t heard a version control database which can track changes in Word documents.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever there are some tools which can compare Word documents, so if you set up your version control client to use these tools for comparison, you can have some fun.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 13:46:18'),(11500,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EThere are a few core concepts that I think are important to learn:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3ECheck-ins/check-outs (obviously)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ELocal versions vs. server versionsx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EMapping/Binding a local workspace to a remote store or repository.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EMerging your changes back into a file that contains changes from\nothers.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EBranching (what it is, when/why to use it)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EMerging changes from a branch back into a main branch or trunk.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMost modern source control systems require some knowledge of the above topics and should help facilitate you learning them. Then you have distributed source control, which I donx27t have any experience with but is supposed to be fairly complicated and may not be suitable for a beginner.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://subversion.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESubversionx3C/ax3E is great because it has all of the modern features youx27d want and is free.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://git-scm.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGitx3C/ax3E is also becoming an increasingly popular option and is another free or very low cost alternative to Subversion. Knowledge regarding the concepts of branching and merging become critical for using Git, however.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can use x3Ca href=x22http://unfuddle.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eunfuddlex3C/ax3E as a free and easy way to experiment with both Git and Subversion. I use it to host a couple of subversion repositories for some side projects Ix27ve worked on in the past.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-22 23:56:09'),(11680,'mbeckinsale1a','x3CPx3EI like to implement x3CA href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.componentmodel.idataerrorinfo.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EIDataErrorInfox3C/Ax3E and put my validation logic in its Error and this[columnName] properties. That way if you want to check programmatically whether therex27s an error you can simply test either of those properties in code, or you can hand the validation off to the data binding in Web Forms, Windows Forms or WPF. x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EWPFx27s x22ValidatesOnDataErrorx22 Binding property makes this particularly easy.x3C/Px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 02:24:01'),(11680,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EJust combine the two commands:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Escp -r web/* web/.htaccess user@site.com:site.com/\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you want 0 entries of your password you can set up x3Ca href=x22http://sial.org/howto/openssh/publickey-auth/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Epublic key authenticationx3C/ax3E for ssh/scp.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-29 05:47:21'),(11720,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EI think the crux of the reason that open source is a good idea is because you pool together a LARGE resource of people usually working for free to create something useful and exciting. A site like Digg is churning out more and better stories than the staff @ Slashdot could because the community drives it. So too, could an open source project get more done than a dedicated team IF you have a project exciting enough to draw in participation. Therex27s also many other benefits like improving your code and learning along the way.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 00:13:13'),(11740,'aa9279','x3Cpx3EI wound up using this. It is a kind of a hack, but it actually works pretty well. The only thing is you have to be very careful with your semicolons. : Dx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evar strSql:String = stream.readUTFBytes(stream.bytesAvailable);      \nvar i:Number = 0;\nvar strSqlSplit:Array = strSql.split(x22;x22);\nfor (i = 0; i x26lt; strSqlSplit.length; i++){\n    NonQuery(strSqlSplit[i].toString());\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',12,0,'2008-08-01 20:09:47'),(11820,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3ENot everything thatx27s important in a class is asserted easily in code. There can be semantics and relationships present that are easily broken by inheriting and overriding methods. Overriding one method at a time is an easy way to do this.  You design a class/object as a single meaningful entity and then someone comes along and thinks if a method or two were x27betterx27 it would do no harm.  That may or may not be true.  Maybe you can correctly separate all methods between private and not private or virtual and not virtual but that still may not be enough. Demanding inheritance of all classes also puts a huge additional burden on the original developer to foresee all the ways an inheriting class could screw things up.x3Cbr /x3E\nI donx27t know of a perfect solution. Ix27m sympathetic to preventing inheritance but thatx27s also a problem because it hinders unit testing. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-24 02:01:43'),(11820,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EIt depends.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EGenerally, code should fail fast. If the value can be set by multiple points in the code and you validate only on after retrieving the value, the bug appears to be in the code that does the update. If the setters validate the input, you know what code is trying to set invalid values.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 23:59:13'),(11930,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EThe most important contribution of making a product open source is that it instantly becomes more accessible for people. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt also helps people who are really interested in your work to see what you have done, make suggestions on improving it and even lend you a hand in doing so sometimes. In addition, you contribute something to the vast repository of open source software and help the community grow and learn in your own small way.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 00:19:25'),(11930,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EThere are some minor differences, but I think later editions of Kx26amp;R are for ANSI C, so therex27s no real difference anymore.x3Cbr /x3E\nx22C Classicx22 for lack of a better terms had a slightly different way of defining functions, i.e.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint f( p, q, r )  \nint p, float q, double r;  \n{  \n    // Code goes here  \n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI believe the other difference was function prototypes. Prototypes didnx27t have to - in fact they couldnx27t - take a list of arguments or types. In ANSI C they do.x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-22 18:35:12'),(11950,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EI use MSBuild completely for building.  Herex27s my generic MSBuild script that searches the tree for .csproj files and builds them:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;Project xmlns=x22http://schemas.microsoft.com/developer/msbuild/2003x22 DefaultTargets=x22Buildx22x26gt;\n  x26lt;UsingTask AssemblyFile=x22$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\\bin\\xUnit\\xunitext.runner.msbuild.dllx22 TaskName=x22XunitExt.Runner.MSBuild.xunitx22/x26gt;\n  x26lt;PropertyGroupx26gt;\n	x26lt;Configuration Condition=x22x27$(Configuration)x27==x27x27x22x26gt;Debugx26lt;/Configurationx26gt;\n    x26lt;DeployDirx26gt;$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\\Build\\$(Configuration)x26lt;/DeployDirx26gt;\n	x26lt;ProjectMaskx26gt;$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\\**\\*.csprojx26lt;/ProjectMaskx26gt;\n	x26lt;ProjectExcludeMaskx26gt;x26lt;/ProjectExcludeMaskx26gt;\n    x26lt;TestAssembliesIncludeMaskx26gt;$(DeployDir)\\*.Test.dllx26lt;/TestAssembliesIncludeMaskx26gt;\n  x26lt;/PropertyGroupx26gt;\n\n  x26lt;ItemGroupx26gt;\n    x26lt;ProjectFiles Include=x22$(ProjectMask)x22 Exclude=x22$(ProjectExcludeMask)x22/x26gt;\n  x26lt;/ItemGroupx26gt;\n\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22Buildx22 DependsOnTargets=x22__Compile;__Deploy;__Testx22/x26gt;\n\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22Cleanx22x26gt;\n    x26lt;MSBuild Projects=x22@(ProjectFiles)x22 Targets=x22Cleanx22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;RemoveDir Directories=x22$(DeployDir)x22/x26gt;\n  x26lt;/Targetx26gt;\n\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22Rebuildx22 DependsOnTargets=x22Clean;Buildx22/x26gt;\n\n  x26lt;!--\n  ===== Targets that are meant for use only by MSBuild =====\n  --x26gt;\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22__Compilex22x26gt;\n    x26lt;MSBuild Projects=x22@(ProjectFiles)x22 Targets=x22Buildx22x26gt;\n      x26lt;Output TaskParameter=x22TargetOutputsx22 ItemName=x22AssembliesBuiltx22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;/MSBuildx26gt;\n    x26lt;CreateItem Include=x22@(AssembliesBuilt -x26gt; x27%(RootDir)%(Directory)*x27)x22x26gt;\n      x26lt;Output TaskParameter=x22Includex22 ItemName=x22DeployFilesx22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;/CreateItemx26gt;\n  x26lt;/Targetx26gt;\n\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22__Deployx22x26gt;\n    x26lt;MakeDir Directories=x22$(DeployDir)x22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;Copy SourceFiles=x22@(DeployFiles)x22 DestinationFolder=x22$(DeployDir)x22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;CreateItem Include=x22$(TestAssembliesIncludeMask)x22x26gt;\n      x26lt;Output TaskParameter=x22Includex22 ItemName=x22TestAssembliesx22/x26gt;\n    x26lt;/CreateItemx26gt;\n  x26lt;/Targetx26gt;\n\n  x26lt;Target Name=x22__Testx22x26gt;\n    x26lt;xunit Assembly=x22@(TestAssemblies)x22/x26gt;\n  x26lt;/Targetx26gt;\nx26lt;/Projectx26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Sorry if itx27s a little dense.  Markdown seems to be stripping out the blank lines.)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s pretty simple though once you understand the concepts and all the dependencies are handled automatically.  I should note that we use Visual Studio project files, which have a lot of logic built into them, but this system allows people to build almost identically both within the Visual Studio IDE or at the command line and still gives you the flexibility of adding things to the canonical build like the xUnit testing you see in the script above.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe one PropertyGroup is where all the configuration happens and things can be customized, like excluding certain projects from the build or adding new test assembly masks.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe ItemGroup is where the logic happens that finds all the .csproj files in the tree.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen there are the targets, which most people familiar with make, nAnt or MSBuild should be able to follow.  If you call the Build target, it calls x3Cemx3E_Compile, _x3C/emx3EDeploy and __Test.  The Clean target calls MSBuild on all the project files for them to clean up their directories and then the global deployment directory is deleted.  Rebuild calls Clean and then Build.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-20 05:56:06'),(12290,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EYou need to create an extension method, which requires .NET 3.5. The method needs to be static, in a static class. The first parameter of the method needs to be prefixed with x22thisx22 in the signature.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic static string MyMethod(this string input)x3Cbrx3E{x3Cbrx3E    // do thingsx3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can then call it likex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex22asdfasx22.MyMethod();x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-07 16:03:42'),(12870,'aalandg','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThen comes the multiple browser issuex3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere is x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/ie7-js/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E that helps remove some inconsistencies from IE. You can also use jQuery to add some selectors via javascript.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI agree with x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/25450/abstraction-away-from-css#25462x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDanx3C/ax3E, learn it and itx27s not so much of a problem, even fun.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-25 03:57:20'),(12890,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EYou can use this program, x3Ca href=x22http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896655.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EHandlex3C/ax3E, to find which process has the lock on your file. Itx27s a command-line tool, so I guess you use the output from that... Ix27m not sure about finding it programmatically.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf deleting the file can wait, you could specify it for deletion when your computer next starts up:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EStart x3Ccodex3EREGEDT32 (W2K)x3C/codex3E or x3Ccodex3EREGEDIT (WXP)x3C/codex3E and navigate to:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EHKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\System\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\Session Manager\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EW2K and WXPx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EW2K:x3C/strongx3Ex3Cbr/x3EEditx3Cbr/x3EAdd Value...x3Cbr/x3EData Type: x3Ccodex3EREG_MULTI_SZx3C/codex3Ex3Cbr/x3EValue Name: x3Ccodex3EPendingFileRenameOperationsx3C/codex3Ex3Cbr/x3Ex3Ckbdx3EOKx3C/kbdx3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EWXP:x3C/strongx3Ex3Cbr/x3EEditx3Cbr/x3ENewx3Cbr/x3EMulti-String Valuex3Cbr/x3Ex3Ckbdx3Eenterx3C/kbdx3Ex3Cbr/x3E\nx3Ccodex3EPendingFileRenameOperationsx3C/codex3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EIn the Data area, enter x3Ccodex3Ex22\\??\\x22 + filenamex3C/codex3E to be deleted. LFNs may\nbe entered without being embedded in quotes. To delete x3Ccodex3EC:\\Long Directory Name\\Long File Name.exex3C/codex3E, enter the following data:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E\\??\\C:\\Long Directory Name\\Long File Name.exe\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen press x3Ckbdx3EOKx3C/kbdx3E.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EThe x22destination file namex22 is a null (zero) string. It is entered\nas follows:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EW2K:x3C/strongx3Ex3Cbr/x3EEditx3Cbr/x3EBinaryx3Cbr/x3Eselect Data Format: Hexx3Cbr/x3Eclick at the end of the hex stringx3Cbr/x3Eenter 0000 (four zeros)x3Cbr/x3Ex3Ckbdx3EOKx3C/kbdx3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EWXP:x3C/strongx3Ex3Cbr/x3ERight-click the valuex3Cbr/x3Echoose x22Modify Binary Datax22x3Cbr/x3Eclick at the end of the hex stringx3Cbr/x3Eenter 0000 (four zeros)x3Cbr/x3Ex3Ckbdx3EOKx3C/kbdx3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EClose x3Ccodex3EREGEDT32/REGEDITx3C/codex3E and reboot to delete the file.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Csupx3E(Shamelessly stolen from x3Ca href=x22http://www.pcreview.co.uk/forums/thread-1581158.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esome random forumx3C/ax3E, for posterityx27s sake.)x3C/supx3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 09:59:53'),(12890,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EOrder of operations in an expression, such as:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efoo * (bar + baz^2 / foo)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EBx3C/strongx3Erackets firstx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EOx3C/strongx3Erders (ie Powers and Square Roots, etc.)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EDx3C/strongx3Eivision and x3Cstrongx3EMx3C/strongx3Eultiplication (left-to-right)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EAx3C/strongx3Eddition and x3Cstrongx3ESx3C/strongx3Eubtraction (left-to-right)x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3Esource: x3Ca href=x22http://www.mathsisfun.com/operation-order-bodmas.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.mathsisfun.com/operation-order-bodmas.htmlx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-06 19:03:35'),(13000,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EIt has pretty extensive coverage up to .NET 4.0 and even include some features from .NET 4.5 APIs, but there are a few areas that we have chosen not to implement due to the APIs being deprecated, new alternatives being created or the scope being too large.   The following APIs are not available in Mono:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EWindows Presentation Foundationx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWindows Workflow Foundation (neither of the two versions)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EEntity Frameworkx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EThe WSE1/WSE2 x22add-onsx22 to the standard Web Services stackx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdditionally, our WCF implementation is limited to what Silverlight supported.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe easiest way to check for your specific project is to run the x3Ca href=x22http://www.mono-project.com/MoMAx22x3EMono Migration Analyzer (MoMA)x3C/ax3E. The benefit is that it will notify the Mono team of issues which will prevent you from using Mono (if any), which lets them prioritize their work.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI recently ran MoMA on SubSonic and found only one issue - a weird use of Nullable types. Thatx27s a big codebase, so the coverage there was pretty impressive.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMono is in active use in x3Ca href=x22http://www.mono-project.com/Softwarex22x3Eseveral commercial as well as open source productsx3C/ax3E. Itx27s in use in some large applications, such as x3Ca href=x22http://www.mono-project.com/Companies_Using_Monox22x3EWikipedia and the Mozilla Developer Centerx3C/ax3E, and has been used in embedded applications such as the Sansa MP3 players and powers thousands of published games.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAt the language level, x3Ca href=x22http://www.mono-project.com/Release_Notes_Mono_2.12x22x3Ethe Mono compiler is fully compliant with the C# 5.0 language specificationx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',65,0,'2008-08-20 22:21:49'),(13000,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EAHA! I knew there had to be a cleaner solution... the code I was working on was starting to look something like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpre class=x22lang-vb prettyprint-overridex22x3Ex3Ccodex3EOn Error Resume Next \nstrComputer = x22.x22\nSet objWMIService = GetObject(x22winmgmts:x22 _\n    x26amp; x22{impersonationLevel=impersonate}!\\\\x22 x26amp; strComputer x26amp; x22\\root\\cimv2x22)\nSet colProcessList = objWMIService.ExecQuery _\n    (x22Select * from Win32_Process Where Name = x27BackgroundProcess.exex27x22)\nFor Each objProcess in colProcessList\n    colProperties = objProcess.GetOwner(strNameOfUser,strUserDomain)\n    If strNameOfUser = x22SYSTEMx22 Then    \n        objProcess.Terminate()\n    End If\nNext\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 13:39:07'),(13060,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EWhile semi-related to your question, it does not entirely fit the Powershell NetCmdlets motif. But I wanted to post it anyhow as I use it daily and it may help others. Simply making shift-control-c key combo into displaying the visual studio command prompt. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-05 22:53:44'),(13060,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eclass Producer implements Runnable {\n   private final BlockingQueue queue;\n   Producer(BlockingQueue q) { queue = q; }\n   public void run() {\n     try {\n       while (true) { queue.put(produce()); }\n     } catch (InterruptedException ex) { ... handle ...}\n   }\n   Object produce() { ... }\n }\n\n class Consumer implements Runnable {\n   private final BlockingQueue queue;\n   Consumer(BlockingQueue q) { queue = q; }\n   public void run() {\n     try {\n       while (true) { consume(queue.take()); }\n     } catch (InterruptedException ex) { ... handle ...}\n   }\n   void consume(Object x) { ... }\n }\n\n class Setup {\n   void main() {\n     BlockingQueue q = new SomeQueueImplementation();\n     Producer p = new Producer(q);\n     Consumer c1 = new Consumer(q);\n     Consumer c2 = new Consumer(q);\n     new Thread(p).start();\n     new Thread(c1).start();\n     new Thread(c2).start();\n   }\n }\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis example was taken from the x3Ca href=x22http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/BlockingQueue.htmlx22x3EJDK 1.6 docs of x3Ccodex3EBlockingQueuex3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E. So You can see that you are doing it the right way. Herex27s the quote which tells you that it have to work:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EMemory consistency effects: As with\n  other concurrent collections, actions\n  in a thread prior to placing an object\n  into a BlockingQueue happen-before\n  actions subsequent to the access or\n  removal of that element from the\n  BlockingQueue in another thread.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 09:39:15'),(13200,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EThis problem has been studied in some detail. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are a set of very up-to-date implementations in the x3Ccodex3ETSpectrum*x3C/codex3E classes of x3CA href=x22http://root.cern.ch/x22x3EROOTx3C/Ax3E (a nuclear/particle physics analysis tool). The code works in one- to three-dimensional data.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe ROOT source code is available, so you can grab this implementation if you want.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFrom the x3CA href=x22http://root.cern.ch/root/html/TSpectrum.htmlx22x3ETSpectrumx3C/Ax3E class documentation:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe algorithms used in this class have been published in the following references:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3E[1] M.Morhac et al.: Background\n  elimination methods for\n  multidimensional coincidence gamma-ray\n  spectra. Nuclear Instruments and\n  Methods in Physics Research A 401\n  (1997) 113-\n  132.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3E[2]  M.Morhac et al.: Efficient one- and two-dimensional Gold\n  deconvolution and its application to\n  gamma-ray spectra decomposition.\n  Nuclear Instruments and Methods in\n  Physics Research A 401 (1997) 385-408.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3E[3]  M.Morhac et al.: Identification of peaks in\n  multidimensional coincidence gamma-ray\n  spectra. Nuclear Instruments and\n  Methods in Research Physics A \n  443(2000), 108-125.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe papers are linked from the class documentation for those of you who donx27t have a NIM online subscription.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Chr /x3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe short version of what is done is that the histogram flattened to eliminate noise, and then local maxima are detected by brute force in the flattened histogram. x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 18:28:23'),(13430,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EYou can get the address that connects to your ServerSocket using http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/net/NetworkInterface.html#getInetAddresses()x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever if your client is connecting via a NAT, then you will get the address of the router and NOT the Ethernet address. If it is on your local network (via a hub/switch, no router with NAT) the it wil work as intended.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-29 08:48:45'),(13470,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EIx27d do something like the following:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EDim unformatedtext As String\n\nsomeRTFtext = Replace(someRTFtext, x22\\ulx22, x22[ul]x22)\nsomeRTFtext = Replace(someRTFtext, x22\\bx22, x22[b]x22)\nsomeRTFtext = Replace(someRTFtext, x22\\ix22, x22[i]x22)\n\nDim RTFConvert As RichTextBox = New RichTextBox\nRTFConvert.Rtf = someRTFtext\nunformatedtext = RTFConvert.Text\n\nunformatedtext = Replace(unformatedtext, x22[ul]x22, x22\\ulx22)\nunformatedtext = Replace(unformatedtext, x22[b]x22, x22\\bx22)\nunformatedtext = Replace(unformatedtext, x22[i]x22, x22\\ix22)\n\nClipboard.SetText(unformatedtext)\n\noWord.ActiveDocument.ActiveWindow.Selection.PasteAndFormat(0)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-21 22:22:48'),(13470,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EI send them to my gmail account, that way I have them where ever I go, and they can be put into appropriate folders for later.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 15:36:45'),(13540,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI know a few of the developers on the Carleton University developed x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/blindside/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBlindside Projectx3C/ax3E.  They are actively developing an open-source web conferencing and presentation tool for e-learning, with the intent of eventually offering university courses online.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s pretty fully featured software, and is meant to be installed as a server that can host many conference rooms at a time.  It has voice, video, text, and a whiteboard/slideshow (x3Cstrongx3EEdit:x3C/strongx3E supports PDF at the moment) capability.  One feature I think it neat is that students can x27raise their handsx27 in the class to ask the instructor a question, where they can take the floor for a moment.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECheck out the demo on the site (if itx27s not working anymore Ix27ll nudge the developers).  Another pro is that the clients only need to have flash installed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrikex3Ex3Cemx3EI just logged onto the online demo and created this preview:x3C/emx3Ex3C/strikex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis project is now called BigBlueButton : x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://code.google.com/p/bigbluebutton/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHere is the demo: x3Ca href=x22http://demo.bigbluebutton.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://demo.bigbluebutton.org/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 02:29:43'),(13550,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EIx27m not sure if this would be handled exactly the same way for webstart, but we ran into this situation in a desktop application when dealing with a set of native libraries (dlls in our case).x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ELoading libA before libB should work, unless one of those libraries has a dependency that is unaccounted for and not in the path. My understanding is that once it gets to a system loadLibrary call (i.e. Java has found the library in its java.library.path and is now telling the OS to load it) - it is completely dependent on the operating system to find any dependent libraries, because at that point it is the operating system that is loading the library for the process, and the OS only knows how to look in the system path. That seems hard to set in the case of a Webstart app, but there is a way around this that does not involve static compiling. You may be able to shuffle where your libraries are - I am unsure x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you use a custom classloader, you can override loadLibrary and findLibrary so that it can locate your libraries from within a jar in your classpath, and if you also make it aware of your native library dependencies (i.e. libB depends on libA depends on libX, then when loading libB you can catch yourself and ensure you load libA first, and in checking that notice and load libX first. Then the OS doesnx27t try to find a library that isnx27t in your path. Itx27s klunky and a bit painful, but ensuring Java finds them and loads them all in the correct order can work.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-07 21:53:38'),(13550,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EVault from SourceGear.com is superb. It is free for single users and provides a superb VS 2005/2008 interface. I love it!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Erp x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-24 01:00:05'),(14040,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EEDIT: Perhaps add a x22dvcsx22, x22distrubutedversioncontrolx22, x22distrubutedx22x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve used Mercurial on Windows with no problems. You can use TortoiseHG or just use the command line. Mercurial does require Python, but that is easy to install in Windows as well.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.selenic.com/mercurial/wiki/index.cgi/BinaryPackages#head-adac70dc1664bb9eac334d5c8b57483d300254f3x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMercurial Binary Packagesx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 17:05:01'),(14040,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EThere are a few ambiguities in your question. What operation needs to be successful?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor everything you want to know about drag and drop, browse through these search results (multiple pages worth):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/search?q=drag+drop+site%3Ablogs.msdn.com%2Foldnewthingx26amp;rls=com.microsoft:en-usx26amp;ie=UTF-8x26amp;oe=UTF-8x26amp;startIndex=x26amp;startPage=1x22 rel=x22nofo