a href=x22http://git.or.cz/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGitx3C/ax3E. Therex27s a Google Talk x3Ca href=x22http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4XpnKHJAok8x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eexplaining all about itx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-05 05:32:34'),(14310,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EI too have always heard having an auto-incrementing int is good for performance even if you donx27t actually use it.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 07:00:36'),(14330,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EMan pages contain the information you want. To read what you have above:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprintf( x22%10.2fx22, 1.5 )\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis will print:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E         1.50\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhereas:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprintf(x22%.2fx22, 1.5 )\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPrints:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E1.50\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENote the justification of both.\nSimilarly:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprintf(x22%10.1fx22, 1.5 )\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWould print:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E        1.5\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAny number after the . is the precision you want printed. Any number before the . is the distance from the left margin.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 17:51:59'),(14330,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EI will have to agree with Greg: make up an attribute for it. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd if youx27re really serious, maybe find a way to figure out if the constructor is being accessed by anything other than XMLSerializer and throw an exception if it is.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:32:44'),(14350,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EHerex27s a snippet from Jasonx27s link. Its the same as Philx27s method but uses rhino. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3ENote: mockHttpContext.Request is stubbed to return mockRequest x3Cstrongx3Ebeforex3C/strongx3E mockRequestx27s internals are stubbed out. I believe this order is required.x3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E// create a fake web context\nvar mockHttpContext = MockRepository.GenerateMockx26lt;HttpContextBasex26gt;();\nvar mockRequest = MockRepository.GenerateMockx26lt;HttpRequestBasex26gt;();\nmockHttpContext.Stub(x =x26gt; x.Request).Return(mockRequest);\n\n// tell the mock to return x22GETx22 when HttpMethod is called\nmockRequest.Stub(x =x26gt; x.HttpMethod).Return(x22GETx22);            \n\nvar controller = new AccountController();\n\n// assign the fake context\nvar context = new ControllerContext(mockHttpContext, \n                  new RouteData(), \n                  controller);\ncontroller.ControllerContext = context;\n\n// act\n...\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',16,0,'2008-08-29 05:53:09'),(14350,'prihak','x3Cpx3EI tend to use it everywhere as well, just to make sure that it is clear that it is instance members that we are dealing with.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-22 23:31:26'),(14370,'wscreen1b','x3CPx3EYou could use any of the DLR languages, which provide a way to really easily host your own scripting platform. However, you donx27t have to use a scripting language for this. You could use C# and compile it with the C# code provider. As long as you load it in its own AppDomain, you can load and unload it to your heartx27s content.x3C/Px3E',5,0,'2008-08-02 10:16:23'),(14530,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EI canx27t believe all of the people that say using it always is a x22best practicex22 and such.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUse x22thisx22 when there is ambiguity, as in x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/a/23264/282110x22x3ECoreyx27s examplex3C/ax3E or when you need to pass the object as a parameter, as in x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/a/23267/282110x22x3ERyanx27s examplex3C/ax3E. There is no reason to use it otherwise because being able to resolve a variable based on the scope chain should be clear enough that qualifying variables with it should be unnecessary.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: The C# documentation on x22thisx22 indicates one more use, besides the two I mentioned, for the x22thisx22 keyword - x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dk1507sz%28VS.71%29.aspxx22x3Efor declaring indexersx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: @Juan: Huh, I donx27t see any inconsistency in my statements - there are 3 instances when I would use the x22thisx22 keyword (as documented in the C# documentation), and those are times when you actually x3Cemx3Eneedx3C/emx3E it. Sticking x22thisx22 in front of variables in a constructor when there is no shadowing going on is simply a waste of keystrokes and a waste of my time when reading it, it provides no benefit.x3C/px3E',34,0,'2008-08-22 23:46:46'),(14570,'aauger2','x3CPx3EOP asked about diagramming views and view dependencies, SQL Management Studio and Enterprise Manager doesnx27t allow you to diagram views. I canx27t vouch for the other tools.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EThe LINQ to SQL designer for Visual Studio does allow you to drop views on the design surface but there isnx27t a easy way to model the dependencies between the views. Ix27m not sure which tool has this type of diagramming functionality. You could take a look at Red Gatex27s SQLDoc tool but it just provides text based output.x3C/Px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 04:08:31'),(14570,'itrowla','x3Cpx3EIf you have to use Railx27s built-in Javascript generation, I would use Orionx27s solution, but with one small alteration to compensate for the return code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eeval (x27(function(){x27 + code + x27})()x27);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, in my opinion youx27d have an easier time in the long run by separating out the Javascript code into an external file or separate callable functions.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-29 09:21:02'),(14570,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EUsing the 3.5 compiler you can use an Extension Method:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic static void Trim(this string s)x3Cbrx3E{x3Cbrx3E  // implementationx3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can use this on a CLR 2.0 targeted project (3.5 compiler) by including this hack:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Enamespace System.Runtime.CompilerServicesx3Cbrx3E{x3Cbrx3E  [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Method | AttributeTargets.Class | AttributeTargets.Assembly)]x3Cbrx3E  public sealed class ExtensionAttribute : Attributex3Cbrx3E  {x3Cbrx3E  }x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-07 16:04:14'),(14760,'clawrence3','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EI think the use of opaque context objects (HANDLEs in Win32, FILE*s in C, to name two well-known examples--hell, HANDLEs live on the other side of the kernel-mode barrier, and it really doesnx27t get much more encapsulated than that) is found in procedural code too; Ix27m struggling to see how this is something particular to OOP.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3EHANDLEx3C/codex3Es (and the rest of the WinAPI) x3Cemx3Eisx3C/emx3E OOP! C doesnx27t support OOP very well so therex27s no special syntax but that doesnx27t mean it doesnx27t use the same concepts. WinAPI is in every sense of the word an object-oriented framework.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESee, this is the trouble with every single discussion involving OOP or alternative techniques: nobody is clear about the definition, everyone is talking about something else and thus no consensus can be reached. Seems like a waste of time to me.x3C/px3E',21,0,'2008-08-23 20:05:08'),(14760,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EIt is possible to skip the step of creating the empty database. You can create the new database as part of the restore process.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThis is actually the easiest and best way I know of to clone a database. You can eliminate errors by scripting the backup and restore process rather than running it through the SQL Server Management Studiox3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are two other options you could explore:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Colx3E\n\nx3Clix3EDetach the database, copy the .mdf file and re-attach.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EUse SQL Server Integration Services (SSIS) to copy all the objects overx3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/olx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI suggest sticking with backup and restore and automating if necessary.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-05 01:46:01'),(15040,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EGo to x3Ca href=x22http://www.fogbugz.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.fogbugz.com/x3C/ax3E then at the bottom under x22Try Itx22, sign up.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Eunder Settings =x26gt; Your FogBugz Hosted Account, it should either already say x22Payment Information:    Using Student and Startup Edition.x22 or there should be some option/link to turn on the Student and Startup Edition.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd yes, itx27s not only for Students and Startups, I asked their support :-)x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EDisclaimer: Ix27m not affiliated with FogCreek and Joel did not just deposit money in my account.x3C/px3E',18,0,'2008-08-06 19:46:49'),(15190,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3ETake a look at x3Ca href=x22http://hudson-ci.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EHudsonx3C/ax3E. Itx27s highly customizable, and, IMHO, easier than CruiseControl.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-27 16:15:44'),(15240,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3E@CodingTheWheelx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EBut to the extent that OOP has been a waste of time, Ix27d say itx27s because of lack of programmer training, compounded by the steep learning curve of learning a language specific OOP mapping. Some people x22getx22 OOP and others never will.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI dunno if thatx27s really surprising, though.  I think that technically sound approaches (LSP being the obvious thing) make x3Cemx3Ehard to usex3C/emx3E, but if we donx27t use such approaches it makes the code brittle and inextensible anyway (because we can no longer reason about it).  And I think the counterintuitive results that OOP leads us to makes it unsurprising that people donx27t pick it up.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMore significantly, since software is already fundamentally too hard for normal humans to write reliably and accurately, should we really be extolling a technique that is consistently taught poorly and appears hard to learn? If the benefits were clear-cut then it might be worth persevering in spite of the difficulty, but that doesnx27t seem to be the case.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 19:06:40'),(15240,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EYou didnx27t mention for what OS, but the x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?familyid=013BB284-3946-44A9-AC3C-BF2A569EAA72x26amp;displaylang=enx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Microsoft Download Centerx22x3EWMI Redistributable Components version 1.0x3C/ax3E definitely exists.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EFor Windows Server 2003, the WMI SDK and redistributables are part of the x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=484269E2-3B89-47E3-8EB7-1F2BE6D7123Ax26amp;displaylang=enx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Windows Server 2003 SDK Full Downloadx22x3EServer SDKx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3EI believex3C/emx3E that the same is true for the x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=F26B1AA4-741A-433A-9BE5-FA919850BDBFx26amp;displaylang=enx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Microsoft Download Centerx22x3EServer 2008 SDKx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 22:44:55'),(15240,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EFor my projects I alternate between SQL Compare from REd Gate and the Database Publishing Wizard from Microsoft which you can download free\n\nx3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?familyid=56E5B1C5-BF17-42E0-A410-371A838E570Ax26amp;displaylang=enx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe Wizard isnx27t as slick as SQL Compare or SQL Data Compare but it does the trick. One issue is that the scripts it generates may need some rearranging and/or editing to flow in one shot.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOn the up side, it can move your schema and data which isnx27t bad for a free tool.x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-03 03:40:04'),(15310,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EStoring a hash is a good idea. However, please definitely read Jeffx27s x3Ca href=x22http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/000953.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EYoux27re Probably Storing Passwords Incorrectlyx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 14:41:15'),(15390,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3ERegarding timezones, yet one more reason to store all dates in a single timezone (preferably UTC). Anyway, I think the answers using datediff, datepart and the different built-in date functions are your best bet.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 19:31:35'),(15390,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EGoogle Analytics is quick to set up and provides more sexy graphs than you can shake a stick at.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/analytics/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/analytics/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.google.com/analytics/x3C/ax3Ex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 18:26:37'),(15470,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EUse a non-standard name and id for the fields, so rather than x22namex22 have x22name_x22. Browsers will then not see it as being the name field. The best part about it is that you can do this to some but not all fields and it will autocomplete some but not all fields.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-05 20:27:39'),(15690,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EYou can always use a template engine to add variables and caclulated fields to your CSS files.x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-25 03:49:58'),(15690,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EIn situations I usually come across, I rarely use IList directly.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUsually I just use it as an argument to a method  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evoid ProcessArrayData(IList almostAnyTypeOfArray)\n{\n    // Do some stuff with the IList array\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis will allow me to do generic processing on almost any array in the .NET framework, unless it uses IEnumerable and not IList, which happens sometimes.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt really comes down to the kind of functionality you need. Ix27d suggest using the List class in most cases. IList is best for when you need to make a custom array that could have some very specific rules that youx27d like to encapsulate within a collection so you donx27t repeat yourself, but still want .NET to recognize it as a list.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 03:17:46'),(15700,'prihak','x3Cpx3EI personally would say Email w/ Verification, OpenId is a great idea but I find that finding a provider that your already with is a pain, I only had an openId for here cause just 2 days before beta i decided to start a blog on blogspot. But everyone on the internet has en email address, especially when dealing with businesses, people arenx27t very opt to using there personal blog or whatnot for a business login.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 19:46:36'),(15900,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EC:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: Actually C++ I guess, because of the variable declaration in the for loop.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E int factorial(int x) {\n      int product = 1;\n\n      for (int i = x; i x26gt; 0; i--) {\n           product *= i;\n      }\n\n      return product;\n }\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 07:50:32'),(15900,'mlowried','x3CPx3EFrom SQL Server Books Online:x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CBLOCKQUOTEx3E\n\nx3CPx3ETo write full-text queries in Microsoft SQL Server 2005, you must learn how to use the CONTAINS and FREETEXT Transact-SQL predicates, and the CONTAINSTABLE and FREETEXTTABLE rowset-valued functions.x3C/Px3Ex3C/BLOCKQUOTEx3E\n\nx3CPx3EThat means all of the queries written above with the % and _ are not valid full text queries.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EHere is a sample of what a query looks like when calling the CONTAINSTABLE function.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CBLOCKQUOTEx3E\n\nx3CPx3ESELECT RANK , * FROM TableName , CONTAINSTABLE (TableName, x3CEMx3E, x27 x22x3C/EMx3EWildCardx22 x27) searchTable WHERE [KEY] = TableName.pk ORDER BY searchTable.RANK DESCx3C/Px3Ex3C/BLOCKQUOTEx3E\n\nx3CPx3EIn order for the CONTAINSTABLE function to know that Ix27m using a wildcard search, I have to wrap it in double quotes. I can use the wildcard character * at the beginning or ending. There are a lot of other things you can do when youx27re building the search string for the CONTAINSTABLE function. You can search for a word near another word, search for inflectional words (drive = drives, drove, driving, and driven), and search for synonym of another word (metal can have synonyms such as aluminum and steel).x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EI just created a table, put a full text index on the table and did a couple of test searches and didnx27t have a problem, so wildcard searching works as intended.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3E[Update]x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EI see that youx27ve updated your question and know that you need to use one of the functions.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EYou can still search with the wildcard at the beginning, but if the word is not a full word following the wildcard, you have to add another wildcard at the end.x3C/Px3EExample:  x22*ildcarx22 will look for a single word as long as it ends with x22ildcarx22.x3CBRx3Ex3CBRx3EExample:  x22*ildcar*x22 will look for a single word with x22ildcarx22 in the middle, which means it will match x22wildcardx22.  [Just noticed that Markdown removed the wildcard characters from the beginning and ending of my quoted string here.]x3CBRx3E\n\nx3CPx3E[Update #2]x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EDave Ward - Using a wildcard with one of the functions shouldnx27t be a huge perf hit. If I created a search string with just x22*x22, it will not return all rows, in my test case, it returned 0 records.x3C/Px3E',3,0,'2008-08-06 19:08:11'),(15900,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3ETry adding the repository first using the x22SVN Repository Exploringx22 perspective (Window x3E Open Perspective x3E Other... x3E SVN Repository Exploring).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMake sure that the URL you are using points to the correct directory, which typically contains these default repository files:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Econf/  dav/  db/  format  hooks/  locks/  README.txt\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope this helps.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-29 10:51:48'),(16100,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EIx27ve been using forms authentication and creating the necessary GenericIdentity and CustomPrincipal objects that allows me to leverage the User.IsInRole type functions you typically only get with Windows authentication.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat way in my web.config file, I can do stuff like...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;location path=x22Login.aspxx22x26gt;\n   x26lt;system.webx26gt;\n      x26lt;authorizationx26gt;\n         x26lt;allow users =x22*x22 /x26gt;\n      x26lt;/authorizationx26gt;\n   x26lt;/system.webx26gt;\nx26lt;/locationx26gt;\n\nx26lt;location path=x22ManagementFolderx22x26gt;\n   x26lt;system.webx26gt;\n      x26lt;authorizationx26gt;\n         x26lt;allow roles =x22Administrator, Managerx22 /x26gt;\n      x26lt;/authorizationx26gt;\n   x26lt;/system.webx26gt;\nx26lt;/locationx26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 22:09:05'),(16100,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EIt depends on what browser you use, but Internet Explorer, for example, would take you to the root directory of your harddrive (eg. C:/), while browsers such as Firefox does nothing. x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 01:46:13'),(16110,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EWith VS2008 you can do this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Edevenv solution.sln /build configuration\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',28,0,'2008-08-29 10:38:23'),(16110,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EWhen it comes to full-text searching, for my money nothing beats x3Ca href=x22http://lucene.apache.orgx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELucenex3C/ax3E.  There is a x3Ca href=x22http://incubator.apache.org/projects/lucene.net.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E.Net port availablex3C/ax3E that is compatible with indexes created with the Java version.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ETherex27s a little work involved in that you have to create/maintain the indexes, but the search speed is fantastic and you can create all sorts of interesting queries.  Even indexing speed is pretty good - we just completely rebuild our indexes once a day and donx27t worry about updating them.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAs an example, x3Ca href=x22http://www.wateronline.com/Search.mvc?keyword=wastewaterx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethis search functionalityx3C/ax3E is powered by Lucene.Net.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 19:34:28'),(16110,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EThe term here is x3Cstrongx3Etranslation unitx3C/strongx3E and you really want to (if possible) have one class per translation unit ie, one class implementation per .cpp file, with a corresponding .h file of the same name.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s usually more efficient (from a compile/link) standpoint to do things this way, especially if youx27re doing things like incremental link and so forth. The idea being, translation units are isolated such that, when one translation unit changes, you donx27t have to rebuild a lot of stuff, as you would have to if you started lumping many abstractions into a single translation unit.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso youx27ll find many errors/diagnostics are reported via file name (x22Error in Myclass.cpp, line 22x22) and it helps if therex27s a one-to-one correspondence between files and classes. (Or I suppose you could call it a 2 to 1 correspondence).x3C/px3E',46,0,'2008-08-26 18:34:39'),(16320,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EBenefits to your company are few. All of the reasons others have given assume a degree of popularity that is... unlikely. Most business folks are going to realize that without needing to think very hard about it so they arenx27t going to find advertising or leverage or public scrutiny or tool improvement enough of a reason to take the x22riskx22 of releasing it as open source.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said, herex27s the best counter to the x22riskx22 argument for a company to release an internal tool as Open Source: if it isnx27t part of your core competency and care is taken so that it doesnx27t suck company resources (or expose company secrets/infrastructure), there really is no risk. The company loses nothing and gains a x3Cemx3Epotentialx3C/emx3E for gainx26mdash;even if that potential is small.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-21 02:42:02'),(16320,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3Ethis will remove time component from a date for you:  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect dateadd(d, datediff(d, 0, current_timestamp), 0)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 19:06:59'),(16330,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EIx27ve used it in several applications and have never had nor heard of threading being anything other than 100% reliable, as long as you know its limits.  You canx27t spawn 1000 threads at the same time and expect your program to run properly on Windows, however you can easily write a worker pool and just feed it 1000 operations, and keep everything nice and under control.x3C/px3E',-2,0,'2008-08-29 09:50:47'),(16340,'aauger2','x3Cpx3ENever. Ever. If you have variable shadowing, your naming conventions are on crack. I mean, really, no distinguishing naming for member variables? x3Cemx3EFacepalmx3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E',-6,0,'2008-08-22 23:53:31'),(16340,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EThe two most commonly used licenses that allow what you want are the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/bsd-license.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBSD Licensex3C/ax3E and \nx3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMIT Licensex3C/ax3E. (see also the full x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licensesx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Elist of licensesx3C/ax3E considered Open Source by the OSI).x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-26 20:33:30'),(16460,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI tried version 1, and it was unreliable to say the least. I canx27t say anything about 2.0.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you can afford it, the one I use, x3Ca href=x22http://www.visualsvn.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVisualSVNx3C/ax3E, is very good and uses TortoiseSVN for all its gui, except for the specialized things related to its VS integration.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 18:01:24'),(16610,'hschade12','x3Cpx3E10.1f means floating point with 10 characters  wide with 1 place after the decimal point.\nIf the number has less than 10 digits, itx27s padded with spaces.\n10.2f is the same, but with 2 places after the decimal point.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou have these basic types:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E%d   - integer\n%x   - hex integer\n%s   - string\n%c   - char (only one)\n%f   - floating point (float)\n%d   - signed int (decimal)\n%i   - signed int (integer) (same as decimal).\n%u   - unsigned int\n%ld  - long (signed) int\n%lu  - long unsigned int\n%lld - long long (signed) int\n%llu - long long unsigned int\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: there are several others listed in @Elix27s response (man 3 printf).x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 17:53:08'),(16860,'clawrence3','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhere\nyear(date1) = year(date2)\nand month(date1) = month(date2)\nand day(date1) = day(date2)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-22 18:56:16'),(16860,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3ERails is still ahead of the competitors as a complete stack with large community driving it forward.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 23:09:40'),(16860,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EIf you use x3Ca href=x22http://winmerge.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWinMergex3C/ax3E it has added support for merging Word and Excel binary files.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 15:44:32'),(16940,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EThe point is that LINQ integrates your queries into your primary programming language, allowing your IDE to provide you with some facilities (Intellisense and debug support, for example) that you otherwise would not have, and to allow the compiler to type-check your SQL code (which is impossible with a normal string query).x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 01:56:11'),(16940,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EYou might want to look at x3Ca href=x22http://blog.objectmentor.com/articles/2008/03/06/tdd-on-three-index-cardsx22x3ETDD on Three Index Cardsx3C/ax3E and x3Ca href=x22http://blog.briandicroce.com/2008/03/14/three-index-cards-to-easily-remember-the-essence-of-test-driven-development/x22x3EThree Index Cards to Easily Remember the Essence of Test-Driven Developmentx3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECard #1. Uncle Bob’s Three Lawsx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EWrite no production code except to pass a failing test.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWrite only enough of a test to demonstrate a failure.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWrite only enough production code to pass the test.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECard #2: FIRST Principlesx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EFast: Mind-numbingly fast, as in hundreds or thousands per second.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EIsolated: The test isolates a fault clearly.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ERepeatable: I can run it repeatedly and it will pass or fail the same way each time.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ESelf-verifying: The Test is unambiguously pass-fail.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETimely: Produced in lockstep with tiny code changes.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECard #3: Core of TDDx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3ERed: test failsx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EGreen: test passesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ERefactor: clean code and testsx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',11,0,'2008-08-20 02:28:56'),(16970,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EHow about writing a cursor to loop through the contents, attempting the cast for each entry?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen an error occurs, output the primary key or other identifying details for the problem record.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI canx27t think of a set-based way to do this.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEditx3C/strongx3E - ah yes, I forgot about ISDATE(). Definitely a better approach than using a cursor. +1 to SQLMenace.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 18:24:18'),(17020,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3Esounds like a case where you could use the x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy_patternx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Estrategy patternx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-05 12:37:19'),(17140,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EIx27m partway to my solution with this entry on MSDN (donx27t know how I couldnx27t find it before).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUser/Machine Hivex3Cbrx3E\nSubkeys and values entered under this hive will be installed under the HKEY_CURRENT_USER hive when a user chooses x22Just Mex22 or the HKEY_USERS hive or when a user chooses x22Everyonex22 during installation.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/x6kd89c5%28VS.80%29.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERegistry Editorx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-04 00:45:27'),(17140,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EI have been using Struts from Jakarta (Apache group) for java, and itx27s really good. Good separation of the layers, which allows you use any othe library/framework in any layer, for example Hibernate for object-relational mapping or even any template framework like Velocity in the view layer.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI recommend you give a look at their x3Ca href=x22http://struts.apache.org/2.0.11.2/index.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ewebsitex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 23:06:00'),(17170,'osilley7','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EPublicity:x3C/strongx3E You could exemplify with the x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_on_Railsx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERuby on Railsx3C/ax3E framework. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt was created to do the x3Ca href=x22http://www.37signals.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E37signalsx3C/ax3E web apps. They open sourced it, then someone came along and build twitter. Imagine the publicity they had from that!x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 00:14:17'),(17250,'mheyward10','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E% Matches any number of charactersx3Cbrx3E_ Matches a single characterx3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve never used Full-Text indexing but you can accomplish rather complex and fast search queries with simply using the build in T-SQL string functions.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 18:00:57'),(17250,'rdowdellz','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://getfirebug.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EFirebugx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 01:16:54'),(17430,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EYou should always use it, I use it to diferantiate private fields and parameters (because our naming conventions state that we donx27t use prefixes for member and parameter names (and they are based on information found on the internet, so I consider that a best practice))x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 23:23:34'),(17500,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EWell, one of the reaons why classes usually contain private members with public getters/setters is exactly because they can verify data.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you have a Number than can be between 1 and 100, i would definitely put something in the setter that validates that and then maybe throw an exception that is being caught by the code. The reason is simple: If you donx27t do it in the setter, you have to remember that 1 to 100 limitation every time you set it, which leads to duplicated code or when you forget it, it leads to an invalid state.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for performance, ix27m with Knuth here:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3Ex22We should forget about small efficiencies, say about 97% of the time: premature optimization is the root of all evil.x22x3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E',12,0,'2008-08-05 23:59:39'),(17840,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3ETherex27s also a C++ library CAS called x3Ca href=x22http://www.ginac.de/x22x3EGiNaCx3C/ax3E.  This isnx27t exactly what you were looking for but itx27s certainly very programmable.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-29 03:52:16'),(17840,'prihak','x3Cpx3EStart with the basics before you get to the higher level stuff like web services (though that is important too). The most important things you need to learn, as a project manager, are the things youx27re going to be questioning your underlings about later. For example, my PM (also a PHP guy) has absolutely no knowledge of garbage collection and its implications, which makes it incredibly difficult for me to explain to him why our .NET Windows service appears to be taking 80MB of RAM.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERemember, you are not the one who needs to know everything. You should be issuing overarching directives, and let the people with the expertise sort out the details. That said, study up on the technicals a bit so that they can communicate effectively with you.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit (8/24/08):You should know something about the underlying technicals; not necessarily all .NET stuff either (garbage collection, .config files, pipes and services if youx27re running services adjacent to your projectx27s main focus, stuff like that). Higher-reaching concepts would probably include WPF (maybe Silverlight as well), LINQ (or your ORM of choice), as well as the Vista bridge and related bridging code if your project includes desktop apps at all. Those three things seem to be the focus for this round of .NET. Something else thatx27s very important to have at least a passing knowledge of is the ways that .NET code can/must interoperate with native code: P/Invoke, Runtime Callable Wrapping and COM Callable Wrapping. There are still a lot of native things that donx27t have a .NET equivalent.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for resources, Ix27d highly recommend MSDN Magazine. They tend to preview upcoming technologies and tools well before average developers will ever see them.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 18:23:40'),(17880,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EThe closest thing to a scripting environment on Windows Mobile is the Configuration Service Provider interface.  While it is not a scripting language x3Cemx3Eper sex3C/emx3E, it does allow one to do a lot of the same type of things such as modify registry settings, copy and delete files and directories, install and uninstall applications and much more.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMike Calligaro has x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/magazine/cc500581.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ea great articlex3C/ax3E on how to write scripts and how to get them from your desktop onto the device in various ways.  One of them is certain to work for you.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 23:36:21'),(17880,'prihak','x3Cpx3EThe problem is most likely how the data is stored, there are only two safe formatsx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EISO YYYYMMDDx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EISO 8601 yyyy-mm-dd Thh:mm:ss:mmm(no spaces)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ethese will work no matter what your language is.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou might need to do a SET DATEFORMAT YMD (or whatever the data is stored as) to make it workx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:20:01'),(17980,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EGx27day,x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI assume that youx27ve done your bind using INADDR_ANY to specify the address.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf this is the case, then the semantics of INADDR_ANY is such that a UDP socket is created on the port specified on all of your interfaces. The socket is going to get all packets sent to all interfaces on the port specified.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen sending using this socket, the lowest numbered interface is used. The outgoing senderx27s address field is set to the IP address of that first outgoing interface used.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFirst outgoing interface is defined as the sequence when you do an ifconfig -a. It will probably be eth0.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHTH.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Echeers,\nRobx3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-27 15:28:46'),(17980,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EIx27ve had to do this before. The only real way to do it is to manually match up the various locations. Use your databasex27s console interface and grouping select statements. First, add your x22Company Namex22 field. Then:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT count(*) AS repcount, x22Location Namex22 FROM mytablex3Cbrx3E WHERE x22Company Namex22 IS NULLx3Cbrx3E GROUP BY x22Location Namex22x3Cbrx3E ORDER BY repcount DESCx3Cbrx3E LIMIT 5;x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EFigure out what company the location at the top of the list belongs to and then update your company name field with an UPDATE ... WHERE x22Location Namex22 = x22The Locationx22 statement.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EP.S. - You should really break your company names and location names out into separate tables and refer to them by their primary keys.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EUpdate: - Wow - no duplicates? How many records do you have?x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 20:40:43'),(17980,'sspindlerw','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EI found this gem on Wikipedia. Sounds intimidating.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s actually not.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETelnet onto an IRC Server and witness the simplicity of the protocol first hand. The hardest part is the handshake, after that its very simple.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-23 19:59:07'),(18010,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EHerex27s when I use it:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EAccessing Private Methods from within the class (to differentiate)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EPassing the current object to another method (or as a sender object, in case of an event)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWhen creating extension methods :Dx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI donx27t use this for Private fields because I prefix private field variable names with an underscore (_). x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 01:19:47'),(18010,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EThe wildcard character in SQL Server is the x3Ccodex3E%x3C/codex3E sign and it works just fine, leading, trailing or otherwise.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said, if youx27re going to be doing any kind of serious full text searching then Ix27d consider utilising the Full Text Index capabilities. Using x3Ccodex3E%x3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3E_x3C/codex3E wild cards will cause your database to take a serious performance hit.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-06 17:57:28'),(18010,'dperrenl','x3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EAnother vote for notepad++x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EFirebug or the dev toolbar in IEx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ELifehackers Texter (for text expansion)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EI couldnx27t live my life on a computer without humanizedx27s x3Ca href=x22http://www.humanized.com/enso/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EEnsox3C/ax3E productx3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:25:07'),(18010,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EAs far as I know, and Ix27m definately not a hacker, you are completely fine. Really, if someone wanted to, they could exploit your code anyway clientside, but i donx27t see how they could exploit your server side code using javascript (unless you use server side javascript)x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-21 21:03:22'),(18080,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EI have found the solution else where:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT SUBSTRING(master.dbo.fn_varbintohexstr(HashBytes(x27MD5x27, x27HelloWorldx27)), 3, 32) x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',118,0,'2008-08-05 18:26:41'),(18460,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EThe x22classx22 that youx27ve constructed above is what most people would use a x3Cemx3Estructx3C/emx3E for in other languages. Ix27m not sure what the performance implications are in PHP, though I suspect instantiating the objects is probably more costly here, if only by a little bit.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat being said, if the cost is relatively low, it IS a bit easier to manage the objects, in my opinion.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m only saying the following based on the title and your question, but:\nBear in mind that classes provide the advantage of methods and access control, as well. So if you wanted to ensure that people werenx27t changing weights to negative numbers, you could make the x3Ccodex3Eweightx3C/codex3E field private and provide some accessor methods, like x3Ccodex3EgetWeight()x3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3EsetWeight()x3C/codex3E. Inside x3Ccodex3EsetWeight()x3C/codex3E, you could do some value checking, like so:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic function setWeight($weight)\n{\n    if($weight x26gt;= 0)\n    {\n        $this-x26gt;weight = $weight;\n    }\n    else\n    {\n        // Handle this scenario however you like\n    }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',9,0,'2008-08-23 14:52:51'),(18460,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EYou do not need domain admin rights to x3Cemx3Elookx3C/emx3E at the active directory. By default, any (authenticated?) user can read the information that you need from the directory.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf that wasnx27t the case, for example, a computer (which has an associated account as well) could not verify the account and password of its user.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou only need admin rights to x3Cemx3Echangex3C/emx3E the contents of the directory.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think it is possible to set more restricted permissions, but thatx27s not likely the case.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 03:03:51'),(18700,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EDatabase connections are a limited resource.  Some DBs have a very low connection limit, and wasting connections is a major problem.  By consuming many connections, you may be blocking others for using the database.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdditionally, throwing a ton of extra connections at the DB doesnx27t help anything unless there are resources on the DB server sitting idle.  If youx27ve got 8 cores and only one is being used to satisfy a query, then sure, making another connection might help.  More likely, though, you are already using all the available cores.  Youx27re also likely hitting the same harddrive for every DB request, and adding additional lock contention.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf your DB has anything resembling high utilization, adding extra connections wonx27t help.  Thatx27d be like spawning extra threads in an application with the blind hope that the extra concurrency will make processing faster.  It x3Cemx3Emightx3C/emx3E in some certain circumstances, but in other cases itx27ll just slow you down as you thrash the hard drive, waste time task-switching, and introduce synchronization overhead.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-26 21:03:06'),(18700,'mschafflere','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EWHERE field IN (1, 2, 3)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 17:00:01'),(18700,'scurraghy','x3CPx3EYou can not do this programatically (in a safe way that is) without creating a new table. x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EWhat Enterprise Manager does when you commit a reordering is to create a new table, move the data and then delete the old table and rename the new table to the existing name. x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIf you want your columns in a particular order/grouping without altering their physical order, you can create a view which can be whatever you desire.x3C/Px3E',51,0,'2008-08-05 01:54:18'),(18920,'achancelier6','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3ESchemex3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHere is a simple recursive definition:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E(define (factorial x)\n  (if (= x 0) 1\n      (* x (factorial (- x 1)))))\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn Scheme tail-recursive functions use constant stack space. Here is a version of factorial that is tail-recursive:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E(define factorial\n  (letrec ((fact (lambda (x accum)\n                   (if (= x 0) accum\n                       (fact (- x 1) (* accum x))))))\n    (lambda (x)\n      (fact x 1))))\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',7,0,'2008-08-23 08:25:31'),(18920,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EI would assume that it is because your requests are not being sent asynchronously, since your requests are done iteratively on the server, blocking each time, you have to pay for the overhead of creating a connection each time, when you only have to do it once...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn Flex, all web service calls are automatically called asynchronously, so you it is common to see multiple connections, or queued up requests on the same connection.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAsynchronous requests mitigate the connection cost through faster request / response time...because you cannot x3Cemx3Eeasilyx3C/emx3E achieve this in PHP without out some threading, then the performance hit is greater then simply reusing the same connection. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ethatx27s my 2 cents...x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 20:58:22'),(19030,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EThe biggest single difference, I think, is function prototyping and the syntax for describing the types of function arguments.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 18:31:19'),(19030,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EFor Python stuff, a good text editor (TextMate on OS X, [g]vim on Linux, Programmers Notepad on Windows), VCS (Ix27m mainly using git currently).. Thatx27s about it..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA bit of a stretch to call it a dev-tool, but searching Google for x22python [module name]x22 is incredibly useful (I use it even though I can put the cursor over the x3Ccodex3Eimport abcx3C/codex3E module and be taken to the pydoc page, I always found the first-google-result much better than the PyDoc page TextMate invokes..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI use PyLint to check Ix27ve not done anything stupid, but Ix27d hardly consider it x27must havex27 (I mostly use it for keeping consistent white-spacing, after commands and around x3Ccodex3Ex = 123x3C/codex3E statements and so on). Ix27m also considering learning pdb (python debugger), but Ix27ve always found the odd print statement, or the logging module (in larger scripts) more than adequate.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E..thatx27s about it.. Text editor, VCS, module documentation.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 07:51:24'),(19280,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EFirefox 30 ignores x3Ccodex3Eautocomplete=x22offx22x3C/codex3E for passwords, opting to prompt the user instead whether the password should be stored on the client. Note the following x3Ca href=x22https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=956906#c100x22x3Ecommentaryx3C/ax3E from May 5, 2014:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Culx3E\n  x3Clix3EThe password manager x3Cemx3Ealwaysx3C/emx3E prompts if it wants to save a password. Passwords are not saved without permission from the user.x3C/lix3E\n  x3Clix3EWe are the third browser to implement this change, after IE and Chrome.x3C/lix3E\n  x3C/ulx3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAccording to x3Ca href=x22https://developer.mozilla.org/en/How_to_Turn_Off_Form_Autocompletionx22x3EMozilla developer documentationx3C/ax3E the form element attribute x3Ccodex3Eautocompletex3C/codex3E prevents form data from being cached in older browsers.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;input type=x22textx22 name=x22foox22 autocomplete=x22offx22 /x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1637,0,'2008-08-05 20:24:53'),(19280,'wscreen1b','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cblockquotex3E\n    x3Cpx3EItx27s the speed that I am thinking of mostly, for anything more complex than what I have here Ix27d probably go with classes but the question is, what is the cost of a class?x3C/px3E\n  x3C/blockquotex3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis would seem to be premature optimisation. Your application isnx27t going to take any real-world performance hit either way, but using a class lets you use getter and setter methods and is generally going to be better for code encapsulation and code reuse. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWith the arrays youx27re incurring cost in harder to read and maintain code, you canx27t unit test the code as easily and with a good class structure other developers should find it easier to understand if they need to take it on.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd when later on you need to add other methods to manipulate these, you wonx27t have an architecture to extend.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 15:10:43'),(19790,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EHerex27s a dynamic sql script Ix27ve used in the past.  It can be further modified but it will give you the basics.  I prefer scripting it to avoid the mistakes you can make using the Management Studio:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex3Cbrx3EDeclare @OldDB varchar(100)x3Cbrx3EDeclare @NewDB varchar(100)x3Cbrx3EDeclare @vchBackupPath varchar(255)x3Cbrx3EDeclare @query varchar(8000)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3E/*Test code to implement x3Cbrx3ESelect @OldDB = x27Pubsx27x3Cbrx3ESelect @NewDB = x27Pubs2x27x3Cbrx3ESelect @vchBackupPath = x27\\\\dbserver\\C$\\Program Files\\Microsoft SQL Server\\MSSQL.1\\MSSQL\\Backup\\pubs.bakx27x3Cbrx3E*/x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3ESET NOCOUNT ON;x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3ESelect @query = x27Create Database x27 + @NewDBx3Cbrx3Eexec(@query)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3ESelect @query = x27x3Cbrx3EDeclare @vBAKPath varchar(256)x3Cbrx3Edeclare @oldMDFName varchar(100)x3Cbrx3Edeclare @oldLDFName varchar(100)x3Cbrx3Edeclare @newMDFPath varchar(100)x3Cbrx3Edeclare @newLDFPath varchar(100)x3Cbrx3Edeclare @restQuery varchar(800)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Eselect @vBAKPath = x27x27x27 + @vchBackupPath + x27x27x27x3Cbrx3Eselect @oldLDFName = name from x27 + @OldDB +x27.dbo.sysfiles where filename like x27x27%.ldf%x27x27x3Cbrx3Eselect @oldMDFName = name from  x27 + @OldDB +x27.dbo.sysfiles where filename like x27x27%.mdf%x27x27x3Cbrx3Eselect @newMDFPath = physical_name from x27 + @NewDB +x27.sys.database_files where type_desc = x27x27ROWSx27x27x3Cbrx3Eselect @newLDFPath = physical_name from x27 + @NewDB +x27.sys.database_files where type_desc = x27x27LOGx27x27x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Eselect @restQuery = x27x27RESTORE DATABASE x27 + @NewDB + x3Cbrx3Ex27 FROM DISK = Nx27x27 + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + @vBAKpath + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + x3Cbrx3Ex27x27 WITH MOVE Nx27x27 + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + @oldMDFName + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 +  x3Cbrx3Ex27x27 TO Nx27x27 + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + @newMDFPath + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 +  x3Cbrx3Ex27x27, MOVE Nx27x27 + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + @oldLDFName + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 +  x3Cbrx3Ex27x27 TO Nx27x27 + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 + @newLDFPath + x27x27x27x27x27x27x27x27 +  x3Cbrx3Ex27x27, NOUNLOAD, REPLACE, STATS = 10x27x27x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Eexec(@restQuery)x3Cbrx3E--print @restQueryx27x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Eexec(@query)x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-05 02:18:05'),(19970,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3E@Eric: No you wonx27t miss anything. If you want to see what happened at 11pm EST, you look for things that happened at the corresponding time in GMT. If all the records are converted into GMT before saving, it shouldnx27t matter. So long as you convert the requested time (i.e. 11pm) to GMT before using it in the query.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 20:37:59'),(19970,'mschafflere','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;form name=x22form1x22 id=x22form1x22 method=x22postx22 \n      autocomplete=x22offx22 action=x22http://www.example.com/form.cgix22x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis will work in IE and FF, the downside is that it is not XHTML standard.x3C/px3E',77,0,'2008-08-05 20:27:40'),(20040,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/18080/best-traffic-performance-usage-monitoring-module#18098x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E@Ianx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELooks like theyx27ve raised the limit. Not very surprising, it is google after all ;)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThis free version is limited to 5 million pageviews a month - however, users with an active Google AdWords account are given unlimited pageview tracking.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/support/googleanalytics/bin/answer.py?hl=enx26amp;answer=55543x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.google.com/support/googleanalytics/bin/answer.py?hl=enx26amp;answer=55543x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 19:39:34'),(20040,'osilley7','x3Cpx3E@jjnguyx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EAnother user may want to re-use your code by sub-classing your class. I donx27t see a reason to stop this.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf they want to use the functionality of my class they can achieve that with containment, and they will have much less brittle code as a result.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EComposition seems to be often overlooked; all too often people want to jump on the inheritance bandwagon. They should not! Substitutability is difficult. Default to composition; youx27ll thank me in the long run.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 01:45:11'),(20450,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EYou should probably write some automated tests for each condition you can think of, and then just start brainstorming more, writing the tests as you think of them.  This way, you can see for sure it will work, and will continue to work if you make further changes.  Look up Test Driven Development if you like the results.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-08 00:57:40'),(20510,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EUnfortunaly the x3Ca href=x22http://www.magicsoftware.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMagicx3C/ax3E tool doesnx27t generates code and also it canx27t implement a design pattern. I donx27t have control over the code cause as i stated before it doesnx27t have code to modify. Te bottom line is that it can speed up productivity in some way but it has the impossibility to user CVS, patterns also and I canx27t control all the details.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI agree with gary when he says x22it seems that the productivity aspect of such CASE tools is heavily dependent on customer requirements and developer skill sets/training/backgroundx22 but also I canx27t agree more with Klelky; x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EThose main disadvantages are:\n1. We cannot do automatic merges, making it close to impossible for parallel development on one component.\n2.Developers get dependant on the tool and x27forgetx27 how to handcode.x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThanksx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 17:25:53'),(20840,'aillidges','x3Cpx3ERead the code of other (good) javascript apps and see how they handle things.  But I start out with a file per class.  But once its ready for production, I would combine the files into one large file and minify.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe only reason, I would not combine the files, is if I didnx27t need all the files on all the pages.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-25 00:32:26'),(20840,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3ELike Rob Allen, I use SQL Compare / Data Compare by Redgate. I also use the Database publishing wizard by Microsoft. I also have a console app I wrote in C# that takes a sql script and runs it on a server. This way you can run large scripts with x27GOx27 commands in it from a command line or in a batch script.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI use Microsoft.SqlServer.BatchParser.dll and Microsoft.SqlServer.ConnectionInfo.dll libraries in the console application.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-04 22:00:50'),(20910,'dmatuszinski15','x3CPx3ECommunity Server itself has been very solid for me, but if all you need is a blogging engine then it may be overkill. Skinning it, for example, is quite a bit of work (despite their quite powerful Chameleon theme engine).x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIx27d probably look closer at one of the dedicated blog engines out there, like BlogEngine.NET, dasBlog or SubText, if thatx27s all you need. Go with Community Server if you think youx27ll want more x22community-focusedx22 features like forums etc.x3C/Px3E',7,0,'2008-08-08 03:13:21'),(20910,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EThis elaborates on my previous answer.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen I first started using CSS I also thought it was a pain that it didnx27t support variables, expressions, etc.  But as I started to use it more and more, I developed a different style to overcome these issues.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor example, instead of this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ea { color: red }\n.entry { color: red }\nh1 { color: red }\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can do:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ea, .entry, h1 { color: red }\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can keep the color declared in one spot by doing this.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOnce you use CSS enough you should be able to overcome most browser inconsistencies easily.  If you find that you need to use a CSS hack there is probably a better way to do it.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-25 05:17:19'),(20910,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EThe best solution for this is usually to provide the shared area on some form of SAN, which will be accessible from all servers and contain failover.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis also has the benefit that you donx27t have to provide sticky load balancing, the upload can be handled by one server, and the edit by another.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 19:04:40'),(21060,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EAnything, but I would learn a modern system like git or subversion myself. My first VCS was RCS, but I got the basics down.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:50:14'),(21280,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3EI think the way to do(get around) this problem is to develop a x22./configure x26amp;x26amp; makex22 script that your client uses to install, specify and compile the binaries. That would offcourse require that the client has all the source-code installed on his server or you can make it available on an NFS share.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 16:34:20'),(21460,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EIf you are compiling Apache2 for a particular location but want your clients to be able to install it somewhere else (and Ix27m assuming they have the same architecture and OS as your build machine) then you can do it but the apachectl script will need some after-market hacking.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI just tested these steps:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EUnpacked the Apache2 source (this should work with Apache 1.3 as well though) and ran x3Cemx3E./configure --prefix=/opt/apache2x3C/emx3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ERan x3Cemx3Emakex3C/emx3E then x3Cemx3Esudo make installx3C/emx3E to install on the build machine.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ESwitch to the install directory (/opt/apache2) and tar and gzip up the binaries and config files. I used x3Cemx3Ecd /opt/apache2; sudo tar cf - apache2 | gzip -c x3E ~/apache2.tar.gzx3C/emx3Ex3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EMove the tar file to the target machine. I decided to install in x3Cemx3E/opt/mynewdir/dan/apache2x3C/emx3E to test. So basically, your clients canx27t use rpm or anything like that -- unless you know how to make that relocatable (I donx27t :-) ).x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EAnyway, your clientx27s x3Cemx3Econf/httpd.confx3C/emx3E file will be full of hard-coded absolute paths -- they can just change these to whatever they need. The x3Cemx3Eapachectlx3C/emx3E script also has hard coded paths. Itx27s just a shell script so you can hack it or give them a x3Cemx3Esedx3C/emx3E script to convert the old paths from your build machine to the new path on your clients.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EI skipped all that hackery and just ran x3Cemx3E./bin/httpd -f /opt/mynewdir/dan/conf/httpd.confx3C/emx3E :-)x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope that helps. Let us know any error messages you get if itx27s not working for you.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 16:31:09'),(21560,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EThis is my general approach to testing/launching.\nHow you test/launch depends mostly on:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EWhat your application x3Cstrongx3Eisx3C/strongx3E.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWho your users x3Cstrongx3Earex3C/strongx3E.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you application is a technical application and is geared to the technically-minded, the word x22betax22 wonx27t really scare them - but provide an opportunity to test the product before it goes x27livex27, and help to improve the system.  This is the ideal circumstance in which to use either an open or closed beta.  Itx27s usually beneficial to start off x27closedx27 with a group of people you select and trust to bug-find quickly and reliably - after youx27re more confident that all the critical bugs are gone, open it up with an invite system (for example).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf, however, your application is x27trivialx27 from a technical standpoint (i.e. itx27s something like Twitter, or Facebook, or Flickr - nothing that is inherently geared towards technical usage), then youx27re going to have to be more careful in how you plan your testing.  Closed testing is most definitely your first port of call, and this should last for longer than a closed beta on a more x27technicalx27 product.  The reason?  Your x27average Joex27 doesnx27t necessarily know what the word x22betax22 means, and others may well be scared by it, or judge your service prematurely (not understanding the concept of this x27public testingx27 phase).  Many wonx27t want to be used as guinea pigs.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 15:04:47'),(21560,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EYou could do that, but if that files are binary you should always put a lock on it before editing. You wonx27t get a conflict (which would be unresolvable).x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-27 13:46:06'),(21830,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EIf you are using Hibernate, take a look at x3Ca href=x22http://www.jboss.org/envers/x22x3EJBoss Enversx3C/ax3E. From the project homepage:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThe Envers project aims to enable easy versioning of persistent JPA classes. All that you have to do is annotate your persistent class or some of its properties, that you want to version, with @Versioned. For each versioned entity, a table will be created, which will hold the history of changes made to the entity. You can then retrieve and query historical data without much effort. x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis is somewhat similar to x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/23770/good-strategy-for-leaving-an-audit-trailchange-history-for-db-applications#23780x22x3EEricx27s approachx3C/ax3E, but probably much less effort. Donx27t know, what language/technology you use to access the database, though.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-23 05:28:23'),(21870,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3ESee this x3Ca href=x22http://aspguy.wordpress.com/2008/07/09/reducing-the-page-size-by-storing-viewstate-on-server/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eblog postx3C/ax3E where the author describes a method for overriding the default behavior for generating the ViewState and instead shows how to save it on the server Session object.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3EIn ASP.NET 2.0, ViewState is saved by\n\n  a descendant of PageStatePersister\n\n  class. This class is an abstract class\n\n  for saving and loading ViewsState and\n\n  there are two implemented descendants\n\n  of this class in .Net Framework, named\n\n  HiddenFieldPageStatePersister and\n\n  SessionPageStatePersister. By default\n\n  HiddenFieldPageStatePersister is used\n\n  to save/load ViewState information,\n\n  but we can easily get the\n\n  SessionPageStatePersister to work and\n\n  save ViewState in Session object.x3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAlthough I did not test his code, it seems to show exactly what you want: a way to gain access to ViewState code while still on the server, before postback. x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 13:04:17'),(22000,'prihak','x3Cpx3EI think the more important question is: What areas of specialization are you most interested in?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOnce you know, begin learning in that area!x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 06:14:12'),(22000,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3ELike everyone else above says, youx27re stuck with OK/Cancel using x3Ccodex3Econfirm()x3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would like to recommend this x3Ca href=x22http://jquery.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EjQueryx3C/ax3E plugin though: x3Ca href=x22http://dev.iceburg.net/jquery/jqModal/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EjqModalx3C/ax3E. Ix27ve used it on 3 recent projects and it has worked great for each one. Specifically check out this example:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3E6). FUN! Overrides -- a. view (alert), b. view (confirm) It is now time to\n  show a real-world use for jqModal --\n  overriding the standard alert() and\n  confirm dialogs! Note; due to the\n  single threaded nature of javascript,\n  the confirm() function must be passed\n  a callback -- it does NOT return\n  true/false.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 07:48:47'),(22140,'idevey11','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EHow about writing a cursor to loop through the contents, attempting the cast for each entry?When an error occurs, output the primary key or other identifying details for the problem record.\n  I canx27t think of a set-based way to do this.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENot totally setbased but if only 3 rows out of 1 million are bad it will save you a lot of timex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect * into BadDates\nfrom Yourtable\nwhere isdate(lastUpdate) = 0\n\nselect * into GoodDates\nfrom Yourtable\nwhere isdate(lastUpdate) = 1\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ethen just look at the BadDates table and fix thatx3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 18:32:14'),(22140,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EIx27d suggest you to use the #error directive.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother pretty unknown attribute that might do the work is the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.diagnostics.conditionalattribute.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Econditional attributex3C/ax3E (depending on what youx27re trying to ahieve)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E[Conditional(x22CONDITIONx22)] \npublic static void MiMethod(int a, string msg)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewhich will remove the method invocation from the IL code itself if x22MY_CONDITIONx22 is defined.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:46:13'),(22500,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI always had stability issues with AnkhSVN. I couldnx27t switch everyone to Subversion where I work without an integrated solution.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThank goodness for x3Ca href=x22http://www.visualsvn.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVisualSVNx3C/ax3E + x3Ca href=x22http://tortoisesvn.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETortoiseSVNx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EVisualSVN isnx27t free, but it is cheap, and works a treat. x3C/px3E',12,0,'2008-08-20 18:04:34'),(22500,'sdally1','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EPython:x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERecursivex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Edef fact(x): \n    return (1 if x==0 else x * fact(x-1))\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUsing iteratorx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eimport operator\n\ndef fact(x):\n    return reduce(operator.mul, xrange(1, x+1))\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 19:31:41'),(22590,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://java.sun.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/net/NetworkInterface.html#getHardwareAddress%28%29x22x3E java.net.NetworkInterface.getHardwareAddressx3C/ax3E (method added in Java 6)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt has to be called on the machine you are interested in - the MAC is not transferred across network boundaries (i.e. LAN and WAN). If you want to make use of it on a website server to interrogate the clients, youx27d have to run an applet that would report the result back to you.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor Java 5 and older I found code x3Ca href=x22http://forums.sun.com/thread.jspa?messageID=3424868#4204392x22x3Eparsing output of command line tools on various systemsx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',15,0,'2008-08-29 08:48:46'),(22590,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3ENot that I know of. This has been a plague of Windows versions for quite some time.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 00:27:05'),(22880,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EThe primary key serves three purposes:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3Eindicates that the column(s) should be uniquex3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3Eindicates that the column(s) should be non-nullx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3Edocument the intent that this is the unique identifier of the rowx3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe first two can be specified in lots of ways, as you have already done.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe third reason is good:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3Efor humans, so they can easily see your intentx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3Efor the computer, so a program that might compare or otherwise process your table can query the database for the tablex27s primary key.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EA primary key doesnx27t have to be an auto-incrementing number field, so I would say that itx27s a good idea to specify your guid column as the primary key.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-08 07:04:55'),(22880,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EYou donx27t test the converter, you test the final code. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf the code doesnx27t compile, clearly your converter is failing. If the code compiles and your functionality tests fail, then you can tweak the code so that it passes the test. If you are fairly successful you should see that you only need to fix the modules that actually fail.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGoodluck!x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 09:21:20'),(22880,'mlowried','x3CPx3EAs always, Google is your friend:x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Ex3CA href=x22http://nixbit.com/cat/programming/libraries/c-generic-library/x22x3Ehttp://nixbit.com/cat/programming/libraries/c-generic-library/x3C/Ax3Ex3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Especifically:x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Ex3CA href=x22http://nixbit.com/cat/programming/libraries/generic-data-structures-library/x22x3Ehttp://nixbit.com/cat/programming/libraries/generic-data-structures-library/x3C/Ax3Ex3C/Px3E',11,0,'2008-08-05 20:43:11'),(22880,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EOOP isnx27t about creating re-usable classes, its about creating Usable classes.x3C/px3E',45,0,'2008-08-23 22:04:49'),(22980,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EStack/queue in JS is a simple array, which can be manipulated with x3Ccodex3E.push(val)x3C/codex3E, x3Ccodex3E.pop()x3C/codex3E, x3Ccodex3E.shift(val)x3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3E.unshift()x3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 20:16:07'),(23190,'nivakhnov17','x3Ch1x3EPerl 6: Functionalx3C/h1x3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Emulti factorial ( Int $n where { $n x26lt;= 0 } ){\n  return 1;\n}\nmulti factorial ( Int $n ){\n   return $n * factorial( $n-1 );\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E\nThis will also work:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Emulti factorial(0) { 1 }\nmulti factorial(Int $n) { $n * factorial($n - 1) }\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3ECheck x3Ca href=x22http://use.perl.org/~JonathanWorthington/journal/39196?from=StackOverflowx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EJonathan Worthingtonx27sx3C/ax3E journal on x3Ca href=x22http://use.perl.orgx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Euse.perl.orgx3C/ax3E, for more information about the last example.x3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 07:47:32'),(23190,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EI tried AnkhSVN (1.0.3, just 4 months ago), and it did not work the way I wanted it to (i.e. needed to select things in the browser window instead of based on active file). I ended up making some macros that utilize TortoiseSVN that work much more like what I expected.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve been very happy with using TortoiseSVN via explorer and my macros inside the IDE.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 18:10:33'),(23310,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EA Primary Key neednx27t be an autoincrementing field, in many cases this just means you are complicating your table structure.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EInstead, a Primary Key should be the minimum collection of attributes (note that most DBMS will allow a composite primary key) that uniquely identifies a tuple.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn technical terms, it should be the field that every other field in the tuple is fully functionally dependent upon.  (If it isnx27t you might need to normalise).x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn practice, performance issues may mean that you merge tables, and use an incrementing field, but I seem to recall something about premature optimisation being evil...x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 10:25:50'),(23370,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EAre you required to have it run as x86? I had similar issues with web apps under Visual Studiox27s dev web server (which is x86), but switching over to IIS (x64) worked for me. Since I was deploying to IIS x64, I called it a day at that point.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI tried tracing with Filemon and Regmon, but didnx27t get any denied or missing keys errors. If I were to look again, Ix27d check HKLM\\Software\\WOW6432Node, guessing that the installer writes to the x64 HKLM\\Software node, but not the x86 one.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 15:21:12'),(23490,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EI think that it sounds like this could be done using x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms141026.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESSIS packagesx3C/ax3E. Theyx27re similar to SQL 2000x27s DTS packages. Ix27ve used them to successfully transform everything from plain text CSV files, from existing SQL tables, and even from XLS files with 6-digit rows spanned across multiple worksheets. You could use C# to transform the data into an importable format (CSV, XLS, etc), then have your SQL server run a scheduled SSIS job to import the data.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s pretty easy to create an SSIS package, therex27s a wizard built-into SQL Serverx27s Enterprise Manager tool (labeled x22Import Datax22 I think), and at the end of the wizard it gives you the option of saving it as an SSIS package. Therex27s a bunch more info x3Ca href=x22http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sqlserver/bb671392.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eon Technetx3C/ax3E as well.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 19:40:00'),(23490,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EFrom x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa259216(SQL.80).aspxx22x3EMSDNx3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EWhen this option is set, it is possible to read uncommitted or dirty data; values in the data can be changed and rows can appear or disappear in the data set before the end of the transaction. x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESimply put, when you are using this isolation level, and you are performing multiple queries on an active table as part of one transaction, there is no guarantee that the information returned to you within different parts of the transaction will remain the same. You could query the same data twice within one transaction and get different results (this might happen in the case where a different user was updating the same data in the midst of your transaction). This can obviously have severe ramifications for parts of your application that rely on data integrity.x3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-21 23:28:31'),(23490,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EEnsure you donx27t use incremting integers for session IDs.  Much better to use a GUID, or some other long randomly generated character string.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 22:10:25'),(23610,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EIx27m not really sure how applicable to programming the old BODMAS mnemonic is anyways.  There is no guarantee on order of operations between languages, and while many keep the standard operations in that order, not all do.  And then there are some languages where order of operations isnx27t really all that meaningful (Lisp dialects, for example).  In a way, youx27re probably better off for programming if you forget the standard order and either use parentheses for everything(eg (a*b) + c) or specifically learn the order for each language you work in.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 19:12:30'),(23610,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EI created a base x22pagex22 class that handles that sort of thing. All my pages can then be decorated with the RequiresLogin attribute if a login is required to view them. If the attribute is not present, the page is accessible to all.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EExample:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;RequiresLogin()x26gt; _ \nx26lt;RequiresPermission(x22processx22)x26gt; _\nPartial Class DesignReviewEditProgressPage\n    Inherits MyPage x27which inherits System.Web.UI.Page and deal with logins itself\n\n    ...\nEnd Class\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe MyPage class checks what attributes are being tagged to itself and if RequiresLogin is present, it forwards you to a login page.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI believe this could be adapted to fit your own problem.x3C/px3E',-1,0,'2008-08-20 22:12:40'),(23640,'clawrence3','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EJust to check, if you use just this part you get an error?x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EIf so, do you still get an error if you copy and paste one of those Inserts into this x3Epage, I am trying to see if itx27s local to the page or that actual line.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EAlso, can you post a copy of the connection calls (minus passwords), unless the inserts x3Euse exactly the same syntax as this example.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHere is what is in the connection.php file.  I linked to the file through an include in the same fashion as where I execute the INSERT queries elsewhere in the code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E$conn = mysql_connect(x22localhostx22, ******, ******) or die(x22Could not connectx22);\nmysql_select_db(x22adbay_com_-_cmsx22) or die(x22Could not select databasex22);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI will try the working INSERT query in this area to check that out.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs to the others posting about the password access.  I did, as stated in my first posting, check permissions.  I used phpMyAdmin to verify that the permissions for the user account I was using were correct.  And if it matters at all, apache@localhost is not the name of the user account that I use to get into the database.  I donx27t have any user accounts with the name apache in them at all for that matter.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 02:40:40'),(23640,'itrowla','x3Cpx3ENo.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EInstead you could use a in browser modal popup.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 07:25:45'),(23640,'kgrenkovu','x3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EPopularityx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECommunity contributionx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EPublic scrutinyx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWe will be forced to adhere to standards. (which will in turn make the product better)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EGoodwillx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',5,0,'2008-08-21 00:08:37'),(23770,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EUsing SMO/DMO, it isnx27t too difficult to generate a script of your schema.  Data is a little more fun, but still doable.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn general, I take x22Script Itx22 approach, but you might want to consider something along these lines:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3EDistinguish between Development and Staging, such that you can Develop with a subset of data ... this I would create a tool to simply pull down some production data, or generate fake data where security is concerned.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EFor team development, each change to the database will have to be coordinated amongst your team members.  Schema and data changes can be intermingled, but a single script should enable a given feature.  Once all your features are ready, you bundle these up in a single SQL file and run that against a restore of production.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EOnce your staging has cleared acceptance, you run the single SQL file again on the production machine.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI have used the Red Gate tools and they are x3Cstrongx3Egreatx3C/strongx3E tools, but if you canx27t afford it, building the tools and working this way isnx27t too far from the ideal.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 21:38:59'),(23770,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EThis is a really vague question. Wex27d need a concrete example to get a better idea of the problem.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 09:26:59'),(23930,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EDepending how much youx27re planning to do on these legacy projects I would consider not switching.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would really advise you to switch to SVN. I know of a few projects that lost source code because the VSS database became corrupted.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think there are tools that perform the migration from SourceSafe to SVN. (Yes-- a quick Google search confirmed it.) That way you wouldnx27t be losing the revision history.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-24 19:00:50'),(23930,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EIx27ve been using both the newest version of Ankh SVN and Tortoise on a project at home. I find them to both be very good with a caveat.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve found that both SVN tools have at times failed to keep up with my file/folder renaming and moving resulting in it thinking that a perfectly good file needs to be deleted on the next commit. This is probably down to me misusing SVN in some way but TFS at work does not have this problem.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 18:45:47'),(23950,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EOpenID is very slick, and something you should seriously consider as it basically removes the requirement to save local usernames and passwords and worry about authentication.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EA lot of sites nowadays are using both OpenID and their own, giving users the option.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you do decide to roll your own, Ix27d recommend using the email address. Be careful, though, if you are creating something that groups users by an account (say, a company that has several users). In this case, the email address might be used more than once (if they do work for more than one company, for example), and you should allow that.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EHTH!x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-08 19:49:41'),(24040,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EYou wouldnx27t change the existing templates.  In other words, donx27t x3Cemx3Emodifyx3C/emx3E anything under the x3Ccodex3E/Developerx3C/codex3E hierarchy (or wherever you installed your developer tools).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EInstead, clone the templates you want to have customized variants of.  Then change their names and the information in them.  Finally, put them in the appropriate location in your accountx27s x3Ccodex3ELibrary/Application Supportx3C/codex3E folder, specifically:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EFile templates: x3Ccodex3E~/Library/Application Support/Developer/Shared/Xcode/File Templates/x3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETarget templates: x3Ccodex3E~/Library/Application Support/Developer/Shared/Xcode/Target Templates/x3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EProject templates: x3Ccodex3E~/Library/Application Support/Developer/Shared/Xcode/Project Templates/x3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat way they wonx27t be overwritten when you install new developer tools, and you can tweak them to your heartx27s content.x3C/px3E',86,0,'2008-08-29 05:14:27'),(24130,'aauger2','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3E10.1f means floating point with 1 place after the decimal point and the 10 places before the decimal point. If the number has less than 10 digits, itx27s padded with spaces. 10.2f is the same, but with 2 places after the decimal point.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOn every system Ix27ve seen, from Unix to Rails Migrations, this is not the case.  @robintw expresses it best:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EBasically in a simple form itx27s %[width].[precision][type].x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat is, not x2210 places x3Cemx3Ebeforex3C/emx3E the decimal point,x22 but x2210 places, x3Cemx3Eboth before and after, and includingx3C/emx3E the decimal point.x22x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 19:17:26'),(24130,'rdowdellz','x3Cpx3EA variation is where you use a direct hierarchical representation (ie. parent link in node), but also store a path value.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eie. for a directory tree consisting of the following:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EC:\\\n   Temp\n   Windows\n       System32\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou would have the following nodesx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EKey     Name     Parent     Path\n1       C:                  *1*\n2       Temp       1        *1*2*\n3       Windows    1        *1*3*\n4       System32   3        *1*3*4*\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPath is indexed, and will allow you to quickly do a query that picks up a node and all its children, without having to manipulate ranges.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eie. to find C:\\Temp and all its children:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EWHERE Path LIKE x27*1*2*%x27\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis representation is the only place I can think of where storing x3Cemx3Eidx27sx3C/emx3E in a string like this is ok.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 16:18:55'),(24270,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI have worked for a company that developed a system for distributing media content to dedicated x22playersx22. It was web based and used ASP.NET technology and have tried almost every possible media format you can think of and your choice really comes down to asking yourself:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Edoes it needs to play directly out of the box, or can I make sure that the components required to play the videos can be installed beforehand?x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf your answer is that it needs to play out of the box then really your only option is flash (I know that it is not installed by default, but most will already have it installed)x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf it is not a big issue that extra components are needed then you can go with formats that are supported by windows media playerx3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe reason why windows media player falls into the second option is because for some browsers and some formats extra components must be installed.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWe had the luxury that the x22playersx22 were provided by us, so we could go for the second option, however even we tried to x3Ca href=x22http://ffmpeg.mplayerhq.hu/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Econvert as much as possiblex3C/ax3E back to flash because it handles way better than windows media playerx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-05 20:49:31'),(24310,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EI guess one thing that nobody seems to have asked is if you have a legal requirement to store history of changes to the docx27s?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhether you do or donx27t is going to have an impact on what solutions you can consider.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso a notification mechanism for out of date copies is also a bundle of fun. If engineer A has a copy of a document and engineer B then edits it and commits the changes you want engineer A to be notified that his copy is out of date.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDocument control can become a real can of worms quite easily.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMaybe keep the docx27s under CVS or SVN and set it up so that emails are generated to whoever has checked out a copy when updates for the same doc. are checked in to the repository?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: I forgot to add donx27t forget to use the binary switch, e.g. -kb for CVS, when adding the new doc. Otherwise, you will get any sequences of data that happen to match the ascii for keyword strings having the relevant config management data appended thereby corrupting your doc. data.x3C/px3E',19,0,'2008-08-27 14:01:47'),(24470,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EThe trick to that is to use URL rewriting so that x3Cstrongx3Ename.domain.comx3C/strongx3E transparently maps to something like x3Cstrongx3Edomain.com/users/namex3C/strongx3E on your server.  Once you start down that path, itx27s fairly trivial to implement.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-04 16:28:03'),(24580,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EWhat you are asking for is a level of optimisation the linq-to-sql does not provide. I think your best bet is to create a query that returns exactly the data you want, possibly as an anonymous type:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efrom order in DB.GetTablex26lt;Ordersx26gt;()\njoin product in DB.GetTablex26lt;Productsx26gt;()\non order.ProductID = product.ID\nselect new { ID = order.ID, Name = order.Name, ProductName = product.Name };\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',5,0,'2008-08-27 02:36:21'),(24610,'achancelier6','x3Cprex3E\nssize_t\n     recvfrom(int socket, void *restrict buffer, size_t length, int flags,\n         struct sockaddr *restrict address, socklen_t *restrict address_len);\n\n     ssize_t\n     recvmsg(int socket, struct msghdr *message, int flags);\n\n[..]\n     If address is not a null pointer and the socket is not connection-oriented, the\n     source address of the message is filled in.\nx3C/prex3E \n\nx3Cpx3EActual code:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3E\nint nbytes = recvfrom(sock, buf, MAXBUFSIZE, MSG_WAITALL, (struct sockaddr *)x26amp;bindaddr, x26amp;addrlen);x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Efprintf(stdout, x22Read %d bytes on local address %s\\nx22, nbytes, inet_ntoa(bindaddr.sin_addr.s_addr));\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ehope this helps.x3C/px3E',-1,0,'2008-08-27 15:18:34'),(24680,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EThere are three key components (assuming ur using SQL server):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ccodex3ESQLConnectionx3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ccodex3ESqlCommandx3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ccodex3ESqlDataReaderx3C/codex3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(if youx27re using something else, replace x3Ccodex3ESqlx3C/codex3E with x22Somethingx22, like x3Ccodex3EMySqlConnectionx3C/codex3E, x3Ccodex3EOracleCommandx3C/codex3E)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEverything else is just built on top of that.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EExample 1:x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eusing (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(x22CONNECTION STRINGx22))\nusing (SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand())\n{\n  command.commandText = x22SELECT Name FROM Users WHERE Status = @OnlineStatusx22;\n  command.Connection = connection;\n  command.Parameters.Add(x22@OnlineStatusx22, SqlDbType.Int).Value = 1; //replace with enum\n  connection.Open();\n\n  using (SqlDataReader dr = command.ExecuteReader))\n  {\n      Listx26lt;stringx26gt; onlineUsers = new Listx26lt;stringx26gt;();\n\n      while (dr.Read())\n      {\n         onlineUsers.Add(dr.GetString(0));\n      }\n  }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EExample 2:x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eusing (SqlConnection connection = new SqlConnection(x22CONNECTION STRINGx22))\nusing (SqlCommand command = new SqlCommand())\n{\n  command.commandText = x22DELETE FROM Users where Email = @Emailx22;\n  command.Connection = connection;\n  command.Parameters.Add(x22@Emailx22, SqlDbType.VarChar, 100).Value = x22user@host.comx22;\n  connection.Open();\n  command.ExecuteNonQuery();\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',5,0,'2008-08-07 04:37:04'),(24680,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EYes, I thought about that, but I soon figured out that another Domain-Specific-Language (DSL) would be a bit too much.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEssentially, they need to interact with my gamestate in possibly unpredictable ways. For example, a card could have a rule x22When this cards enter play, all your undead minions gain +3 attack against flying enemies, except when the enemy is blessedx22. As trading card games are turn based, the GameState Manager will fire OnStageX events and let the cards modify other cards or the GameState in whatever way the card needs.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf I try to create a DSL, I have to implement a rather large feature set and possibly constantly update it, which shifts the maintenance work to another part without actually removing it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThatx27s why I wanted to stay with a x22realx22 .NET language to essentially be able to just fire the event and let the card manipulate the gamestate in whatever way (within the limits of the code access security).x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-02 03:49:57'),(24680,'srm4902','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EJavax3C/strongx3E: functionalx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint factorial(int x) {\n    return x == 0 ? 1 : x * factorial(x-1);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 23:27:59'),(24730,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EHere are a few x22How Do Ix22 videos to get you started:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://windowsclient.net/learn/videos_wpf.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://windowsclient.net/learn/videos_wpf.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 12:10:11'),(25200,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EPersonally I wouldnx27t use an exit command.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would throw an exception so you can clear any other initialisation up at the end of the function.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eie:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Etry\n{\n    // init opengl/directx\n    // init directaudio\n    // init directinput\n\n    if (GLEW_OK != glewInit())\n    {\n    	throw std::exception(x22glewInit failedx22);\n    }\n}\ncatch ( const std::exceptionx26amp; ex )\n{\n    // message to screen using ex.what()\n    // clear up\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd I agree with OJ - if you want to write tutorials for others, then this is really the wrong place for it. There are already a load of good places for opengl tutorials. x3Ca href=x22http://nehe.gamedev.net/x22x3ETry this one for instancex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 09:08:59'),(25450,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EIx27ve not used the Android Emulator but I have set the $http_proxy environment variable for perl and wget and a few cygwin tools on windows. That might work for you for android, but the slash in the domain name seems like a potential problem.\nI know I tried having my domain x22GLOBALx22 in there, but ended up taking it out and sticking with: x3Ccodex3Ehttp://$USER:password@www-proxy.company.com:80x3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOne problem I run into a lot though is programs that cannot be told to use the proxy for DNS queries too. In cases where they donx27t I always get a host name not found. Ix27d like to find a local dns resolver that can use the proxy for all the programs that wonx27t.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 19:37:35'),(25450,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EI wrote a x3Ccodex3EPowerShellx3C/codex3E provider to give me access to x3Ccodex3EIE7x3C/codex3Ex27s x3Ccodex3ERSSx3C/codex3E feed store, and had lots of fun with it. It lets me x3Ccodex3Ecdx3C/codex3E to a drive called feed: and navigate around folders and feeds using cd and dir. It even lets you add or remove feeds from the command line. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESee this post on my blog as an example:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.madprops.org/blog/getting-the-most-prolific-authors-in-your-feeds/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGetting the Most Prolific Authors in your Feedsx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s rolled up into the x3Ccodex3EPowerShellx3C/codex3E Community Extensions project nowadays, which you can find on x3Ccodex3ECodePlexx3C/codex3E x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/PowerShellCXx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 17:11:06'),(25450,'prihak','x3Cpx3EHave you tried working with your customer to define / formulate x3Cstrongx3Eacceptance testsx3C/strongx3E?x3Cbr /x3E\nUsing something like Fit to come up with these tests - would result in better specs as well as force the customer to think about what is really required. The icing on the cake is instant-doc-executable specs at the end of this process.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat is of course, if your customers are available and open to this approach. Give it a try!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf not (and that seems to be the majority - because it is less work) - calendar flash x27em - schedule meetings/telecons every week until they sing like canaries :) +1 to Dana x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 22:59:07'),(25450,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3ESilverlight programmerx27s donx27t know what theyx27re missing out on, when it comes to Flex.  Silverlight lacks the component model and event triggering capabilites that Flex has.  Using XNA, and C#, a friend of mine has to jump through all kinds of hoops to get his Silverlight application to work.  Then, it has to be handed off to a designer to get it to look half way decent.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EListen to the deepfriedbytes.com podcasts on Silverlight, and youx27ll hear how even a couple guys that really push Silverlight, acknowledge some of these issues.  (I x3Cemx3Ethinkx3C/emx3E, if I recall correctly, one of the guys works for Microsoft, but I could be wrong - I listened to it last week).  They agree that Silverlight isnx27t quite ready for any huge applications, in its current state.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would go with Flex, for a nice clean, straightforward approach - especially if youx27re already familiar with Flash and ActionScript 3.0.  Flex makes alot more sense, in my opinion - Silverlight still has to mature.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-22 23:59:58'),(25460,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EIf youx27ve already got a bunch of custom tasks you use with nAnt, stick with it - you donx27t gain much with MSBuild.  That said, there doesnx27t seem to be anything that nAnt can do that MSBuild canx27t at its core.  Both can call external tools, both can run .Net-based custom tasks, and both have a bunch of community tasks out there.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWex27re using MSBuild here for the same reason you are - itx27s the default build system for VS now, and we didnx27t have any nAnt-specific stuff to worry about.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe x3Ca href=x22http://msbuildtasks.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSBuildCommunityTasksx3C/ax3E are a good third-party task base to start with, and covers most of the custom stuff I ever did in nAnt, including VSS and Subversion support.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-04 19:52:42'),(25530,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EThe way we do this is to have a x27catch allx27 for our domain name registered in DNS so that anything.ourdomain.com will point to our server.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWith Apache you can set up a similar catch-all for your vhosts.  The ServerName must be a single static name but the ServerAlias directive can contain a pattern.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EServername www.ourdomain.com\nServerAlias *.ourdomain.com\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow all of the domains will trigger the vhost for our project.  The final part is to decode the domain name actually used so that you can work out the username in your code, something like (PHP):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Elist( $username ) = explode( x22.x22, $_SERVER[ x22HTTP_HOSTx22 ] );\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eor a RewriteRule as already suggested that silently maps user.ourdomain.com/foo/bar to www.ourdomain.com/foo/bar?user=user or whatever you prefer.x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-04 17:39:39'),(25530,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3Eif you donx27t need to know this pre-render, you could always use the win32 method of getpixel, I believe. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ENote: typing on iPhone in the middle of Missouri with no inet access. Will look up real win32 example and see if there is a .net equivalent.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIn case anyone cares, and doesnx27t want to use the (excellent) answer posted above, you can get the color value of a pixel in .Net via this link x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.drawing.bitmap.getpixel.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSDN examplex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 10:39:12'),(25730,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EEric Z Beard:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ethe activity date is meant to indicate the local time zone, but not a specific onex3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOkay - back to the drawing board. Try this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhere t.TheDateINeedToCheck BETWEEN (\n    dateadd(hh, (tz.Offset + ISNULL(ds.LocalTimeZone, 0)) * -1, @ActivityDate)\n    AND\n    dateadd(hh, (tz.Offset + ISNULL(ds.LocalTimeZone, 0)) * -1, (@ActivityDate + 1))\n)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewhich will translate the @ActivityDate to local time, and compare against that. Thatx27s your best chance for using an index, though Ix27m not sure itx27ll work - you should try it and check the query plan.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe next option would be an indexed view, with an indexed, computed TimeINeedToCheck x3Cemx3Ein local timex3C/emx3E. Then you just go back to:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhere v.TheLocalDateINeedToCheck BETWEEN @ActivityDate AND (@ActivityDate + 1)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewhich would definitely use the index - though you have a slight overhead on INSERT and UPDATE then.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 06:14:08'),(25950,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EThere may be some confusion here about what x22Kx26amp;R Cx22 is. The term refers to the language as documented in the first edition of x22The C Programming Language.x22 Roughly speaking: the input language of the Bell Labs C compiler circa 1978.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EKernighan and Ritchie were involved in the ANSI standardization process. The x22ANSI Cx22 dialect superceded x22Kx26amp;R Cx22 and subsequent editions of x22The C Programming Languagex22 adopt the ANSI conventions. x22Kx26amp;R Cx22 is a x22dead language,x22 except to the extent that some compilers still accept legacy code.x3C/px3E',25,0,'2008-08-22 18:48:18'),(25950,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EYes, sort of.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere is no support included in the trunk, you need to write your own dialect.  Or you can port the x3Ca href=x22http://www.hxtt.com/hibernate.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EParadox dialect created for Hibernatex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 22:24:39'),(26020,'itrowla','x3Cpx3EI would use the dayofyear function of datepart:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E\nSelect *\nfrom mytable\nwhere datepart(dy,date1) = datepart(dy,date2)\nand\nyear(date1) = year(date2) --assuming you want the same year too\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESee the datepart reference x3Ca href=x22http://www.tizag.com/sqlTutorial/sqldatepart.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 19:27:02'),(26230,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EOne thing worth keeping in mind is that leading wildcard queries come at a significant performance premium, compared to other wildcard usages.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-06 18:03:59'),(26230,'srm9547','x3Cpx3ECurrently in my winforms app I have handlers for x3Ccodex3EApplication.ThreadExceptionx3C/codex3E, as above, but also x3Ccodex3EAppDomain.CurrentDomain.UnhandledExceptionx3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EMost exceptions arrive via the x3Ccodex3EThreadExceptionx3C/codex3E handler, but the AppDomain one has also caught a few in my experiencex3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-06 00:42:31'),(26260,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EI know this might sound bad, but you need to ensure there is no whitespace between then end of you x3Ccodex3Ex26lt;imgx26gt;x3C/codex3E tag and the start of the end x3Ccodex3Ex26lt;/tdx26gt;x3C/codex3E tag.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ei.e. The following will present the problem:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;tdx26gt;\n x26lt;img src=x22image.jpgx22/x26gt;\nx26lt;/tdx26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd this will not:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;tdx26gt;x26lt;img src=x22image.jpgx22/x26gt;x26lt;/tdx26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope that helps.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: OK, that wasnx27t the solution at all. doh!x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-22 14:08:45'),(26450,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EIf you are quite happy with MSBuild, then I would stick with MSBuild.  This may be one of those cases where the tool you learn first is the one you will prefer.  I started with NAnt and canx27t quite get used to MSBuild.  Ix27m sure they will both be around for quite some time.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are some fundamental differences between the two, probably best highlighted by x3Ca href=x22http://forums.msdn.microsoft.com/en-US/msbuild/thread/994761a3-ea9d-40c7-8d4f-4c208b2023f6/x22x3Ethis conversation between some NAnt fans and a Microsoftiex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EInterestingly, x3Ca href=x22http://codebetter.com/blogs/jeremy.miller/default.aspxx22x3EJeremy Millerx3C/ax3E asked the exact opposite question x3Ca href=x22http://codebetter.com/blogs/jeremy.miller/archive/2007/09/20/is-there-a-good-reason-to-switch-to-msbuild.aspxx22x3Eon his blogx3C/ax3E last year.  x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-05 02:52:31'),(26450,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EErick,x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re interested in setting the document root, you might look at getting a web server installed on your machine, or, if you already have one (like Apache or IIS), storing your project-in-development in the web root of that server (htdocs in Apache, not entirely sure in IIS). If youx27d rather leave your files where they are, you can set up virtual hosts and even map them to addresses that you can type into your browser (for example, I have a local.mrwarshaw.com address that resolves to the web root of my personal sitex27s development folder).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re on Windows and donx27t want to mess around with setting up a server on your own, you could get a package like XAMPP or WAMPP, though bear in mind that those carry the extra weight of PHP and MySQL with them. Still, if youx27ve got the space, theyx27re a pretty easy drop-in development environment for your machine.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 14:47:11'),(26570,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EOne issue that hasnx27t been raised by others is whether x3Cstrongx3Edoublex3C/strongx3E is the same as a x3Cstrongx3Efloatx3C/strongx3E.  On some systems a different format specifier was needed for a double compared to a float.  Not least because the parameters passed could be of different sizes.\nx3CPREx3E\n %f - float\n %lf - double\n %g - double\nx3C/PREx3Ex3C/px3E',-1,0,'2008-08-23 15:00:49'),(26620,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIf youx27re using VB.NET, you can tap into the very convenient ApplicationEvents.vb.  This file comes for free with a VB.NET WinForms project and contains a method for handling x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/3a02k5s0%28VS.80%29.aspxx22x3Eunhandled exceptionsx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ETo get to this nifty file, itx27s x22Project Properties x26gt;x26gt; Application x26gt;x26gt; Application Eventsx22x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re not using VB.NET, then yeah, itx27s handling x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.windows.forms.application.threadexception.aspxx22x3EApplication.ThreadExceptionx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-06 00:16:26'),(26760,'dperrenl','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#include x26lt;stdlib.hx26gt;\n\nint main()\n{\n    system(x22echo HAIx22);\n\n    return 0;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',9,0,'2008-08-20 02:58:47'),(26760,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EIt would probably be more work than itx27s worth, but you can use static C#/VB variables in a SQL CLR UDF, so I think youx27d be able to do what you want to do by simply incrementing this variable every time the UDF is called.  The static variable would be lost whenever the appdomain unloaded, of course.  So if you need continuity of your ID from one day to the next, youx27d need a way, on first access of NextId, to poll all of tables that use this ID, to find the highest value.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-27 10:07:01'),(27020,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EI cannot live without Eclipse and Mylynx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:15:07'),(27020,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3ENotepad2, e.TextEditor, Textmatex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWinSplit Revolutionx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGoogle, Pandorax3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESynergyx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFireBugx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESVNx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EVisual Studio if .net appx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:34:14'),(27020,'itrowla','x3CPx3EIf you are already spending time in Visual Studio, then you can always use the x3CSTRONGx3EServer Explorerx3C/STRONGx3E to connect to any .Net compliant database server.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EProvided youx27re using Professional or greater, you can create and edit tables and databases, run queries, etc.x3C/Px3E',4,0,'2008-08-08 03:47:57'),(27220,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EIf by some chance you happen to be using Ruby, therex27s x3Ca href=x22http://haml.hamptoncatlin.com/docs/rdoc/classes/Sass.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESassx3C/ax3E. It supports hierarchical selectors (using indentation to establish hierarchies), among other things, which makes life easier to an extend from a syntactical perspective (you repeat yourself a lot less). x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI am certainly with you, though. While I would consider myself a small-time CSS expert, I think it would be nice if there were tools for CSS like there are with Javascript (Prototype, JQuery, etc.). You tell the tool what you want, and it handles the browser inconsistencies behind-the-scenes. That would be ideal, methinks.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-25 05:05:01'),(27240,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3ELike everything else it is environmental and depends on the use of the system.  The question you need to ask your self is:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Colx3E\n\nx3Clix3EWill this be actively developedx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EIs this going to be used over the course of many years and expanded onx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EIs the expansion of the application unknown and thus infinitex3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/olx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EReally it comes down to laziness.  How much time to do you want to spend reworking the system from the UI?  Because having no business layer means duplication of rules in your UI across possibility many many pages.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThen again if this is a proof of concept or short demo or class project.  Take the easy way out.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 06:46:16'),(27240,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EThe reason why #1 is slower is that [\\d;]+ is a greedy quantifier. Using +? or *? is going to do lazy quantifing. See x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/3206d374%28VS.80%29.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSDN - Quantifiersx3C/ax3E for more info.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou may want to try:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex22(\\e\\[(\\d{1,2};)*?[mz]?)?x22x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThat may be faster for you.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-07 20:24:02'),(27240,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EEric, the document root is the folder in which your file is, wherever it may be.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-21 07:43:02'),(27610,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIn my opinion it is more a question of personal preference.  nAnt is a great framework and MSBuild is almost as capable.  With the ability to easily develop custom tasks (in both frameworks) you can accomplish almost anything that you need to do.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI cannot answer the x22still supportedx22 portion of your questions, but I would say if you are already comfortable with nAnt then itx27s probably viable.  If you (or someone in your group) is familiar with MSBuild then that is a fine way to go as well.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-04 19:12:37'),(27640,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EBackup and Restore is the most straight-forward way I know.  You have to be careful between servers as security credentials donx27t come with the restored database.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-05 05:31:16'),(27670,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3ESure thing, the simplest way is this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect foo from bar where baz in (1,2,3)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',26,0,'2008-08-20 16:59:51'),(27670,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EThe exact definitions of x22vsize,x22 x22rss,x22 x22rprvt,x22 x22rshrd,x22 and other obscure-looking abbreviations vary from OS to OS.  The manual pages for the x22topx22 and x22psx22 commands will have some sort of description, but all such descriptions are simplified greatly (or are based on long-extinct kernel implementations).  x22Process sizex22 as a concept is fiendishly difficult to pin down in the general case.  Answers in specific instances depend heavily on the actual memory management implementation in the OS, and are rarely as satisfying as the tidy x22process sizex22 concept that exists in the minds of most users (and most developers).x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EFor example, none of those numbers (nor, likely, any combination of them) can be used to tell you exactly how many such processes can run at once in a given amount of free memory.  But really, your best bet is to come at it from that end: why do you want this number, and what will you use it for?  Given that information, I think youx27ll get more useful answers.x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-05 05:07:50'),(27670,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EIf to be used with SQL Server 2000/2005 the original code needs to be enclosed in transaction to make sure that data remain consistent in concurrent scenario.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EBEGIN TRANSACTION Upsert\nupdate myTable set Col1=@col1, Col2=@col2 where ID=@ID\nif @@rowcount = 0\ninsert into myTable (Col1, Col2) values (@col1, @col2)\nCOMMIT TRANSACTION Upsert\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis will incur additional performance cost, but will ensure data integrity.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAdd, as already suggested, MERGE should be used where available.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-25 00:21:28'),(27670,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EWell, if you are just wanting to learn on your own, I would say you should go with something free, like subversion.  If you are a company who has never used source control before, then it really depends on your needs.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:51:03'),(27670,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EJust set x3Ccodex3Eautocomplete=x22offx22x3C/codex3E. There is a very good reason for doing this: You want to provide your own autocomplete functionality!x3C/px3E',12,0,'2008-08-05 20:32:11'),(27700,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EYou can still use in forx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect *\nfrom table\nwhere field  = x271x27 or field = x272x27 or field = x273x27\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eits justx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect * from table where field in (x271x27,x272x27,x273x27)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 17:08:03'),(27850,'ajan8','x3Cpx3E@Tim Sullivan from Bertrand Meyer it can only be related to Eiffel :)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think hex27s talking about x3Ca href=x22http://www.cse.yorku.ca/~sel/espec/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EESpecx3C/ax3E. Given the name RSpec from the Ruby Folk, I think we can give them the label x22heavily inspiredx22.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 03:40:59'),(27850,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EI donx27t understand what you mean by x22bring in the appx22 and x22one turn drop itx22. By x22bring in the appx22 do you mean deploy? As for x22One turn dropx22, I totally donx27t understand it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for open betas, that depends on your audience, really. Counterstrike, for example, apparently run a few closed betas before doing open betas, so herex27s my suggestion:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3ESet up a forum in some free forumboard, or set up a topic in a popular gaming forum.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ELook for people (whether or not they are in those forums) that you trust, and let them in in a closed beta. This will allow you to iron out serious kinks at first.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EIf your closed group isnx27t reporting as much bugs any more, release it to open beta, pointing out ways on how they could give feedback to you.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis is similar to the approach StackOverflow took, but this being a game setting it up on a gaming forum will give the dual benefit of advertising your game x3Cemx3Eandx3C/emx3E getting some interested beta testers.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 15:01:15'),(27910,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EIn addition to simply being x22clearerx22, separating classes into separate files makes it easier for multiple developers not to step on each others toes.  There will be less merging when it comes time to commit changes to your version control tool.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-26 18:34:40'),(27910,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3ERelative to straight procedural programming, the first fundamental tenet of OOP is the notion of information hiding and encapsulation. This idea leads to the notion of the x3Cstrongx3Ex3Cemx3Eclassx3C/emx3Ex3C/strongx3E that seperates the interface from implementation. These are hugely important concepts and the basis for putting a framework in place to think about program design in a different way and better (I think) way. You canx27t really argue against those properties - there is no trade-off made and it is always a cleaner way to modulize things.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOther aspects of OOP including inheritance and polymorphism are important too, but as others have alluded to, those are commonly over used. ie: Sometimes people use inheritance and/or polymorphism because they can, not because they should have. They are powerful concepts and very useful, but need to be used wisely and are not automatic winning advantages of OOP.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERelative to re-use. I agree re-use is over sold for OOP. It is a possible side effect of well defined objects, typically of more primitive/generic classes and is a direct result of the encapsulation and information hiding concepts. It is potentially easier to be re-used because the interfaces of well defined classes are just simply clearer and somewhat self documenting.x3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-23 19:43:04'),(27910,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIx27ve seen similar behaviour when setting certain properties of controls in the constructor of the form itself. They seem to revert back to their design-time defaults.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI notice youx27re already overriding the OnLoad method. Have you tried setting AutoSize = false there? Or are you mainly concerned with providing a x3Cemx3Edefaultx3C/emx3E value of false?x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-29 04:53:56'),(28110,'aa9279','x3Cpx3ESo far, from what I have seen, RMC seems to be one-of-a-kind, which is both cool, but sad :(x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt seems pretty inactive, but I have posted a couple of questions on there, and amazed at the response (a lot of people just have the RSS feed and wait for something to happen). So I would definately recommend just getting active on there..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, I have read some great books on Safari including x3Ca href=x22http://safari.oreilly.com/0735619484x22x3EMS Pressx27 x22Test Driven Developmentx22x3C/ax3E which I found really x3Cemx3Ehelpedx3C/emx3E . However I have to admit, I still need a lot of work in adjusting my brain for TDD etc.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFollowing this question though! (+1) look forward to seeing if there is more out there! :)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Ch3x3EEdit:x3C/h3x3E\n\nx3Cpx3EJust found x3Ca href=x22http://codebetter.com/blogs/darrell.norton/pages/50337.aspxx22x3Ethis blog postx3C/ax3E that outlines a number of good bits of software, websites and books :) I knew I had one somewhere!x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 10:43:54'),(28150,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EGenerally when you need to do a sizeable (or frequent) queries to busy tables, where read committed would possibly be blocked by locks from uncommited transactions, but ONLY when you can live with inaccurate data. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs an example, on a gaming web site I worked on recently there was a summary display of some stats about recent games, this was all based on dirty reads, it was more important for us to include then exclude the transactional data not yet committed (we knew anyway that few, if any, transactions would be backed out), we felt that on average the data would be more accurate that way.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-21 23:26:02'),(28160,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3ETherex27s no need for the JavaScript function, the first argument to x3Ccodex3EExternalInterfacex3C/codex3E can be any JavaScript code, it doesnx27t have to be a function name (the documentation says so, but it is wrong).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETry this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EExternalInterface.call(x22alert(x27hellox27)x22);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',7,0,'2008-08-21 21:43:48'),(28160,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EI found x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/svnrevisionlabellerx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E project on google code. This is x3Ccodex3ECCNETx3C/codex3E plugin to generate the label in x3Ccodex3ECCNETx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe x3Ccodex3EDLLx3C/codex3E is tested with x3Ccodex3ECCNET 1.3x3C/codex3E but it works with x3Ccodex3ECCNET 1.4x3C/codex3E for me. Ix27m successfully using this plugin to label my build.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow onto passing it to x3Ccodex3EMSBuildx3C/codex3E...x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-04 15:51:59'),(28280,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EA shared SAN with failover is a great solution with a great (high) cost.  Are there any similar solutions with failover at a reasonable cost?  Perhaps something like DRBD for windows?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe problem with a simple shared filesystem is the lack of redundancy (what if the fileserver goes down)?x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 19:16:24'),(28380,'aauger2','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.prescod.net/rest/rest_vs_soap_overview/x22x3EGoogle first hitx3C/ax3E seems pretty comprehensive.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think the problem here is there are too many advocates of one or the other, may be better of googling and getting more of a handle of the prox27s/conx27s yourself and making your own decision.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI know that sounds kinda lame, but ultimately these sort of design decisions fall down to the developer/architect working on it, and x3Cstrongx3E99% of the time, the problem domain will be the deciding factorx3C/strongx3E (or at least it should be), not a guide on the net.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-26 23:53:04'),(28530,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EThe x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/blindside/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBlindSidex3C/ax3E site also listed these other projects:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.epresence.tv/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EePresencex3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/openmeetingsx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EOpenMeetingsx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.dimdim.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDimDimx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.webhuddle.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWebHuddlex3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAll opensource as well.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 02:46:06'),(28530,'nivakhnov17','x3Cpx3EIx27ll try to answer with the limited amount of details youx27ve given.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E1: Wether itx27s open or closed is really only an issue if you have great buzz, and a large group of users hammering down  your door, trying toget in on the action. \nIf this is the case, I think you might get more loyalty and commitment from users in a closed beta.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E2: You havenx27t given many (any) details as to what kind of game you are talking about, so itx27s pretty hard to answer this one.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E/Jonasx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 15:04:31'),(28530,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EI once implemented a client and a server with 2 more guys (as part of a course).x3Cbr /x3E\nI can tell you that the RFC you were already linked to is great.x3Cbr /x3E\nIx27d also try simply sniffing a connection with an existing client to see for yourself how stuff work.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 23:24:06'),(28820,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EOU is an Organizational Unit (sort of like a Subfolder in Explorer), not a Group, Hence group1, 2 and 3 are not actually groups.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou are looking for the DN Attribute, also called x22distinguishedNamex22. You can simply use DOMAIN\\DN once you have that.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: For groups, the CN (Common Name) could also work. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe full string from Active Directory normally looks like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ecn=Username,cn=Users,dc=DomainName,dc=comx3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Can be longer or shorter, but the important bit is that the x22oux22 part is worthless for what youx27re trying to achieve.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 01:57:23'),(28820,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3Euse it if you want the data back right away and it is not that important if it is rightx3Cbrx3E\ndo not use if if the data is important to be correct or if you are doing updates with itx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso take a look at snapshot isolation which has been introduced in sql server 2005x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-21 23:26:44'),(28820,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EIn your convert call, you need to specify a third style parameter, e.g., the format of the datetimes that are stored as varchar, as specified in this document: x3Ca href=x22http://doc.ddart.net/mssql/sql70/ca-co_1.htmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECAST and CONVERT (T-SQL)x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 18:13:25'),(28840,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EOlder AnkhSVN (pre 2.0) was very crappy and I was only using it for shiny icons in the solution explorer. I relied on Tortoise for everything except reverts.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe newer Ankh is a complete rewrite (it is now using the Source Control API of the IDE) and looks x26amp; works much better. Still, I havenx27t forced it to any heavy lifting. Icons is enough for me.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe only gripe I have with 2.0 is the fact that it slaps its footprint to x3Cstrongx3E.slnx3C/strongx3E files. I always revert them lest they cause problems for co-workers who do not have Ankh installed. Dunno if my fears are groundless or not.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Chr /x3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eaddendum:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI have been using v2.1.7141 a bit more extensively for the last few weeks and here are the new things I have to add:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3ENo ugly crashes that plagued v1.x. Yay!x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EFor some reason, x22Show Changesx22 (diff) windows are limited to only two. Meh.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDiff windows do not allow editing/reverting yet. Boo!x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EUpdates, commits and browsing are MUCH faster than Tortoise. Yay!x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAll in all, I would not use it standalone, but once you start using it, it becomes an almost indispensable companion to Tortoise.x3C/px3E',21,0,'2008-08-20 18:00:26'),(28840,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EA lot of it depends on the kind of work Ix27m doing.  I use x3Ca href=x22http://git.or.cz/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Egit or x3Ca href=x22http://subversion.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esvnx3C/ax3E on pretty much everything I write these days.  x3Ca href=x22http://github.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGithubx3C/ax3E has raised the bar for ease of collaboration and generally what I expect from an SCM repository.  x3Ca href=x22http://macromates.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETextMatex3C/ax3E always comes in useful for snippets, regex find and replace, and all sorts of little editing niceties; for most projects itx27s my primary text editor.  For Java Ix27ll spend a good bit of time in x3Ca href=x22http://www.eclipse.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EEclipsex3C/ax3E, and back when I was did .NET work Ix27d use x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/vstudio/products/default.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EVisual Studiox3C/ax3E.  If Ix27m scratching together a prototype design for a web site, Ix27ll use Coda or something similar.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you count libraries and frameworks as x22development tools,x22 x3Ca href=x22http://www.rubycentral.com/book/tut_stdtypes.html#S4x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERubyx27s regexesx3C/ax3E take the cake for ease of use.  Haskellx27s x3Ca href=x22http://legacy.cs.uu.nl/daan/parsec.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EParsecx3C/ax3E wins for doing serious parsing, followed very closely by Javax27s x3Ca href=x22http://www.antlr.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EANTLRx3C/ax3E.  Hype be damned, Ix27ve yet to be as productive writing a web app than I am with x3Ca href=x22http://www.rubyonrails.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERuby on Railsx3C/ax3E, though x3Ca href=x22http://pylonshq.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EPylonsx3C/ax3E in Python land is nice.  Likewise with Visual Studio for doing client side GUI work, though I think Cocoax3C/ax3Ex3Ca href=x22http://developer.apple.com/tools/xcode/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EXCodex3C/ax3E in Leopard could be very competitive if I ever get a good grasp on Objective-C.  x3Ca href=x22http://llvm.org/docs/LangRef.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELLVMx27s IRx3C/ax3E is the new assembly if youx27re writing a compiler.  x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:52:27'),(28950,'prihak','x3Cpx3ECC.NET is simply the build server technology, not the build script technology. We use CC.NET at work to very successfully call MSBuild build scripts with no problems.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENAnt is an older and more mature build scripting language, but they are both similar in how they work. There are very few things I could do in NAnt that I canx27t also do in MSBuild, so it really comes down to which one you are more comfortable with. As far as how active NAnt is, donx27t go by when the last release was...instead go by when the last nightly build was. NAnt tends to go a long time between releases, but the nightly builds are usually pretty stable.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-29 08:23:19'),(29040,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3ExUnit.net looks like it provides a slightly different approach to N/MB/MS/Unit, which is interesting.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn my search for an rspec-like solution (because I LOVE the rspec), I also came across x3Ca href=x22http://nspec.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ENSpecx3C/ax3E, which looks a bit wordy, but combined with the x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/nspec-extensions/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ENSpec Extensionsx3C/ax3E addon to use C#3 extension methods, it looks pretty nice.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-06 00:53:00'),(29370,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EI guess a fairly big downside is that the extra volume of code that you have to write, manage and maintain for a x3Cstrongx3Esmallx3C/strongx3E project may just be overkill.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s all down to whatx27s appropriate for the size of the project, the expected life of the final project and the budget!  Sometimes, whilst doing things x27properlyx27 is appealing, doing something a little more x27lightweightx27 can be the right commercial decision!x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-08 17:08:40'),(29370,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EThe main performance hit isnx27t going to be from the transfer of the encoded file, itx27s going to be in the processing that the server has to do to encode the file pre-transfer (unless the files donx27t change often and the encoded version can be cached somehow).x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 23:24:17'),(29370,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3ENotepadd++, Mercurial, FireFox, FireBugx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:25:52'),(29370,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3ECheckout x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/PSHypervx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EPowershell Management library for Hyper-V on CodePlexx3C/ax3E. Some features:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EFinding a VMx3Cbr /x3E\n  Connecting to a VMx3Cbr /x3E\n  Discovering and manipulating Machine statesx3Cbr /x3E\n  Backing up, exporting and snapshotting VMsx3Cbr /x3E\n  Adding and removing VMs, configuring motherboard settings.x3Cbr /x3E\n  Manipulating Disk controllers, drives and disk imagesx3Cbr /x3E\n  Manipluating Network Interface Cardsx3Cbr /x3E\n  Working with VHD files  x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 20:50:42'),(29460,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EIf this is for XML serialization and NHibernate, where you want the parameterless constructor to be accessible (as is the case in the x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/27758/notify-developer-of-a-do-not-use-method#27796x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eexamplex3C/ax3E you referenced), then use a private or protected parameterless constructor for serialization, or a protected constructor for NHibernate.  With the protected version, you are opening yourself up to inherited classes being able to call that code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you donx27t want code calling a method, donx27t make it accessible.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: To perhaps answer the deeper question, AFAIK the compiler only knows about three attributes: x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa664620(VS.71).aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EObsolete, Conditional, and AttributeUsagex3C/ax3E. To add special handling for other attributes would require modifying the compiler.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-26 18:36:30'),(29460,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EThe #1 thing you need to be aware of (and Ix27m guessing you probably already are) is that the guys doing the coding x3Cemx3Eshouldx3C/emx3E know what they are doing.  Depending on the personailties of the members of your team, you should be able to find someone who is willing and able to explain any of the intricacies to you on an as-required basis.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn my experience, the biggest hinderence to a project is the PM who understands the project, but not how to accomplish it (not in itself a problem), but who is also unwilling to listen to what his team tell him.  As with any project management, accept that you canx27t know everything, and be humble enough to ask for explanations where needed.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 18:30:19'),(29460,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIn the past I have used triggers to construct db update/insert/delete logging. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou could insert a record each time one of the above actions is done on a specific table into a logging table that keeps track of the action, what db user did it, timestamp, table it was preformed on, and previous value. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere is probably a better answer though as this would require you to cache the value before the actual delete or update was preformed I think. But you could use this to do rollbacks. x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-23 04:12:10'),(29460,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EThis may not apply to your code, but a lot of classes within the .NET framework are sealed purposely so that no one tries to create a sub-class.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are certain situations where the internals are complex and require certain things to be controlled very specifically so the designer decided no one should inherit the class so that no one accidentally breaks functionality by using something in the wrong way.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 01:42:44'),(29580,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EMy first exposure was CVS with WinCVS as a client.  it was horrid.  Next was Subversion, with TortoiseSVN and Eclipsex27s integration.  It was intuitive, and heavenly.  I think that using CVS with TortoiseCVS and Eclipsex27s would be nice as well, though I prefer the way SVN handles revisioning. The entire repository is versioned with each check in, not individual files.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:53:17'),(29630,'prihak','x3Cpx3EPython threads are good for x3Cstrongx3Econcurrent I/O programmingx3C/strongx3E. Threads are swapped out of the CPU as soon as they block waiting for input from file, network, etc. This allows other Python threads to use the CPU while others wait. This would allow you to write a multi-threaded web server or web crawler, for example.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, Python threads are serialized by the x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Interpreter_Lockx22x3EGILx3C/ax3E when they enter interpreter core. This means that if two threads are crunching numbers, only one can run at any given moment. It also means that you canx27t take advantage of multi-core or multi-processor architectures.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are solutions like running multiple Python interpreters concurrently, using a C based threading library. This is not for the faint of heart and the benefits might not be worth the trouble. Letx27s hope for an all Python solution in a future release.x3C/px3E',43,0,'2008-08-29 10:33:54'),(29680,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EPersonally, I try to always use x3Cemx3Ethisx3C/emx3E when referring to member variables.  It helps clarify the code and make it more readable.  Even if there is no ambiguity, someone reading through my code for the first time doesnx27t know that, but if they see x3Cemx3Ethisx3C/emx3E used consistently, they will know if they are looking at a member variable or not.x3C/px3E',35,0,'2008-08-23 09:05:44'),(29700,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EIf indeed you are able to insert using the same connection calls, your problem most likely lies in the user x22apachex22 not having SELECT permissions on the database. If you have phpMyAdmin installed you can look at the permissions for the user in the Privileges pane. phpMyAdmin also makes it very easy to modify the permissions.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you only have access to the command line, you can check the permissions from the mysql database.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYoux27ll probably need to do something like: x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EGRANT SELECT ON myDatabase.myTable TO x27apachex27@x27localhostx27;x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 02:02:23'),(29760,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIx27d suggest that modifying the underlying XML file is x22considered harmfulx22.  Especially if you havenx27t checked to see if the document is open!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve had a quick look at the Scripting Dictionary for Pages, and it seems pretty comprehensive; here is part of one entry:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Edocumentx3C/strongx3E n [inh. x3Cemx3Edocumentx3C/emx3E x3E x3Cemx3Eitemx3C/emx3E; see also Standard Suite] : A Pages document.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3Eelementsx3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Econtains x3Cstrongx3Ecaptured pages, character\n  styles, charts, graphics, images,\n  lines, list styles, pages, paragraph\n  styles, sections, shapes, tables, text\n  boxesx3C/strongx3E.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cemx3Epropertiesx3C/emx3Ex3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Ebody textx3C/strongx3E (text) : The main text flow of the document.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Ebottom marginx3C/strongx3E (real) : The bottom margin of the publication.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Efacing pagesx3C/strongx3E (boolean) : Whether or not the view is set to facing\n  pages.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Efooter marginx3C/strongx3E (real) : The footer margin of the publication.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Eheader marginx3C/strongx3E (real) : The header margin of the publication.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3Eidx3C/strongx3E (integer, r/o) : The unique identifier of the document.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3E...x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo, I guess Ix27d want to know what it is that you want to do that you canx27t do with AppleScript?x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 14:08:56'),(29820,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EI donx27t really know javascript, but couldnx27t you create a stack of windows?x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 18:00:33'),(29890,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIf you donx27t want to use the DLR you can x3Ca href=x22http://docs.codehaus.org/display/BOO/Boo+as+an+embedded+scripting+languagex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Euse Boo (which has an interpreter)x3C/ax3E or you could consider x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/scriptdotnetx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethe Script.NET (S#) project on CodePlexx3C/ax3E. With the Boo solution you can choose between compiled scripts or using the interpreter, and Boo makes a nice scripting language, has a flexible syntax and an extensible language via its open compiler architecture. Script.NET looks nice too, though, and you could easily extend that language as well as its an open source project and uses a very friendly Compiler Generator (x3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/ironyx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EIrony.netx3C/ax3E).x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-06 20:28:19'),(29890,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3ESubversion with tortoisesvn. (tortoisesvn because you can see a lot of what goes on visually and will provide a good jumping off point for the command line stuff. ) There is tons of documentation out there and most likely you will see it at least one point in your career. Almost every company I have worked for and interviewed with runs SVN. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 00:31:59'),(29890,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EFlash is certainly the most ubiquitous and portable solution.  x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adobe_Flash#Market_sharex22x3E98% of browsersx3C/ax3E have Flash installed.  Other alternatives are x3Ca href=x22http://www.apple.com/quicktime/download/x22x3EQuicktimex3C/ax3E, x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windowsmedia/default.mspxx22x3EWindows Media Playerx3C/ax3E, or even x3Ca href=x22http://silverlight.net/x22x3ESilverlightx3C/ax3E (Microsoftx27s Flash competitor, which can be used to embed several video formats).x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI would recommend using Flash (and itx27s FLV video file format) for embedding your video unless you have very specific requirements as far as video quality or DRM.x3C/px3E',19,0,'2008-08-05 20:44:01'),(29980,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EThis is an alternative way (DataReader is faster than this one):x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Estring s = x22x22;x3Cbrx3ESqlConnection conn = new SqlConnection(x22Server=192.168.1.1;Database=master;Connect Timeout=30;User ID=foobar;Password=raboof;x22);x3Cbrx3ESqlDataAdapter da = new SqlDataAdapter(x22SELECT TOP 5 name, dbid FROM sysdatabasesx22, conn);x3Cbrx3EDataTable dt = new DataTable();x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Eda.Fill(dt);x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3Efor (int i = 0; i x26lt; dt.Rows.Count; i++)x3Cbrx3E{x3Cbrx3E    s += dt.Rows[i][x22namex22].ToString() + x22 -- x22 + dt.Rows[i][x22dbidx22].ToString() + x22\\nx22;x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3Cbrx3EMessageBox.Show(s);x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',6,0,'2008-08-05 18:17:22'),(30080,'abaterb','x3Cpx3ESometimes your class interface just isnx27t meant to be inheirited.  The public interface just isnx27t virtual and while someone could override the functionality thatx27s in place it would just be wrong.  Yes in general they shouldnx27t override the public interface, but you can insure that they donx27t by making the class non-inheritable.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe example I can think of right now are customized contained classes with deep clones in .Net.  If you inherit from them you lose the deep clone ability.[Ix27m kind of fuzzy on this example, itx27s been a while since I worked with IClonable]  If you have a true singelton class, you probably donx27t want inherited forms of it around, and a data persistence layer is not normally place you want a lot of inheritance.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-24 01:45:29'),(30080,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIn addition to the benefits already mentioned, another nice feature of using FogBugz is BugzScout, which you can use to report errors from your app and log them into FogBugz automatically.  If youx27re a one person team, chances are there are some bugs in your code youx27ve never seen during your own testing, so itx27s nice to have those bugs found x22in the wildx22 automatically reported and logged for you.x3C/px3E',12,0,'2008-08-06 19:08:52'),(30160,'itrowla','x3Cpx3EYou canx27t dynamically add methods to existing objects or classes in .NET, except by changing the source for that class.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can, however, in C# 3.0, use extension methods, which x3Cemx3Elookx3C/emx3E like new methods, but are compile-time magic.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ETo do this for your code:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic static class StringExtensionsx3Cbrx3E{x3Cbrx3E    public static String trim(this String s)x3Cbrx3E    {x3Cbrx3E        return s.Trim();x3Cbrx3E    }x3Cbrx3E}x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ETo use it:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EString s = x22  Test  x22;x3Cbrx3Es = s.trim();x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThis looks like a new method, but will compile the exact same way as this code:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EString s = x22  Test  x22;x3Cbrx3Es = StringExtensions.trim(s);x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWhat exactly are you trying to accomplish? Perhaps there are better ways of doing what you want?x3C/px3E',18,0,'2008-08-07 16:04:11'),(30160,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EWe use NUnit and x3Ca href=x22http://mbunit.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMBUnitx3C/ax3E here. We use x3Ca href=x22http://testdriven.netx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETestDriven.NETx3C/ax3E to run the unit tests from within Visual Studio. We use the excellent, highly recommended x3Ca href=x22http://www.ayende.com/projects/rhino-mocks/downloads.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERhinoMocksx3C/ax3E as a mock framework.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-06 20:07:06'),(30170,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EI thought you meant x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paginationx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Epagination of the printed pagex3C/ax3E - thatx27s where I cut my teeth.  I was going to enter a great monologue about collecting all the content for the page, positioning (a vast number of rules here, constrait engines are quite helpful) and justification... but apparently you were talking about the process of organizing information on webpages.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor that, Ix27d guess database hits.  Disk access is slow.  Once youx27ve got it in memory, sorting is cheap.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 10:37:13'),(30170,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3E@akux3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ethen you should throw System.ArgumentNullExceptionx3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI donx27t see how throwing a .net framework exception is going to help him :)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOtherwise, in a Java way, assuming the null comes from a programming error (ie. should never go outside the testing phase), then leave the system throw it, or if there are side-effects reaching that point, check for null at the beginning and throw either IllegalArgumentException or NullPointerException.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf the null could come from an actual x3Cemx3Eexceptionx3C/emx3Eal case but you donx27t want to use a checked exception for that, then you definitely want to go the IllegalArgumentException route at the beginning of the method.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-29 03:55:19'),(30230,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EThe SSL only helps with sniffing attacks. If an attacker has access to your machine I will assume they can copy your secure cookie too.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAt the very least, make sure old cookies lose their value after a while. Even a successful hijaking attack will be thwarted when the cookie stops working. If the user has a cookie from a session that logged in more than a month ago, make them reenter their password. Make sure that whenever a user clicks on your sitex27s x22log outx22 link, that the old session UUID can never be used again. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m not sure if this idea will work but here goes: Add a serial number into your session cookie, maybe a string like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESessionUUID, Serial Num, Current Date/Timex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEncrypt this string and use it as your session cookie. Regularly change the serial num - maybe when the cookie is 5 minutes old and then reissue the cookie.  You could even reissue it on every page view if you wanted to. On the server side, keep a record of the last serial num youx27ve issued for that session.  If someone ever sends a cookie with the wrong serial number it means that an attacker may be using a cookie they intercepted earlier so invalidate the session UUID and ask the user to reenter their password and then reissue a new cookie.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERemember that your user may have more than one computer so they may have more than one active session. Donx27t do something that forces them to log in again every time they switch between computers.x3C/px3E',28,0,'2008-08-23 22:07:32'),(30230,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EWhat on Earth are you all Word-is-binary-so-no-diff people talking about? TortoiseSVN, for example, integrates right out of the box with Word and enables you to use Wordx27s built-in diff and merge functionality. It works just fine.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI have worked on projects that store documents in version control. It has worked out pretty well, although if people are unfamiliar with version control, they are probably going to have conceptual difficulties with things like x22working copyx22 and x22mergex22 and x22conflictx22. Donx27t overestimate the usersx27 capabilities when you plan your document management system.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI believe there exist big and powerful commercial solutions for all of this, as well. Ix27m sure if you have enough kilodollars, you can get something that fits your needs perfectly. Document management systems are a big business for big enterprise.x3C/px3E',36,0,'2008-08-27 16:27:06'),(30310,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EOOP x3Cemx3Ehasx3C/emx3E reduced costs, and increased efficiency.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen I made the jump from classic ASP/VBScript to C# I noticed a HUGE increase in productivity thanks to OOP.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 19:57:02'),(30310,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EIx27m using Subsonicx27s migrations mechanism so I just have a dll with classes in squential order that have 2 methods, up and down. There is a continuous integration/build script hook into nant, so that I can automate the upgrading of my database.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIts not the best thign in the world, but it beats writing DDL.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 21:39:20'),(30310,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EIf you are looking to find out which dllx27s your target machine is missing then use depends.exe which used to come with MSDev, but can also be found x3Ca href=x22http://dependencywalker.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E. Testing this on a few target machines should tell you which dllx27s you need to package with your application.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-07 10:40:28'),(30430,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EAt my last place of work they wouldnx27t let me set up a wiki or anything - so I just made various word documents full of tips and instructions and gave that to my successor when I left.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow though Ix27d use a private wiki, or maybe a blog.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 16:50:05'),(30430,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EI beg to differ, there is ALWAYS another way..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd if you really x3Cemx3Ecannotx3C/emx3E refactor, then you need to break the problem down into smaller parts.. Like I said, establish which dimensions you need to sum, then hit them one at a time..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, stop changing the edits, they are correcting your spelling errors, they are trying to help you ;)x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:13:10'),(30430,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EA word of caution - donx27t attempt to match dotted files (like x3Ccodex3E.htaccessx3C/codex3E) with x3Ccodex3E.*x3C/codex3E - this inconveniently also matches x3Ccodex3E..x3C/codex3E, and would result in copying all the files on the path to the root directory. I did this once (with x3Ccodex3Ermx3C/codex3E, no less!) and I had to rebuild the server because Ix27d messed with x3Ccodex3E/varx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E@jwmittag:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI just did a test on Ubuntu and x3Ccodex3E.*x3C/codex3E matches when I use x3Ccodex3Ecpx3C/codex3E. Herex27s an example:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eroot@krash:/# mkdir a\nroot@krash:/# mkdir b\nroot@krash:/# mkdir a/c\nroot@krash:/# touch a/d\nroot@krash:/# touch a/c/e\nroot@krash:/# cp -r a/c/.* b\ncp: will not create hard link `b/cx27 to directory `b/.x27\nroot@krash:/# ls b\nd  e\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf x3Ccodex3E.*x3C/codex3E did not match x3Ccodex3E..x3C/codex3E, then x3Ccodex3Edx3C/codex3E shouldnx27t be in x3Ccodex3Ebx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-29 05:58:20'),(30540,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EScott Hanselman has a great, updated every year or two list of tools: x3Ca href=x22http://www.hanselman.com/blog/ScottHanselmans2011UltimateDeveloperAndPowerUsersToolListForWindows.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EScott Hanselmanx27s Ultimate Developer and Power Users Tool List for Windowsx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-23 01:17:17'),(30660,'achancelier6','x3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EWinamp (I love coding with music playing in the background)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECoffeex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',14,0,'2008-08-23 01:30:37'),(30660,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EJust to check, if you use x3Cstrongx3Ejustx3C/strongx3E this part you get an error?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;?php\ninclude(x22../includes/connect.phpx22);\n\n$query = x22SELECT * from storyx22;\n$result = mysql_query($query) or die(mysql_error());\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf so, do you still get an error if you copy and paste one of those Inserts into this page, I am trying to see if itx27s local to the page or that actual line.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, can you post a copy of the connection calls (minus passwords), unless the inserts use exactly the same syntax as this example.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 01:52:44'),(30660,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EFlash is usually the product of choice: Everyone has it, and using the x3Ca href=x22http://www.jeroenwijering.com/?item=JW_FLV_Media_Playerx22x3EJW FLV Playerx3C/ax3E makes it relatively easy on your side.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for other Video Formats, there are WMV and QuickTime, but the players are rather x22heavyx22, not everyone might have them and they feel so 1990ish...x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EReal Player... Donx27t let me even start ranting about that pile of ...x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe only other alternative of Flash that I would personally consider is Silverlight, which allows streaming WMV Videos. I found the production of WMV much better and easier than FLV because all Windows FLV Encoders I tried are not really good and stable, whereas pretty much every tool can natively output WMV. The problem with Silverlight is that no one has that Browser Plugin (yet?). There is also a player x3Ca href=x22http://www.jeroenwijering.com/?item=JW_WMV_Playerx22x3Efrom JWx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-05 20:44:43'),(30660,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://office.microsoft.com/en-us/sharepointtechnology/default.aspxx22x3ESharepointx3C/ax3E also does a good (ok decent) job of versioning MS-specific documents.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-27 16:19:31'),(30710,'osilley7','x3Cpx3ELINQ is not just an ORM system, as Jonathan pointed out it brings a lot of functional programming elements to C#. And it lets you do a lot of x22database-yx22 things in regular C# code. Itx27s difficult to explain just how incredibly powerful that can be. Consider how much having solid, well designed generic data structures (such as list, stack, dictionary/hash, etc.) included in common frameworks has improved the state of development in modern languages. Precisely because using these data structures is very common and reducing the intellectual overhead of using them is a huge benefit. LINQ doesnx27t do anything you canx27t do yourself, but it makes a lot of operations a lot more straightforward and a lot easier.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EConsider the time-honored example of removing duplicates from a non-ordered list. In a lower level language like C or C++ youx27d probably have to sort the list and maintain two indices into the list as you removed dupes. In a language with hashes (Java, C#, Javascript, Perl, etc.) you could create a hash where the keys are the unique values, then extract the keys into a new list. With LINQ you could just do this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eint[] data = { 0, 1, 3, 3, 7, 8, 0, 9, 2, 1 };\n\nvar uniqueData = data.GroupBy(i =x26gt; i).Select(g =x26gt; g.Key);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',5,0,'2008-08-22 03:20:41'),(30770,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EYou might wanna check out x3Ca href=x22http://books.google.com/books?id=7dlaMs0SECsCx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDomain Driven Designx3C/ax3E, by Eric Evans. DDD has this notion of  a Specification:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3E... explicit predicate-like VALUE\n\n  OBJECTS for specialized purposes. A\n\n  SPECIFICATION is a predicate that\n\n  determines if an object does or does\n\n  not satisfy some criteria.x3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI think failing fast is one thing, the other is where to keep the logic for validation. The domain is the right place to keep the logic and I think a Specification Object or a validate method on your Domain objects would be a good place.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 00:03:46'),(30770,'rdowdellz','x3Cpx3EMy standard strategy for normal x22utilityx22 boxes is to give them a swap partition twice the size of their RAM, a 1GB /boot partition and leave the rest as one vast partition.  Whilst I see why some people want a separate /var, separate /home, etc., if I only have trusted users and Ix27m not running some production service, I donx27t think the reasons Ix27ve heard to date apply.  Instead, I do my best to avoid any resizing, or any partition becoming too small - which is best achieved with one huge partition.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for the size of swap and /boot - if your machine has 4GB memory, you may not want to have double that in swap.  Itx27s nonetheless wise to at least have some.  Even if you nonetheless have double, youx27re using a total of 9GB, for 0.9% of your new drive.  /boot can be smaller than 1GB, this is just my standard x22will not become full, everx22 size.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 01:58:12'),(30790,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3Ein 1.x there used to be things DataTables couldnx27t do which DataSets could (donx27t remember exactly what). All that was changed in 2.x.  My guess is thatx27s why a lot of examples still use DataSets.  DataTables should be quicker as they are more lightweight. If youx27re only pulling a single resultset, its your best choice between the two.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-05 17:10:26'),(30790,'enewberryf','x3Ch1x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.digitalmars.com/d/2.0/template-comparison.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ED Templates: Functionalx3C/ax3Ex3C/h1x3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Etemplate factorial(int n : 1)\n{\n  const factorial = 1;\n}\n\ntemplate factorial(int n)\n{\n  const factorial =\n     n * factorial!(n-1);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eor x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Etemplate factorial(int n)\n{\n  static if(n == 1)\n    const factorial = 1;\n  else \n    const factorial =\n       n * factorial!(n-1);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUsed like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efactorial!(5)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',7,0,'2008-08-23 19:22:08'),(30790,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EI would just use one input box. The x22Confirmx22 input is a remnant form the x22Confirm Passwordx22 method. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWith passwords, this is useful because they are usually typed as little circles. So, you canx27t just look at it to make sure that you typed it correctly. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EWith a regular text box, you can visually check your input. So, there is no need for a confirmation input box.x3C/px3E',12,0,'2008-08-07 20:00:04'),(30790,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3Ex22Even if there is no actual [information architecture], it doesn’t mean we don’t experience or perceive it as such. Zen Buddhists say there is no actual “self” but they still name their kids.x22-Andrew Hintonx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 19:11:50'),(30800,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EI would suggest cleaning up the mess and changing the column to a datetime because doing stuff like thisx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EWHERE datediff(dd, convert(datetime, lastUpdate), getDate()) x26lt; 31\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ecannot use an index and it will be many times slower than if you had a datetime colum,n and didx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhere lastUpdate x26gt; getDate() -31\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou also need to take into account hours and seconds of coursex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:12:26'),(30940,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3ECan you give us some more information on how you add the combo boxes to the JPanel?  This is a pretty common thing to do in Swing so I doubt that itx27s a JVM issue but I guess anything is possible.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESpecifically, I would double check to make sure youx27re not accessing the GUI from any background threads.  In this case, maybe youx27re reading the choices from a DB or something and updating the JComboBox from a background thread, which is a big no-no in Swing.  See SwingUtils.invokeLater().x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-21 23:30:02'),(31090,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EMy current toy project uses dynamic_cast twice; once to work around the lack of multiple dispatch in C++ (itx27s a visitor-style system that could use multiple dispatch instead of the dynamic_casts), and once to special-case a specific subtype.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBoth of these are acceptable, in my view, though the former at least stems from a language deficit.  I think this may be a common situation, in fact; most dynamic_casts (and a great many x22design patternsx22 in general) are workarounds for specific language flaws rather than something that aim for.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 17:55:34'),(31090,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EI recommend the Java based x3Ca href=x22http://wicket.apache.org/x22x3EWicketx3C/ax3E Framework. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s a component based MVC library which is really easy to use and allows to do all the view stuff in the java code (in contrast to using JSPs or templates or whatever in other frameworks).x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-24 21:21:15'),(31090,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EI am a big fan of Embarcaderox27s x3Ca href=x22http://www.embarcadero.com/products/er-studiox22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EER/Studiox3C/ax3E.  It is very powerful and produces excellent on-screen as well as printed results.  They have a free trial as well, so you should be able to get in and give it a shot without too much strife.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGood luck!x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 03:36:58'),(31090,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3ETake a look at x3Ca href=x22http://www.danga.com/memcached/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ememcachedx3C/ax3E.  It is a really cool, fast and lightweight distributed caching system.  There are APIs for several of the most popular languages, including C#.  It may not serve well on the client side (unless of course the client is obtaining the cached data from a server of some kind), but if you abstract your usage of memcached to a specific interface, you could then implement the interface with another caching system.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 10:21:15'),(31140,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EC++x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efactorial(int n)\n{\n    for(int i=1, f = 1; ix26lt;=n; i++)\n        f *= i;\n    return f;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 08:27:12'),(31140,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EGo as deep as you can starting off in one environment, win32, .net, Java, Objective C... whatever.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt is important to build the deep understanding of how X works... so that you can translate the same concepts into other languages or platforms/environments, if you so desire.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex22Are there any areas of specialization that hinder your ability of developing other areas of specialization.x22  Sort of, but nothing permanent i think.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESince I am relatively green myself (less than 4 years) I come from a really OOP mindset.  Ix27ve rarely jumped out of .NET, so I had a hard time on one job when coming into contact with embedded code.  With embedded programmers fearing object creation and the performance loss of inheritance.  I had to learn the environment, seriously low memory and slow clock times, they were coming from.  Those are times to grow, I had a better time at it because i understood my area pretty well.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI will say if you pick something to specialize in for marketability and money, you will probably burn out fast.  If you do start to specialize pick something you enjoy.  I love GUI programing and hate server side stuff, my buddy is the opposite, but we both love our jobs.  If he had to do my job, and I his, we would both go insane out of boredom.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 12:29:15'),(31140,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EWhen I wrote my first trigger it was in Perl because that was the language used in the example I found but the last triggers I wrote where in Python because Ix27m more comfortable with that.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI think programmer comfort is my main reason to choose python but I think Perl is still better supported.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 10:43:30'),(31200,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EFirst: Yes, this is something that belongs in the Application for the exact reson you specified: What happens after new user profiles are created? Sure, if youx27re using a domain itx27s possible to have some stuff put in the registry on creation, but this is not really a use case. The Application should check if there are seetings and use the default settings if not.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThat being said, it IS possible to change other users Keys through the HKEY_USERS Hive.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI have no experience with the Visual Studio 2003 Setup Project, so here is a bit of (totally unrelated) VBScript code that might just give you an idea where to look:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Econst HKEY_USERS = x26amp;H80000003x3Cbrx3EstrComputer = x22.x22x3Cbrx3ESet objReg=GetObject(x22winmgmts:{impersonationLevel=impersonate}!\\\\x22 x26amp; strComputer x26amp; x22\\root\\default:StdRegProvx22)x3Cbrx3EstrKeyPath = x22x22x3Cbrx3EobjReg.EnumKey HKEY_USERS, strKeyPath, arrSubKeysx3Cbrx3EstrKeyPath = x22\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\WinTrust\\Trust Providers\\Software Publishingx22x3Cbrx3EFor Each subkey In arrSubKeysx3Cbrx3E    objReg.SetDWORDValue HKEY_USERS, subkey x26amp; strKeyPath, x22Statex22, 146944x3Cbrx3ENextx3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3E(Code Courtesy of x3Ca href=x22http://jritmeijer.spaces.live.com/blog/cns%218A48A27460FB898A%21965.entryx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EJeroen Ritmeijerx3C/ax3E)x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-04 00:48:47'),(31320,'rmaccurlyer','x3CPx3EYou need to set the run-time library (Under C/C++ -x26gt; Code Generation) for ALL projects to static linkage, which correlates to the following default building configurations:x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CULx3E\n\nx3CLIx3EMultithreaded Debug/Releasex3C/LIx3E\n\nx3CLIx3ESinglethreaded Debug/Releasex3C/LIx3Ex3C/ULx3E\n\nx3CPx3EAs opposed to the x22DLLx22 versions of those libraries.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EEven if you do that, depending on the libraries youx27re using, you might have to install a Merge Module/framework/etc. It depends on whether static LIB versions of your dependencies are available.x3C/Px3E',10,0,'2008-08-08 01:11:52'),(31320,'srm9547','x3Cpx3ESimply move your code into an Excel Addin (XLA) - this gets loaded at startup (assuming itx27s in the %AppData%\\Microsoft\\Excel\\XLSTART folder) but if itx27s a addin, not a workbook, then only your macros and defined startup functions will be loaded.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf the functions depend on a spreadsheet itself, then you might want to use a combination of templates and addins.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m distributing part of an application like this, we have addins for Word, Excel and Powerpoint (XLA, PPA, DOT) and also Office 2007 x27ribbonx27 versions (DOTM, XLAM and PPAM)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe addin startup code creates toolbar buttons if theyx27re not found, this means in any workbook/document/etc they can simply hit the toolbar button to run our code (we have two action buttons and one button that displays a settings dialog)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETemplates arenx27t really the way to go for VBA code, Addins are definitely the way to go...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo to load the toolbars on startup wex27re using something like.. (checking to see if toolbar exists though - code will run for each worksheet that is opened, but toolbars are persistent for the user session)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EPublic Sub Workbook_Open()\n     x27 startup code / add toolbar / load saved settings, etc.\nEnd Sub\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ehope that helps :)x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-27 13:22:20'),(31320,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EI would agree with Leex27s advice for taking parameters, but not returning.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you specify your methods to return an interface that means you are free to change the exact implementation later on without the consuming method ever knowing. I thought Ix27d never need to change from a Listx26lt;Tx3E but had to later change to use a custom list library for the extra functionality it provided. Because Ix27d only returned an IListx26lt;Tx3E none of the people that used the library had to change their code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOf course that only need apply to methods that are externally visible (i.e. public methods). I personally use interfaces even in internal code, but as you are able to change all the code yourself if you make breaking changes itx27s not strictly necessary.x3C/px3E',19,0,'2008-08-20 13:12:08'),(31340,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EI would be a bit reluctant to use nested classes here.  What if you created an abstract base class for a x22multimedia driverx22 to handle the back-end stuff (workhorse), and a separate class for the front-end work?  The front-end class could take a pointer/reference to an implemented driver class (for the appropriate media type and situation) and perform the abstract operations on the workhorse structure.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMy philosophy would be to go ahead and make both structures accessible to the client in a polished way, just under the assumption they would be used in tandem.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would reference something like a x3Ca href=x22http://qt-project.org/doc/qt-4.8/qtextdocument.htmlx22x3EQTextDocumentx3C/ax3E in Qt.  You provide a direct interface to the bare metal data handling, but pass the authority along to an object like a QTextEdit to do the manipulation.x3C/px3E',19,0,'2008-08-02 07:00:24'),(31340,'sdally1','x3Cpx3EKomodo Edit, Cygwin (ssh, cat, less, sed, grep, etc.), Python, TortoiseSVN, TortoiseCVSx3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 01:15:12'),(31480,'aa9279','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.runtime.compilerservices.runtimehelpers.gethashcode.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERuntimeHelpers.GetHashCodex3C/ax3E might help:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EFrom Msdn:x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EServes as a hash function for a\n  particular type, suitable for use in\n  hashing algorithms and data structures\n  such as a hash table.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E',-1,0,'2008-08-20 06:32:20'),(31480,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://svnbook.red-bean.com/x22x3EVersion Control with Subversionx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EA very good resource for source control in general. Not really TortoiseSVN specific, though.x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-01 18:45:37'),(31500,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EI use x3Ca href=x22https://github.com/unittest-cppx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EUnitTest++x3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn the years since I made this post the source has moved from SourceForge to github.  Also the x3Ca href=x22https://github.com/unittest-cpp/unittest-cpp/wiki/Writing-More-Tests-With-the-Bowling-Game-Katax22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eexample tutorialx3C/ax3E is now more agnostic - doesnx27t go into any configuration or project set up at all.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI doubt it will still work for Visual Studio 6 as the project files are now created via CMake. If you still need the older version support you can get the last available version under the x3Ca href=x22https://github.com/unittest-cpp/unittest-cpp/tree/sourceforgex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESourceForgex3C/ax3E branch.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-06 12:28:14'),(31790,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EHonestly, with 8 objects max and 8 properties max per object, your best bet is to just traverse each object and make the comparisons directly.  Itx27ll be fast and itx27ll be easy.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re going to be using these types of comparisons often, then I agree with Jason about JSON serialization...but otherwise therex27s no need to slow down your app with a new library or JSON serialization code.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-26 16:52:12'),(31800,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EWhen Management Studio does it, itx27s creating a temporary table, copying everything across, dropping your original table and renaming the temporary table.  Therex27s no simple equivalent T-SQL statement.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you donx27t fancy doing that, you could always create a view of the table with the columns in the order youx27d like and use that?x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: beaten!x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-05 02:00:53'),(31800,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3EBlog about it. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOne of the nice side-effects of blogging is that if you use a sensible categorization or tagging system, itx27s quite easy to search for stuff within your blog. The fact that you wrote about it also makes it easier to remember problems you have encountered before (x22hey, I blogged about that!x22).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThatx27s a great benefit aside from, of course, being able to share this information publicly so that others might be able to find your solution to a particular problem using Google.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 15:36:17'),(31800,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EI think the only fool proof way would be to extend the Visual Studio (through VSIP) and subscribe to the correct event (maybe in the EnvDTE.BuildEvents) class, and check your code for usage of the constructor, and cancel the build if you detect it.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 02:26:13'),(31930,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EThe problem with leading Wildcards: They cannot be indexed, hence youx27re doing a full table scan.x3C/px3E',12,0,'2008-08-06 18:07:59'),(32000,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3ETherex27s no empirical evidence that suggests that object orientation is a more natural way for people to think about the world. Therex27s some work in the field of psychology of programming that shows that OO is not somehow more fitting than other approaches.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EObject-oriented representations do not appear to be universally more usable or less usable.x3C/px3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EIt is not enough to simply adopt OO methods and require developers to use such methods, because that might have a negative impact on developer productivity, as well as the quality of systems developed.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhich is from x22On the Usability of OO Representationsx22 from Communications of the ACM Oct. 2000. The articles mainly compares OO against theprocess-oriented approach. Therex27s lots of study of how people who work with the OO method x22thinkx22 (Int. J. of Human-Computer Studies 2001, issue 54, or Human-Computer Interaction 1995, vol. 10 has a whole theme on OO studies), and from what I read, therex27s nothing to indicate some kind of naturalness to the OO approach that makes it better suited than a more traditional procedural approach.x3C/px3E',24,0,'2008-08-24 18:03:42'),(32020,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EI think that OpenID is definitely worth looking at.  Besides giving you a framework in which to provide a unified id for customers, it can also provide large businesses with the ability to manage their own logins and provide a common login across all products that they use, including your own.  This isnx27t that large of a benefit now when OpenId is still relatively rare, but as more products begin to use it, I suspect that the ability to use a common company OpenId login for each employee could become a good selling point.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ESince youx27re mostly catering to businesses, I donx27t think that itx27s all that unreasonable to offer to host the OpenId accounts yourself.  I just think that the extra flexibility will benefit your customers.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 19:48:06'),(32020,'hbuxcy1c','x3CPx3EIf I understand your question, you want to affect what columns are returned first, second, third, etc in x3CSTRONGx3Eexistingx3C/STRONGx3E queries, right?x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIf all of your queries are written with SELECT * FROM TABLE - then they will show up in the output as they are layed out in SQL. If your queries are written with SELECT Field1, Field2 FROM TABLE - then the order they are layed out in SQL does not matter.x3C/Px3E',3,0,'2008-08-06 19:42:19'),(32100,'prihak','x3Cpx3ESometimes the easiest way to get input from people is to force it out of them.  My company used SCRUM on a project, and found very quickly that people tend to keep to themselves when they already know what theyx27re doing.  We ended up organizing weekly meetings where team members were required to display something that was learned during the week.  It was forced, but it worked pretty well.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 22:58:52'),(32260,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EYour problem could be that youx27re not actually overriding Autosize in your code (ie, in the same way that youx27re overriding Font or ForeColor).x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 21:38:53'),(32280,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EGenerally, I follow this rule:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E1) Make it a class if multiple parts of your application use the data structure.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E2) Make it a 2D array if youx27re using it for quick processing of data in one part of your application.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 14:56:10'),(32280,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EIt depends exactly what you mean by x27betterx27. Ix27d go for the object oriented way (using classes) because I find it makes for cleaner code (at least in my opinion). However, Ix27m not sure what the speed penalties might be for that option.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 14:42:51'),(32280,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3ENotepad++ for surex3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-23 01:11:05'),(32540,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EActually Windows XP tries to avoid that. Of course some programs found a way to x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/18505/sending-a-mouse-click-to-a-button-in-the-taskbar-using-cx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ecircumventedx3C/ax3E that. Microsoft Powertoy TweakUI has a way to turn the option on again in case it was turned off. You could also edit the registry yourself using the x3Ca href=x22http://xphelpandsupport.mvps.org/how_do_i_prevent_applications_fr.htmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Efollowing informationx3C/ax3E. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 00:52:56'),(32550,'abaterb','x3Cpx3ERequest.Url will return you the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.uri.aspxx22x3EUrix3C/ax3E of the request.  Once you have that, you can retrieve pretty much anything you want.  To get the protocol, call the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.uri.scheme.aspxx22x3ESchemex3C/ax3E property.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESample:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EUri url = Request.Url;\nstring protocol = url.Scheme;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope this helps.x3C/px3E',18,0,'2008-08-22 06:48:54'),(32640,'mlowried','x3Ch1x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://blogs.technet.com/markrussinovich/archive/2008/07/21/3092070.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELinkx3C/ax3Ex3C/h1x3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cimg src=x22http://i.stack.imgur.com/BLf9j.pngx22 alt=x2264 processors 2tb ramx22x3Ex3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-29 04:24:22'),(32780,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EHonestly it depends on what fits in to your environment better.  If you are using a lot of Non-Microsoft tools, nunit, ccnet, ncover.  You will probably find better support with nant.  Alternatively if you are using MSTest, TFSBuild, you will probably find MSBuild a better environment.  I would learn both and use which every fits more smoothly with your environment.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-04 19:37:31'),(32790,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3ECreate an FxCop rule, and add FxCop to your integration build in order to check for this.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYoux27ll get warnings, rather than a failing build.  Attributes x27runx27 at reflection time rather than build time.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlternatively (and this is rather nasty) put a compiler directive around the method you donx27t want to be called. Then your code will break if you call it, but you can set up a build that passes the right compiler directive and doesnx27t.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:51:54'),(32930,'sdally1','x3Cpx3ENot necessarily. It depends on how often the new files are committed to the repo. If the files are edited several times before a commit, then youx27re precisely where you are now. The biggest benefit is if the file becomes corrupted.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can version any file; this is how Time Machine in Mac OS X Leopard works, for example, and there is an interesting article by someone who committed his entire computing environment into CVS and then just maintained working copies on his home and work machines.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBut x22betterx22 and x22easierx22 are specific to your situation, and Ix27m not sure I completely understand your problem as things stand.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 13:51:00'),(33150,'achancelier6','x3CPx3EI would be pushing hard for the N tiered approach even if itx27s a small project. If you use an ORM tool like codesmith + nettiers you will be able to quickly setup the projects and be developing code that solves your business problems quickly.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIt kills me when you start a new project and you spend days sitting around spinning wheels talking about how the x22architecturex22 should be architected. You want to be spending time solving the business problem, not solving problems that other people have solved for you. Using an ORM (it doesnx27t really matter which one, just pick one and stick to it) to help you get initial traction will help keep you focussed on the goals of the project and not distract you trying to solve x22architecturex22 issues.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIf, at the end of the day, the architect wants to go the one project approach, there is no reason you canx27t create an app_code folder with a BLL and DAL folder to seperate the code for now which will help you move to an N-Tiered solution later.x3C/Px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 17:18:38'),(33150,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EYou might be able to use IronRuby for that. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOtherwise Ix27d suggest you have a directory where you place precompiled assemblies. Then you could have a reference in the DB to the assembly and class, and use reflection to load the proper assemblies at runtime.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you really want to compile at run-time you could use the CodeDOM, then you could use reflection to load the dynamic assembly. x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/microsoft.csharp.csharpcodeprovider.aspxx22x3EMSDN article which might helpx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-02 08:18:15'),(33250,'rtomeo0','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EWouldnx27t the isdate() check take care of this?x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERun this to see what happensx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect isdate(x2720080131x27)\nselect isdate(x2701312008x27)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 18:27:31'),(33390,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EA good editor and your compiler of choice.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESure, some tools make your job a little easier.  Developing .Net applications without using Visual Studio would be more convoluted, but I would bet that at the end of the task, using only a text editor and the csc compiler, you would have a guru like comprehension of the language in no time at all.  You would learn things that other people may never get into.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOf course, a good debugger helps (Also built into VS).  I use Komodo for Perl development purely for the debugging tools involved.  Even though I still prefer to edit the code using e-TextEditor.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 01:18:41'),(33390,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EFrom the perspective of having the most maintainable code, I think you should do as much validation as you can in the setter of a property. This way you wonx27t be caching or otherwise dealing with invalid data.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAfter all, this is what properties are meant for. If all you have is a bunch of properties like...x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic string Name\n\n{\n\n    get\n\n    {\n\n        return _name;\n\n    }\n\n    set\n\n    {\n\n        _name = value;\n\n    }\n\n}\n\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3E... they might as well be fieldsx3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 23:59:05'),(33510,'gdodding5','x3Cpx3EIx27ve had surprising success using x3Ca href=x22http://drupal.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDrupalx3C/ax3E as a web app framework.  Itx27s highly extensible - pretty much every default behaviour can be overridden easily via modules, and itx27s a pretty blank slate to start with as well.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDrupal 7 has x3Ca href=x22http://drupal.org/project/simpletestx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eunit testing built-in, and earlier versions can do it easily via a pluginx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-24 21:55:44'),(33550,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EAnother advantage of Flex development is that you can switch to developing desktop applications (Adobe AIR) with the same source code (and same IDE) and distribute them from web. You can check out x3Ca href=x22http://labs.adobe.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E\n for the future of Flash platform.\nx3Cbrx3E\nUpdate Q3/2011: Flash 11 supports low-level 3D acceleration, and there are already many frameworks and major engines (Unreal Engine 3, Unity) supporting it. The selling point for the future, however, is that AIR application will work on Windows, Mac, Android, Playbook, and iOS platforms (Linux support has been dropped). With an absolute minimum of hassle between porting between those (at least when you have Adobe CS5.5+).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUpdate Q2/2015: Silverlight is officially dead. Adobe AIR is alive, but not thriving - it might be useful based on your skills and tool chain. Both Microsoft and Adobe admit that HTML5 is the way to go (whether with AIR or Apache Cordova or Visual Studio).x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-24 20:46:51'),(33590,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EDoes the apache user require a password to connect to the database?  If so, then the fact that it says x22using password: NOx22 would lead me to believe that the code is trying to connect without a password.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf, however, the apache user doesnx27t require a password, a double-check of the permissions may be a good idea (which you mentioned you already checked).  It may still be beneficial to try executing something like this at a mysql prompt:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3EGRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ONx3C/codex3E x3Cemx3Edatabasenamex3C/emx3Ex3Ccodex3E.* to x27apachex27@x27localhostx27;x3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThat syntax should be correct.  x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOther than that, Ix27m just as stumped as you are.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-06 01:56:20'),(33630,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIt really depends on what youx27re trying to do, exactly, as itx27s:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EOS dependentx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ENot quite clear what youx27re trying to do.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENevertheless, Ix27ll try to provide some information for you to decide.x3Cbr /x3E\nOn UNIX, x3Ccodex3Efork()x3C/codex3E creates a clone of your process from the place where you called fork. Meaning, if I have the following process:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#include x26lt;unistd.hx26gt;\n#include x26lt;stdio.hx26gt;\n\nint main()\n{\n    printf( x22hi 2 u\\nx22 );\n    int mypid = fork();\n\n    if( 0 == mypid )\n        printf( x22lol child\\nx22 );\n    else\n        printf( x22lol parent\\nx22 );\n\n    return( 0 );\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe output will look as follows:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cblockquotex3E\n    x3Cpx3Ehi 2 ux3Cbr /x3E\n    lol childx3Cbr /x3E\n    lol parent  x3C/px3E\n  x3C/blockquotex3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen you x3Ccodex3Efork()x3C/codex3E the pid returned in the child is 0, and the pid returned in the parent is the childx27s pid. Notice that x22hi2ux22 is only printed once... by the x3Cstrongx3Eparentx3C/strongx3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3Eexecve()x3C/codex3E and its family of functions are almost always used with x3Ccodex3Efork().x3C/codex3E x3Ccodex3Eexecve()x3C/codex3E and the like overwrite the current stackframe with the name of the application you pass to it. x3Ccodex3Eexecve()x3C/codex3E is almost always used with x3Ccodex3Efork()x3C/codex3E where you fork a child process and if youx27re the parent you do whatever you need to keep doing and if youx27re the child you exec a new process. x3Ccodex3Eexecve()x3C/codex3E is also almost always used with x3Ccodex3Ewaitpid()x3C/codex3E -- waitpid takes a pid of a child process and, quite literally, x3Cemx3Ewaitsx3C/emx3E until the child terminates and returns the childx27s exit status to you.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUsing this information, you should be able to write a very basic shell; one that takes process names on the command line and runs processes you tell it to. Of course, shells do more than that, like piping input and output, but you should be able to accomplish the basics using x3Ccodex3Efork()x3C/codex3E, x3Ccodex3Eexecve()x3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3Ewaitpid()x3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3ENOTE: This is *nix specific! This will NOT work on Windows.x3C/strongx3E  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope this helped.x3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-21 22:44:38'),(33720,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EExecutive summary:  Yes, if your database has a message queue service.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can push a message onto a queue and the queue processor will consume it asynchronously.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EOracle: queuesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ESql Server: service brokerx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDB2: event brokerx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor x22purex22 stored procedure languages (PL/Sql or T-Sql) the answer is no, since it works against the fundamental transaction model most databases have.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, if your database has a queuing mechanism, you can use that to get the same result.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-25 04:34:44'),(33790,'idevey11','x3CPx3EWithin your overridden ProcessCmdKey how are you determining which key has been pressed?x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EThe value of keyData (the second parameter) will change dependant on the key pressed and any modifier keys, so, for example, pressing the left arrow will return code 37, shift-left will return 65573, ctrl-left 131109 and alt-left 262181.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EYou can extract the modifiers and the key pressed by ANDing with appropriate enum values:x3C/Px3Ex3CPREx3Ex3CCODEx3Eprotected override bool ProcessCmdKey(ref Message msg, Keys keyData)\n\n{\n\n    bool shiftPressed = (keyData x26amp; Keys.Shift) != 0;\n\n    Keys unmodifiedKey = (keyData x26amp; Keys.KeyCode);\n\n\n\n    // rest of code goes here\n\n}\n\nx3C/CODEx3Ex3C/PREx3E',10,0,'2008-08-07 21:38:05'),(33790,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EThe x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_Lesser_General_Public_Licencex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGNU Lesser General Public Licencex3C/ax3E is also corporate-friendly and quite often used in libraries. It allows for x3Cemx3Eusagex3C/emx3E of a certain library but modifications to it should be made public.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-26 20:35:53'),(33860,'astarmoreq','x3CPx3EIf you have a fixed set of columns and you know what they are, you can basically do a series of subselects x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Ex3CCODEx3E(SELECT Column1 AS ResultA FROM TableA) as R1x3C/CODEx3E x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3Eand join the subselects. All this in a single query.x3C/Px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 18:41:29'),(33960,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEMAIL ADDRESSx3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ERationalx3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Colx3E\n\nx3Clix3EUsers donx27t change emails very oftenx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3ERemoves the step of asking for username and email address, which youx27ll need anywayx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EUsers donx27t often forget their email address (see number one)x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EEmail will be unique unless the user already registered for the site, in which case forward them to a forgot your password screenx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EAlmost everyone is using email as the primary login for access to a website, this means the rate of adoption shouldnx27t be affected by the fact that youx27re asking for an email addressx3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/olx3E\n\n\n\nx3Chrx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EUpdatex3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAfter registration, be sure to ask the user to create some kind of username, donx27t litter a public site with their email address! Also, another benefit of using an email address as a login: you wonx27t need any other information (like password / password confirm), just send them a temp password through the mail, or forgo passwords altogether and send them a one-use URL to their email address every time theyx27d like to login (see: x3Ca href=x22http://mugshot.org/mainx22x3Emugshot.orgx3C/ax3E)x3C/px3E',41,0,'2008-08-08 19:46:12'),(33960,'prihak','x3Cpx3E@Terrapin, re:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3EIf all you have is a bunch of [simple\n\n  public set/get] properties ... they\n\n  might as well be fieldsx3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EProperties have other advantages over fields. Theyx27re a more explicit contract, theyx27re  serialized, they can be debugged later, theyx27re a nice place for extension through inheritance. The clunkier syntax is an accidental complexity -- .net 3.5 for example overcomes this.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EA common (and flawed) practice is to start with public fields, and turn them into properties later, on an x27as neededx27 basis. This breaks your contract with anyone who consumes your class, so itx27s best to start with properties.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-08 04:07:08'),(33990,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EOne option is to use serialization. Herex27s a blog post explaining it:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://weblogs.java.net/blog/emcmanus/archive/2007/04/cloning_java_ob.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://weblogs.java.net/blog/emcmanus/archive/2007/04/cloning_java_ob.htmlx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 13:52:10'),(33990,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EIn my company, we are currently using Qt and are very happy with it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI personnally never had to move a MFC-app into using the Qt framework, but here is something which might be of some interest for you :x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrikex3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.qtsoftware.com/products/appdev/add-on-products/catalog/3/Windows/qtwinmigrate/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EQt/MFC Migration Frameworkx3C/ax3Ex3C/strikex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://doc.qt.nokia.com/solutions/4/qtwinmigrate/index.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EQt/MFC Migration Frameworkx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EItx27s part of Qt-Solutions, so this means youx27ll have to buy a Qt license along with a Qt-Solutions license. (edit: x3Ca href=x22http://www.qtsoftware.com/about/news/lgpl-license-option-added-to-qtx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Enot any morex3C/ax3E)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI hope this helps !x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-26 15:50:35'),(33990,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EIx27d suggest you try Subversion, for example with the x3Ca href=x22http://svn1clicksetup.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E1-click SVN installerx3C/ax3E. Try searching SO for x22Subversionx22, and youx27ll find loads of questions with answers that point to good tutorials.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EGood luck!x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-22 23:53:08'),(34020,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EOne consideration would be whether video playback is via progressive download or streaming. If itx27s progressive download, then I would say use Flash because you get a wider audience reach.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor streaming wmv, it is out of the box functionality provided by x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windowsmedia/forpros/server/server.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWindows Media Servicesx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor streaming flash, you will have to install a streaming server on your Windows box. Some options are:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.adobe.com/products/flashmediaserverx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EAdobe Flash Media Serverx3C/ax3E (Commercial)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.wowzamedia.com/products.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWowza Media Serverx3C/ax3E (Free/Commercial) x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://osflash.org/red5x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERed5 Flash Serverx3C/ax3E (Open Source)x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 00:03:56'),(34020,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3EWe are using FindBugs and Checkstyle as well as Clover for Code Coverage. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI think itx27s important to have some kind of static analysis, supporting your development. Unfortunately itx27s still not widely spread that these tools are important.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-07 11:21:49'),(34020,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EWell, for your sample and any with a limited number of unique columns, this should do it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect \n    distinct a,\n    (select distinct t2.b  from t t2  where t1.a=t2.a and t2.b=x27VIEWx27),\n    (select distinct t2.b from t t2  where t1.a=t2.a and t2.b=x27EDITx27)\nfrom t t1\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',5,0,'2008-08-23 23:44:24'),(34120,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EXcode has refactoring for C and Objective-C built in.  Just select what youx27d like to refactor, choose x22Refactor...x22 from either the menu bar or the contextual menu, and youx27ll get a window including the available refactorings and a preview area.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EXcode doesnx27t currently have a public plug-in API; if there are specific types of plug-ins youx27d like Apple to enable, file enhancement requests in the x3Ca href=x22http://bugreport.apple.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Bug Reporter - itx27s not just for bugs!x22x3EBug Reporterx3C/ax3E.  That way Apple can count and track such requests.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, there are third-party tools like x3Ca href=x22http://www.kevincallahan.org/software/accessorizer.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Accessorizerx22x3EAccessorizerx3C/ax3E and x3Ca href=x22http://rentzsch.com/code/mogeneratorx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22mogenerator: Core Data codegenx22x3Ex3Ccodex3Emogeneratorx3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E (the latest release is x3Ca href=x22http://rentzsch.com/code/mogenerator_v1.10x22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22mogenerator 1.10x22x3Ex3Ccodex3Emogenerator 1.10x3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E) that you can use to make various development tasks faster.  Accessorizer helps you create accessor methods for your classes, while x3Ccodex3Emogeneratorx3C/codex3E does more advanced code generation for Core Data managed object classes that are modeled using Xcodex27s modeling tools.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-22 00:04:09'),(34270,'clawrence3','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EIs there a way to open file in a non-exclusive way,x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYes, using Win32, passing the various FILE_SHARE_Xxxx flags to CreateFile.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Eis it cross platform?x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENo, it requires platform-specific code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDue to annoying backwards compatibility concerns (DOS applications, being single-tasking, assume that nothing can delete a file out from under them, i.e. that they can fclose() and then fopen() without anything going amiss; Win16 preserved this assumption to make porting DOS applications easier, Win32 preserved this assumption to make porting Win16 applications easier, and itx27s awful), Windows defaults to opening files exclusively.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe underlying OS infrastructure supports deleting/renaming open files  (although I believe it does have the restriction that memory-mapped files cannot be deleted, which I think isnx27t a restriction found on *nix), but the default opening semantics do not.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EC++ has no notion of any of this; the C++ operating environment is much the same as the DOS operating environment--no other applications running concurrently, so no need to control file sharing.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-26 15:02:41'),(34390,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EHow about increasing the memory allocated to the server or the buffer size used by the server, if possible?x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 17:00:12'),(34390,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EYou need to go to the Active Directory Users Snap In after logging in as a domain admin on the machine:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EGo to start --x3E run and type in mmc.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EIn the MMC console go to File --x3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EAdd/Remove Snap-In Click Add Selectx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EActive Directory Users and Computers and select Add. x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EHit Close and then hit OK.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFrom here you can expand the domain tree and search (by right-clicking on the domain name).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou may not need special privileges to view the contents of the Active Directory domain, especially if you are logged in on that domain.  It is worth a shot to see how far you can get.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen you search for someone, you can select the columns from View --x3E Choose Columns.  This should help you search for the person or group you are looking for.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 02:23:50'),(34490,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EI know this is a little late in the game, but the URL mentioned for the JavaScript is mentioned in a list of sites known to have been part of the ASPRox bot resurgence that started up in June (at least thatx27s when we were getting flagged with it). Some details about it are mentioned below:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.bloombit.com/Articles/2008/05/ASCII-Encoded-Binary-String-Automated-SQL-Injection.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.bloombit.com/Articles/2008/05/ASCII-Encoded-Binary-String-Automated-SQL-Injection.aspxx3C/ax3E x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe nasty thing about this is that effectively every varchar type field in the database is x22infectedx22 to spit out a reference to this URL, in which the the browser gets an tiny iframe that turns it into a bot. A basic SQL fix for this can be found here:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://aspadvice.com/blogs/programming_shorts/archive/2008/06/27/Asprox-Recovery.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://aspadvice.com/blogs/programming_shorts/archive/2008/06/27/Asprox-Recovery.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe scary thing though is that the virus looks to the system tables for values to infect and a lot of shared hosting plans also share the database space for their clients. So most likely it wasnx27t even your dadx27s site that was infected, but somebody elsex27s site within his hosting cluster that wrote some poor code and opened the door to SQL Injection attack.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf he hasnx27t done so yet, Ix27d send an URGENT e-mail to their host and give them a link to that SQL code to fix the entire system. You can fix your own affected database tables, but most likely the bots that are doing the infection are going to pass right through that hole again and infect the whole lot.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EHopefully this gives you some more info to work with.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: One more quick thought, if hex27s using one of the hosts online design tools for building his website, all of that content is probably sitting in a column and was infected that way.x3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-08 02:49:55'),(34570,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EThe IRC Specification is laid out in RFC 1459x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.irchelp.org/irchelp/rfc/rfc.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.irchelp.org/irchelp/rfc/rfc.htmlx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-23 19:49:53'),(34570,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EOn UNIX, I think you basically need to fork it if you want the spawned process to run detached from your the spawing one : For instance if you donx27t want your spawned process to be terminate when you quit your spawning process.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.yolinux.com/TUTORIALS/ForkExecProcesses.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EHere is ax3C/ax3E page that explains all the subtle differences between Fork, System, Exec.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you work on Win,Mac and linux, I can recommend you the x3Ca href=x22https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/qprocess.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EQt Framework and its QProcess objectx3C/ax3E, but I donx27t know if thatx27s an option for you. The great advantages is that you will be able to compile the same code on windows linux and mac :x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E QString program = x22./yourspawnedprogramx22;\n QProcess * spawnedProcess = new QProcess(parent);\n spawnedProcess-x26gt;start(program);\n // or spawnedProcess-x26gt;startDetached(program);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd for extra, you can even kill the child process from the mother process,\nand keep in communication with it through a stream.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 03:47:13'),(34600,'aa9279','x3Cpx3EThis kind of thing is much easier if you use STL containers, or maybe x3Ca href=x22http://www.boost.org/libs/multi_array/doc/index.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBoost.MultiArrayx3C/ax3E. But if you must use an array:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E#include x26lt;iostreamx26gt;\n#include x26lt;boost/foreach.hppx26gt;\n#include x26lt;vectorx26gt;\n\nint sum(int x) {\n    return x;\n}\n\ntemplate x26lt;class T, unsigned Nx26gt;\nint sum(const T (x26amp;x)[N]) {\n    int r = 0;\n    for(int i = 0; i x26lt; N; ++i) {\n        r += sum(x[i]);\n    }\n    return r;\n}\n\ntemplate x26lt;class T, unsigned Nx26gt;\nstd::vectorx26lt;intx26gt; reduce(const T (x26amp;x)[N]) {\n    std::vectorx26lt;intx26gt; result;\n    for(int i = 0; i x26lt; N; ++i) {\n        result.push_back(sum(x[i]));\n    }\n    return result;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int x[][2][2] = {\n        { { 1, 2 }, { 3, 4 } },\n        { { 5, 6 }, { 7, 8 } }\n    };\n\n    BOOST_FOREACH(int v, reduce(x)) {\n        std::coutx26lt;x26lt;vx26lt;x26lt;x22\\nx22;\n    }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 00:46:19'),(34600,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI like OpenID, but Ix27d still go with the email address, unless your user community is very technically savvy. Itx27s still much easier for most people to understand and remember.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-08 19:44:12'),(34600,'clawrence3','x3Cpx3EThis is not directly an answer, butx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThe thing is that to remove the disk you have to eject the volume and in this case do it for both volumesx3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI have a similar situation.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOSX remembers where you put your icons on the desktop - Ix27ve moved the icons for both of my removable drives to x3Cemx3Ejustx3C/emx3E above where the trash can lives.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEject procedure becomesx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EHit top-left of screen with mouse to show desktopx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDrag small box around both removable drivesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDrag 2cm onto trash so they both get ejectedx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ERemove firewire cablex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 00:32:05'),(34600,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EThere is x3Ca href=x22http://209.85.135.104/search?q=cache:EzaP2dgUM9cJ:hammett.castleproject.org/%3Fp%3D114+Castle.Components.Validatorx26amp;hl=rux26amp;ct=clnkx26amp;cd=2x26amp;gl=rux26amp;client=firefox-ax22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECastle.Components.Validatorx3C/ax3E module in Castle project. Itx27s very agile and powerfull. It generates validation rules based on model attributes (or any other source) and even able to generate JS validation using jQuery, Prototype Validation, fValidate and other.\nOf course itx27s wise to abstract validator away behind IValidationEngine interface. x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 16:36:40'),(34600,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3EAny time you need a reference to the current object.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOne particularly handy scenario is when your object is calling a function and wants to pass itself into it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EExample:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evoid onChange()\n{\n    screen.draw(this);\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',11,0,'2008-08-22 23:26:37'),(35070,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EBy x22corporatex22 I tend to think of internal development, programs distributed only to people that are employed by the same company. In that sense, pretty much all free software licences are x22corporate-friendly.x22x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, in terms of distributing closed-source software that contains free software the only big one (off the top of my head) that is excluded is the GPL. You could embed LGPL, BSD, MIT, Artistic licenced code. The x22pricex22 might be having to give credit, but that would be way cheaper than actually writing and debugging the software.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThings can get hazy when you consider licences that try to protect trademarks (Mozilla) or the compatibility of a broader range of software (Sun). Your constraints are not always only related to the distribution of the code.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn summary, if youx27re unsure you should consult a lawyer.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 20:41:25'),(35070,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EOn the desktop side, Mono works great if you commit to using GTK#. The Windows.Forms implementation is still a little buggy (for example, TrayIconx27s donx27t work) but it has come a long way. Besides, GTK# is a better toolkit than Windows Forms as it is.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOn the web side, Mono has implemented enough of ASP.NET to run most sites perfectly. The difficulty here is finding a host that has mod_mono installed on apache, or doing it yourself if you have shell access to your host.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEither way, Mono is great, and stable. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EKey things to remember when creating a cross platform program:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EUse GTK# instead of Windows.Formsx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EEnsure to properly case your filenamesx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EUse x3Ccodex3EPath.Separatorx3C/codex3E instead of hardcoding x3Ccodex3Ex22\\x22x3C/codex3E, also use x3Ccodex3EEnvironment.NewLinex3C/codex3E instead of x3Ccodex3Ex22\\nx22x3C/codex3E.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDo not use any P/Invoked calls to Win32 API.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EDo not use the Windows Registry.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',37,0,'2008-08-20 22:17:32'),(35170,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EIn many cases, you can take existing code and just run it on Mono, particularly if youx27re porting an ASP.NET application.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn some cases, you may require whole new sections of code to make it work. If you use System.Windows.Forms, for example, the application wonx27t work unmodified. Likewise if you use any Windows-specific code (registry access code, for example). But I think the worst offender is UI code. Thatx27s particularly bad on Macintosh systems.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-20 22:17:22'),(35170,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EYou can use a x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.web.ui.webcontrols.datalist.aspxx22x3Ex3Ccodex3EDataListx3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E control instead. It has a x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.web.ui.webcontrols.datalist.repeatcolumns.aspxx22x3Ex3Ccodex3ERepeatColumnsx3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E property that you can define the number of columns you want to display.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn .NET Framework 3.5, there is an even better solution, the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.web.ui.webcontrols.listviewx22x3Ex3Ccodex3EListViewx3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E control. You can find further information about how to use the ListView control x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb398790.aspxx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',14,0,'2008-08-21 17:05:57'),(35170,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EI had to do this for a C++ project in Visual Studio x3Cstrongx3E2003x3C/strongx3E so I donx27t know how relevant this is to later version of visual studio:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn the directory where your executable is created there will be a x3Ccodex3EBuildLog.htmx3C/codex3E file. Open that file in your browser and then for each section such as:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ECreating temporary file x22c:\\some\\path\\RSP00003C.rspx22 with contents\n[\n/D x22WIN32x22 /D x22_WINDOWSx22 /D x22STRICTx22 /D x22NDEBUGx22 ..... (lots of other switches)\n.\\Project.cpp\n.\\Another.cpp\n.\\AndAnother.cpp\nx22.\\And Yet Another.cppx22\n]\nCreating command line x22cl.exe @c:\\some\\path\\RSP00003C.rsp /nologox22\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ecreate a .rsp file with the content between the square brackets (but not including the square brackets) and call it whatever you like. I seem to remember having problems with absolute paths so you may have to make sure all the paths are relative.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen in your build script add the command line from the x3Ccodex3EBuildLog.htmx3C/codex3E file but with your .rsp filename:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ecl.exe @autobuild01.rsp /nologo\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(note there will also be a link.exe section as well as cl.exe)x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 01:04:15'),(35240,'aauger2','x3Cpx3ENot to directly reject your premise but I actually think being a generalist is a good position in programming. You will certainly develop expertise in specific areas but it is likely to be a product of either personal interest or work necessity. Over time the stuff you are able to transfer across languages and problem domains is at the heart of what makes good programmers.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-20 06:12:21'),(35240,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EThis is much more concise:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ewhere \n  datediff(day, date1, date2) = 0\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',34,0,'2008-08-22 19:02:46'),(35320,'rdowdellz','x3Cpx3EIf you want a classic setup, Ix27d go for a 50GB x22/x22 partition, for all your application goodness, and split the rest across users, or a full 950GB for a single user. Endless diskspace galore!x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 01:51:52'),(35380,'ajan8','x3Cpx3ETinyMCE only goes out of its way to disable spell-checking when you donx27t specify the x3Ccodex3Egecko_spellcheckx3C/codex3E option (i verified this with their example code). Might want to double-check your x3Ccodex3EtinyMCE.init()x3C/codex3E call - it should look something like this:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EtinyMCE.init({\n	mode : x22textareasx22,\n	theme : x22simplex22,\n	gecko_spellcheck : true\n});\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 03:24:39'),(35380,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EIts probably not exactly what your looking for, but you may be able to implement OS level clustering.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-05 05:44:13'),(35420,'idevey11','x3Cpx3ETry and gather as much information as you can. See if the host can give you a log showing all the FTP connections that were made to your account. You can use those to see if it was even an FTP connection that was used to make the change and possibly get an IP address.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re using a prepacked software like Wordpress, Drupal, or anything else that you didnx27t code there may be vulnerabilities in upload code that allows for this sort of modification. If it is custom built, double check any places where you allow users to upload files or modify existing files.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe second thing would be to take a dump of the site as-is and check everything for other modifications. It may just be one single modification they made, but if they got in via FTP who knows what else is up there.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ERevert your site back to a known good status and, if need be, upgrade to the latest version.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThere is a level of return you have to take into account too. Is the damage worth trying to track the person down or is this something where you just live and learn and use stronger passwords?x3C/px3E',13,0,'2008-08-06 04:16:07'),(35420,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EAnother alternative would be x3Ca href=x22http://www.sproutcore.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESproutCorex3C/ax3E, which is entirely client-side. The project is still in its infancy, however.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-24 21:15:16'),(35480,'achancelier6','x3Cpx3EI donx27t think there are hard and fast rules for this type of thing, but I usually go by the guideline of using the lightest possible way until absolutely necessary.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor example, letx27s say you have a x3Ccodex3EPersonx3C/codex3E class and a x3Ccodex3EGroupx3C/codex3E class. A x3Ccodex3EGroupx3C/codex3E instance has many people, so a List here would make sense. When I declare the list object in x3Ccodex3EGroupx3C/codex3E I will use an x3Ccodex3EIListx26lt;Personx26gt;x3C/codex3E and instantiate it as a x3Ccodex3EListx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Epublic class Group {\n  private IListx26lt;Personx26gt; people;\n\n  public Group() {\n    this.people = new Listx26lt;Personx26gt;();\n  }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnd, if you donx27t even need everything in x3Ccodex3EIListx3C/codex3E you can always use x3Ccodex3EIEnumerablex3C/codex3E too. With modern compilers and processors, I donx27t think there is really any speed difference, so this is more just a matter of style.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 03:17:07'),(35480,'kgrenkovu','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex = number_of_dimensions;\nwhile (x x26gt; 1)\n{\n  switch (x)\n  {\n    case 20:\n      reduce20DimensionArray();\n      x--;\n    break;\n    case 19:\n      .....\n  }\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Sorry, couldnx27t resist.)x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:46:57'),(35490,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EWe use FindBugs and JDepend integrated with Ant. We use JUnit but wex27re not using any coverage tool. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m not using it integrated to Rational Application Developer (the IDE Ix27m using to develop J2EE applications) because I like how neat it looks when you run javac in the Windows console. :Px3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 04:20:41'),(35490,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EMy guess is that youx27ll see a dramatic improvement if you change that index to be x3Cstrongx3Enonclusteredx3C/strongx3E. This leaves you with two options:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EChange the index to nonclustered, and leave it as a heap table, without a clustered indexx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EChange the index to nonclustered, but then add a surrogate key (like x22idx22) and make it an identity, primary key, and clustered indexx3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEither one will speed up your inserts x3Cstrongx3Ewithoutx3C/strongx3E noticeably slowing down your reads. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThink about it this way -- right now, youx27re telling SQL to do a bulk insert, but then youx27re asking SQL to reorder the entire table every table you add anything. With a nonclustered index, youx27ll add the records in whatever order they come in, and then build a separate index indicating their desired order. x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-24 00:37:47'),(35490,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIn my opinion, with contributions from the SO communityx3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://zendframework.com/x22x3EZend Fraemworkx3C/ax3E for PHPx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.djangoproject.com/x22x3EDjangox3C/ax3E for Pythonx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://rubyonrails.orgx22x3ERailsx3C/ax3E for Rubyx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://merbivore.com/x22x3EMerbx3C/ax3E for Ruby (for the experienced)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.asp.net/mvc/x22x3EASP.NET MVCx3C/ax3E for .NETx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.seaside.st/x22x3ESeasidex3C/ax3E for Smalltalkx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://catalystframework.orgx22x3ECatalystx3C/ax3E for Perlx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',32,0,'2008-08-23 22:25:46'),(35530,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EI think you want to x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cross-correlationx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ecross-correlatex3C/ax3E your signal with an expected, exemplar signal. But, it has been such a long time since I studied signal processing and even then I didnx27t take much notice.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-06 15:38:05'),(35530,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EExpression Engine with the Multi-Site Manager works great for that kind of situation.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 04:15:04'),(35560,'cscarbarrowm','x3Cpx3EIt really depends on the sort of data youx27re bringing back.  Since a DataSet is (in effect) just a collection of DataTable objects, you can return multiple distinct sets of data into a single, and therefore more manageable, object.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPerformance-wise, youx27re more likely to get inefficiency from unoptimized queries than from the x22wrongx22 choice of .NET construct.  At least, thatx27s been my experience.x3C/px3E',69,0,'2008-08-05 17:12:15'),(35560,'prihak','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EIx27m starting to think it canx27t be done that way since there doesnx27t seem to be a way to maintain the offset counter between calls. Is that right, or is there something Ix27m missing.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou arenx27t missing anything; SQL Server does not support global variables, and it doesnx27t support data modification within UDFs.  And even if you wanted to do something as kludgy as using CONTEXT_INFO (see x3Ca href=x22http://weblogs.sqlteam.com/mladenp/archive/2007/04/23/60185.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://weblogs.sqlteam.com/mladenp/archive/2007/04/23/60185.aspxx3C/ax3E), you canx27t set that from within a UDF anyway.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIs there a way you can get around the x22hardcodingx22 of the offset by making that a variable and looping over the iteration of it, doing the inserts within that loop?x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-27 11:14:44'),(35670,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EI would buy a book - the Adam Nathan WPF book is good.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/0672328917x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.amazon.com/Windows-Presentation-Foundation-Unleashed-WPF/dp/0672328917x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 12:02:42'),(35700,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EYou mention your Dad was using a website publishing tool.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf the publishing tool publishes from his computer to the server, it may be the case that his local files are clean, and that he just needs to republish to the server.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EHe should see if therex27s a different login method to his server than plain FTP, though... thatx27s not very secure because it sends his password as clear-text over the internet.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-06 07:31:22'),(35720,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3ENo, but there are JavaScript libraries that can accomplish this for you. Just as an example, x3Ca href=x22http://extjs.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EExt JSx3C/ax3E can be used to create a x3Ca href=x22http://extjs.com/deploy/dev/examples/message-box/msg-box.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Emessage box dialogx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-21 07:32:42'),(35720,'rmaccurlyer','x3Cpx3ETherex27s two questions here: Silverlight vs. Flash as platform and Silverlight vs. Flex as RIA framework.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe first question depends on your timeframe. Flash Player has over 95% reach, Silverlight has no way near that. However, Silverlight may get there, it is after all backed by Microsoft. If you aim to launch a site next week and want a huge audience, Silverlight is not an option. If you aim to launch a really cool application that everyone would want to use itx27s a bit different, if your app is good enough your target audience may install Silverlight just to be able to run it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for the second question its a matter of how easy it is to develop x3Cemx3Eapplicationsx3C/emx3E in Silverlight. Flex isnx27t just a set of widgets, itx27s a very big framework that does a lot of thing that ease the work of the developer. You could write the same applications using only the core Flash API, but it would be very much more work. Depending on whatx27s available in Silverlight, this should be an important factor when deciding. If you can cut development time, is having two platforms worth it?x3C/px3E',30,0,'2008-08-22 11:23:59'),(35870,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EAs a possible alternative to the BSD license you can also use the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/ms-pl.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMs-PLx3C/ax3E license (Microsoft public license). Pretty much the same but (arguably) better worded. Additionally, Itx27s got “Microsoft” in its name, which screams “corprate-friendly” like nothing else does. ;-)x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-26 20:36:17'),(35940,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EI do not have personal experience with this product, but x3Ca href=x22http://www.dokeos.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Edokeosx3C/ax3E is recommended by several people on other sites.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-23 02:29:51'),(36260,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EIf you didnx27t actually want to submit the form, but just invoke whatever code happened to be in the onsubmit, you could possibly do this: (untested)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Evar code = document.getElementById(x27formIdx27).getAttribute(x27onsubmitx27);\neval(code);\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',-3,0,'2008-08-29 08:03:59'),(36350,'dperrenl','x3CPx3EIx27ve worked with the following formula (pseudocode) with some success:x3C/Px3Enow x26lt;- number of minutes since the work day startedx3CBRx3Edelay x26lt;- number of minutes in the delayx3CBRx3Eday x26lt;- length of a work day in minutesx3CBRx3Ex3CBRx3Ex x26lt;- (now + delay) / day {integer division}x3CBRx3Ey x26lt;- (now + delay) % day {modulo remainder}x3CBRx3Ex3CBRx3Ereturn startoftoday + x {in days} + y {in minutes}x3CBRx3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 06:22:08'),(36350,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EYou need to handle the x3Ccodex3ESystem.Windows.Forms.Application.ThreadExceptionx3C/codex3E event for Windows Forms. This article really helped me: x3Ca href=x22http://bytes.com/forum/thread236199.htmlx22x3Ehttp://bytes.com/forum/thread236199.htmlx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',21,0,'2008-08-06 00:11:45'),(36350,'idevey11','x3Cpx3ENot sure what the confusion is. Sites on your intranet are in the intranet zone, web sites are in the internet zone, and sites on your computer are in the local zone, unless youx27ve specifically overridden something in the browserx27s preferences.x3C/px3E',-2,0,'2008-08-22 23:29:29'),(36430,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EViEmu works great with Visual Studio.  I used Vi(m) strictly in Linux, but I was turned on to bringing the Vi(m) editing process into the Windows world by x3Ca href=x22http://www.jpboodhoo.com/x22x3EJP Boodhoox3C/ax3E.  JP x3Ca href=x22http://blog.jpboodhoo.com/HookedOnVIM.aspxx22x3Epraisesx3C/ax3E about it also.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-24 02:08:49'),(36600,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EIf you are querying a SQL Server database (Version 7 and up) you should replace the OleDb classes with corresponding classes in the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.data.sqlclient.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESystem.Data.SqlClientx3C/ax3E namespace (x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.data.sqlclient.sqlconnection.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESqlConnectionx3C/ax3E, x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.data.sqlclient.sqlcommand.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESqlCommandx3C/ax3E and x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.data.sqlclient.sqldatareader.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESqlDataReaderx3C/ax3E) as those classes have been optimized to work with SQL Server.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother thing to note is that you should x27neverx27 select all as this might lead to unexpected results later on if you add or remove columns to this table.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-21 18:19:29'),(36600,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EHave you tried using transactions?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFrom what you describe, having the server committing 100% of the time to disk, it seems you are sending each row of data in an atomic SQL sentence thus forcing the server to commit (write to disk) every single row.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you used transactions instead, the server would only commit x3Cemx3Eoncex3C/emx3E at the end of the transaction.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor further help: What method are you using for inserting data to the server? Updating a DataTable using a DataAdapter, or executing each sentence using a string?x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 17:10:32'),(36760,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EVim, Cygwin, TortoiseSVN, Eclipse. SoapUI is an awesome tool if youx27re working with SOAP web services. I also find TCPTrace a very handy little tool.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 02:15:04'),(36890,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EThinking out of the box, would migrating to a Wiki be out of the question?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESince you consider it feasible to force your users into Subversion (or something similar), a larger change seem acceptable.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother migration target could be to use some kind of structured XML document format (x3Ca href=x22http://www.docbook.org/x22x3EDocBookx3C/ax3E comes to mind). This would enable you to indeed use diffs and source control, while getting all sorts of document formats for free.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-27 14:23:10'),(36890,'abaterb','x3Cpx3EI use it every time I refer to an instance variable, even if I donx27t need to. I think it makes the code more clear.x3C/px3E',23,0,'2008-08-22 23:22:48'),(36890,'hschade12','x3Cpx3ENot Invented here but itx27s on my todo list to setup.\nx3Ca href=x22http://awstats.sourceforge.net/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://awstats.sourceforge.net/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 19:34:34'),(36890,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EI use it whenever x3Ca href=x22http://code.msdn.microsoft.com/sourceanalysisx22x3EStyleCopx3C/ax3E tells me to. x3Ca href=x22http://code.msdn.microsoft.com/sourceanalysisx22x3EStyleCopx3C/ax3E must be obeyed. Oh yes.x3C/px3E',25,0,'2008-08-23 00:00:47'),(37310,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Ch1x3EPerl 6:Proceduralx3C/h1x3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Esub factorial ( int $n ){\n\n  my $result = 1;\n\n  loop ( ; $n x26gt; 0; $n-- ){\n\n    $result *= $n;\n\n  }\n\n  return $result;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 07:48:58'),(37310,'mlowried','x3Cpx3EIx27m not sure of the SQL Server syntax for this but in MySQL I would dox3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT IDColumn, ( IF( Column1 x26gt;= 3, 1, 0 ) + IF( Column2 x26gt;= 3, 1, 0 ) + IF( Column3 x26gt;= 3, 1, 0 ) + ... [snip ] )\n  AS NumberOfColumnsGreaterThanThree\nFROM TableA;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEDIT: A very (very) brief Google search tells me that the x3Ccodex3ECASEx3C/codex3E statement does what I am doing with the x3Ccodex3EIFx3C/codex3E statement in MySQL.  You may or may not get use out of x3Ca href=x22http://www.craigsmullins.com/ssu_0899.htmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethe Google result I foundx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFURTHER EDIT: I should also point out that this isnx27t an answer to your question but an alternative solution to your actual problem.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 18:59:36'),(37590,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EI know at least x3Ca href=x22http://developer.yahoo.com/yui/editor/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eyahoo!x27s Rich Text Editorx3C/ax3E will let you use the included spell checker in FireFox.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI also tested FCKeditor, but that requires the users to install additional plugins on their computer.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 02:20:58'),(37590,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EThe key to a real understanding of CSS (and the browser headaches) is a solid understanding of the x3Ca href=x22http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS2/box.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ebox modelx3C/ax3E used by the CSS Standards, and the incorrect model used by some browsers. Once you have that down and start learning selectors you will get away from browser specific properties and CSS will become something you look forward to.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-25 04:35:50'),(37640,'cribbens4','x3Cpx3EAs long as a field is viewable, you do not need a confirm box. As long as you do some form validation to be sure that  it is at least in valid format for an email address let the user manage the rest of the issues.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-07 20:34:49'),(37640,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3Eit tends to take an inexperienced team longer to build 3-tier.Itx27s more code, so more bugs. Ix27m just playing the devilx27s advocate though.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-08 17:06:16'),(37830,'cscarbarrowm','x3CPx3EWhen I was working for myself doing my consulting business I signed up for a hosted account and honestly I couldnx27t have done without it. x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EWhat I liked most about it was it took 30 seconds to sign up for an account and I was then able to integrate source control using sourcegear vault (which is an excellent source control product and free for single developers) set up projects, clients, releases and versions and monitor my progress constantly.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EOne thing that totally blew me away was that I ended up completely abandoning outlook for all work related correspondence. I could manage all my client interactions from within fogbugz and it all just worked amazingly well.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EIn terms of overhead, one of the nice things you could do was turn anything into a case. Anything that came up in your mind while you were coding, you simply created a new email, sent it to fogbugz and it was instantly added as an item for review later.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EI would strongly recommend you get yourself one of the hosted accounts and give it a whirlx3C/Px3E',14,0,'2008-08-06 14:46:14'),(37920,'mheyward10','Youx27d be looking to static link (as opposed to dynamically link)\n\n\n\nIx27m not sure how many of the MS redistributables statically link in.',0,0,'2008-08-06 16:10:55'),(38010,'aauger2','x3Cpx3EDepending how much youx27re planning to do on these legacy projects I would consider not switching.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhen digging through legacy code it really helps to have all the history and blame. SVN is miles better than VSS, but youx27ll be losing the history when you switch.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27re going to be a lot of ongoing development in VB6 then it may well be worth switching to SVN, but if youx27re going to be doing that much going forward is it also worth reviewing the project?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI have a similar problem, only the legacy projects are in Delphi. Were they in VB6 I think I would consider x27upgradingx27 them to VB.Net, just for maintainability.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 17:31:38'),(38010,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EHave you had a look at the x3Ca href=x22http://trac.sitecore.net/Blogx22 rel=x22nofollowx22 title=x22Bristol University Language Engineering Coursex22x3EShared Source blog modulex3C/ax3E for Sitecore?x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 03:49:13'),(38010,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EDonx27t worry about DNS and URL rewritingx3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYour DNS record will be static, something like:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E*.YOURDOMAIN.COM A 123.123.123.123x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAsk your DNS provider to do it for you (if itx27s not done already) or do it by yourself if you have control over your DNS records. This will automatically point all your subdomains (current and future ones) into the same HTTP server.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EOnce itx27s done, you will only need to parse HOST header on every single http request to detect what hostname was used to access your server-side scripts on your http server.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAssuming youx27re using ASP.NET, this is kind of silly example I came up with but works and demonstrates simplicity of this approach:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;%@ Language=x22C#x22 %x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex26lt;%x3Cbrx3Estring subDomain = Request.Url.Host.Split(x27.x27)[0].ToUpper();x3Cbrx3Eif (subDomain == x22CLIENTXXXx22) Response.Write(x22Hello CLIENTXXX, your secret number is 33x22);x3Cbrx3Eelse if (subDomain == x22CLIENTYYYx22) Response.Write(x22Hello CLIENTYYY, your secret number is 44x22);x3Cbrx3Eelse Response.Write(subDomain+x22 doesnx27t existx22);x3Cbrx3E%x26gt;x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',7,0,'2008-08-04 16:32:24'),(38010,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EIn our scenario, we have a separate file server that both of our front end app servers write to, that way you either server has access to the same sets of files.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 19:03:07'),(38010,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EYou could also adjust the line height of the td element:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpre class=x22lang-css prettyprint-overridex22x3Ex3Ccodex3Etd {\n    line-height: 0\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',4,0,'2008-08-22 15:03:36'),(38070,'ajan8','x3Cpx3Etwo of many Mathematica solutions (although ! is built-in and efficient):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E(* returns pure function *)\n(FixedPoint[(If[#[[2]]x26gt;1,{#[[1]]*#[[2]],#[[2]]-1},#])x26amp;,{1,n}][[1]])x26amp;\n\n(* not using built-in, returns pure function, donx27t use: might build 1..n list *)\n(Times @@ Range[#])x26amp;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 20:27:07'),(38070,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EItx27s acceptable as long as you understand the consequences. The main reason youx27d have a BLL is to re-use that logic elsewhere throughout your application.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you have all that validation logic in the presentation code, youx27re really making it difficult to re-use elsewhere within your application.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-07 06:48:48'),(38090,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EAll too often, the class is used\n  simply for its syntactic sugar; it\n  puts the functions for a record type\n  into their own little namespace.  x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYes, I find this to be too prevalent as well. This is not Object Oriented Programming. Itx27s Object Based Programming and data centric programing. In my 10 years of working with OO Languages, I see people mostly doing Object Based Programming. OBP breaks down very quickly IMHO since you are essentially getting the worst of both words: 1) Procedural programming without adhering to proven structured programming methodology and 2) OOP without adhering to to proven OOP methodology.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOOP done right is a beautiful thing. It makes very difficult problems easy to solve, and to the uninitiated (not trying to sound pompous there), it can almost seem like magic. That being said, OOP is just one tool in the toolbox of programming methodologies. It is not the be all end all methodology. It just happens to suit large business applications well.   x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMost developers who work in OOP languages are utilizing examples of OOP done right in the frameworks and types that they use day-to-day, but they just arenx27t aware of it. Here are some very simple examples: ADO.NET, Hibernate/NHibernate, Logging Frameworks, various language collection types, the ASP.NET stack, The JSP stack etc... These are all things that heavily rely on OOP in their codebases.x3C/px3E',43,0,'2008-08-23 20:42:45'),(38090,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EIx27d also recommend Subversion. It does not take too long to set up, it is free, and there is a really good book available online that goes over the basics as well as some advanced topics: x3Ca href=x22http://svnbook.red-bean.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://svnbook.red-bean.com/x3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 00:26:08'),(38090,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EIf you want to do it programatically. Ix27m not sure... and Ix27d really recommend against it.\n\nIf youx27re just troubleshooting stuff on your own machine, x3Ca href=x22http://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/sysinternals/bb896653.aspxx22x3ESysInternals Process Explorerx3C/ax3E can help youx3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ERun it, use the Find Handle command (I think itx27s either in the find or handle menu), and search for the name of your file. Once the handle(s) is found, you can forcibly close them.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can then delete the file and so on.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EBewarex3C/strongx3E, doing this may cause the program which owns the handles to behave strangely, as youx27ve just pulled the proverbial rug out from under it, but it works well when you are debugging your own errant code, or when visual studio / windows explorer is being crap and not releasing file handles even though you told them to close the file ages ago... sigh :-)x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-04 10:12:11'),(38160,'mheyward10','x3Cpx3EA number of people I know swear by x3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/notebookx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGoogle Notebookx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 16:20:35'),(38190,'aa9279','x3Cpx3EIf you prefer doing it on the x3Ccodex3EMSBuildx3C/codex3E side over the x3Ccodex3ECCNetx3C/codex3E config, looks like the x3Ccodex3EMSBuildx3C/codex3E Community Tasks extensionx27s x3Ca href=x22http://msbuildtasks.tigris.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ex3Ccodex3ESvnVersionx3C/codex3Ex3C/ax3E task might do the trick.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-04 16:03:03'),(38210,'dperrenl','x3CPx3EOkay, how about these? The difference between the approaches should speak for themselves.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EAlso, this is tested about as far as I can throw it. The warranty lasts until... now.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EHope it helps!x3C/Px3Ex3CPREx3Ex3CCODEx3EModule Module1\n\n\n\n    Public Function IsInBusinessHours(ByVal d As Date) As Boolean\n\n        Return Not (d.Hour x26lt; 8 OrElse d.Hour x26gt; 17 OrElse d.DayOfWeek = DayOfWeek.Saturday OrElse d.DayOfWeek = DayOfWeek.Sunday)\n\n    End Function\n\n\n\n\n\n    Public Function AddInBusinessHours(ByVal fromDate As Date, ByVal hours As Integer) As Date\n\n        Dim work As Date = fromDate.AddHours(hours)\n\n        While Not IsInBusinessHours(work)\n\n            work = work.AddHours(1)\n\n        End While\n\n        Return work\n\n    End Function\n\n\n\n\n\n    Public Function LoopInBusinessHours(ByVal fromDate As Date, ByVal hours As Integer) As Date\n\n        Dim work As Date = fromDate\n\n        While hours x26gt; 0\n\n            While hours x26gt; 0 AndAlso IsInBusinessHours(work)\n\n                work = work.AddHours(1)\n\n                hours -= 1\n\n            End While\n\n            While Not IsInBusinessHours(work)\n\n                work = work.AddHours(1)\n\n            End While\n\n        End While\n\n        Return work\n\n    End Function\n\n\n\n    Sub Main()\n\n        Dim test As Date = New Date(2008, 8, 8, 15, 0, 0)\n\n        Dim hours As Integer = 5\n\n        Console.WriteLine(x22Date: x22 + test.ToString() + x22, x22 + hours.ToString())\n\n        Console.WriteLine(x22Just skipping: x22 + AddInBusinessHours(test, hours))\n\n        Console.WriteLine(x22Looping: x22 + LoopInBusinessHours(test, hours))\n\n        Console.ReadLine()\n\n    End Sub\n\n\n\nEnd Module\n\nx3C/CODEx3Ex3C/PREx3E',2,0,'2008-08-08 01:20:33'),(38280,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EI assume you have seen the writeup of x3Ca href=x22http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/db2luw/v9/index.jsp?topic=/com.ibm.db2.udb.msg.doc/doc/sql1159.htmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESQL1159x3C/ax3E in the x3Ca href=x22http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/db2luw/v9/index.jspx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDB2 Reference Guidex3C/ax3E?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUnfortunately for you, the reason codes stop at 6 and donx27t continue to 7.  It does say:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EUser response: There was a problem with your DB2 installation. If this is the first time DB2 was installed on this computer, review the install logs for any possible errors and run a repair of DB2 from the Add/Remove Programs control panel applet. The default location of the installation logs is the My Documents/DB2LOG folder of the user that performed the installation. If this does not resolve the issue please contact IBM Support and provide the reason code associated with this message along with any installation logs.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo I guess try to reinstall it and if the problem continues youx27ll have to contact IBM.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESorry, I know thatx27s not much help.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 07:06:15'),(38370,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EYou can use the x3Ca href=x22http://www.chilkatsoft.com/python.aspx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EChilkatx3C/ax3E library.  Itx27s commercial, but has a free evaluation and seems pretty nice.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHerex27s an example I got from x3Ca href=x22http://www.example-code.com/python/zip.aspx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eimport chilkat\n\n# Demonstrates how to create a WinZip-compatible 128-bit AES strong encrypted zip\nzip = chilkat.CkZip()\nzip.UnlockComponent(x22anything for 30-day trialx22)\n\nzip.NewZip(x22strongEncrypted.zipx22)\n\n# Set the Encryption property = 4, which indicates WinZip compatible AES encryption.\nzip.put_Encryption(4)\n# The key length can be 128, 192, or 256.\nzip.put_EncryptKeyLength(128)\nzip.SetPassword(x22secretx22)\n\nzip.AppendFiles(x22exampleData/*x22,True)\nzip.WriteZip()\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 05:20:48'),(38670,'enewberryf','x3CPx3EIs the site just plain static HTML? i.e. he hasnx27t managed to code himself an upload page that permits anyone driving by to upload compromised scripts/pages?x3C/Px3E\n\nx