E',4,0,'2008-08-29 06:00:22'),(38820,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EAnother version of this (in middle school) was x22Please Excuse My Dear Aunt Sallyx22.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3EParenthesesx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EExponentsx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EMultiplicationx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EDivisionx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EAdditionx3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3ESubtractionx3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe mnemonic device was helpful in school, and still useful in programming today.x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-06 19:01:15'),(38820,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EAs far as I know there are no real bugs, but the performance when threading in cPython is really bad (compared to most other threading implementations, but usually good enough if all most of the threads do is block) due to the x3Ca href=x22http://docs.python.org/api/threads.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGILx3C/ax3E (Global Interpreter Lock), so really it is implementation specific rather than language specific. Jython, for example, does not suffer from this due to using the Java thread model.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESee x3Ca href=x22http://www.artima.com/weblogs/viewpost.jsp?thread=214235x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E post on why it is not really feasible to remove the GIL from the cPython implementation, and x3Ca href=x22http://www.pyzine.com/Issue001/Section_Articles/article_ThreadingGlobalInterpreter.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E for some practical elaboration and workarounds.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDo a quick google for x3Ca href=x22http://www.google.com/search?q=python+gilx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ex22Python GILx22x3C/ax3E for more information.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-29 09:58:34'),(38870,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3ESo the really, really big deal about LINQ has nothing to do with Linq to SQL. Itx27s about the enhancements it brought to the C# language itself.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-22 02:18:05'),(38870,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EIx27m guessing that the settings would have to be in powershell.exe.config in the powershell directory, but that seems to be a bad 