on you wanted this index to be clustered?x3C/px3E',18,0,'2008-08-23 17:27:42'),(38960,'mschafflere','x3Cpx3EThe x3Ca href=x22http://library.gnome.org/devel/glib/stable/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGlibx3C/ax3E library used on the Gnome project may also be some use. Moreover it is pretty well tested.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIBM developer works has a good tutorial on its use: x3Ca href=x22https://www.ibm.com/developerworks/linux/tutorials/l-glib/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EManage C data using the GLib collectionsx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',33,0,'2008-08-05 22:50:09'),(39240,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3ENo, what youx27re doing is fine. Donx27t let those people confuse you.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf youx27ve written the web services with .net then the reference proxies generated by .net are going to be quite suitable. The situation you describe (where you are both producer and consumer) is the ideal situation.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you need to connect to a web services that is x3Cemx3Eunknownx3C/emx3E at compile time, then you would want a more dynamic approach, where you deduce the x27shapex27 of the web service. x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EBut start by using the auto generated proxy class, and donx27t worry about it until you hit a limitation. And when you do -- come back to stack overflow ;-)x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-02 19:33:13'),(39240,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EThe x3Cstrongx3EPublish to Providerx3C/strongx3E functionality has worked great for me.  See x3Ca href=x22http://weblogs.asp.net/scottgu/archive/2006/12/22/recipe-deploying-a-sql-database-to-a-remote-hosting-environment-part-1.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EScott Gux27s Blog Entryx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you need something really robust look  at redgate softwarex27s tools x3Ca href=x22http://www.red-gate.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eherex3C/ax3E...if you are doing much SQL at all, these are worth the $$.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-05 05:11:30'),(39770,'ajan8','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms180026.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EUNIONx3C/ax3E should be your friend:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT Column1 FROM table WHERE idColumn = 1x3Cbrx3EUNION ALLx3Cbrx3ESELECT Column2 FROM table WHERE idColumn = 1x3Cbrx3EUNION ALLx3Cbrx3ESELECT Column3 FROM table WHERE idColumn = 1x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ebut it can x3Ca href=x22http://blog.falafel.com/2006/01/20/TSQLTipAvoidUNION.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ealso be your foex3C/ax3E on large result sets.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 18:39:17'),(39770,'kgrenkovu','x3Cpx3E[C++]x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI agree with the x22use it when you have tox22 brigade. Decorating code unnecessarily with x3Cemx3Ethisx3C/emx3E isnx27t a great idea because the compiler wonx27t warn you when you forget to do it. This introduces potential confusion for people expecting x3Cemx3Ethisx3C/emx3E to always be there, i.e. theyx27ll have to x3Cemx3Ethinkx3C/emx3E about it.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo, when would you use it? Ix27ve just had a look around some random code and found these examples (Ix27m not passing judgement on whether these are x3Cemx3Egoodx3C/emx3E things to do or otherwise):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EPassing x22yourselfx22 to a function.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EAssigning x22yourselfx22 to a pointer or something like that.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECasting, i.e. up/down casting (safe or otherwise), casting away constness, etc.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ECompiler enforced disambiguation.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',4,0,'2008-08-26 21:25:29'),(39770,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EWhat type is selectedYear? A DateTime? If so then you might need to convert to a string.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-08 09:21:07'),(39780,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EI have been writing OO code for the last 9 years or so.  Other than using messaging, itx27s hard for me to imagine other approach.  The main benefit I see totally in line with what CodingTheWheel said: modularisation.  OO naturally leads me to construct my applications from modular components that have clean interfaces and clear responsibilities (i.e. loosely coupled, highly cohesive code with a clear separation of concerns).  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think where OO breaks down is when people create deeply nested class heirarchies.  This can lead to complexity.  However, factoring out common finctionality into a base class, then reusing that in other descendant classes is a deeply elegant thing, IMHO!x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-23 19:02:58'),(39780,'tplumsteadj','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cblockquotex3E\n    x3Cpx3EHANDLEs (and the rest of the WinAPI) is OOP!x3C/px3E\n  x3C/blockquotex3E\n  \n  x3Cpx3EAre they, though? Theyx27re not inheritable, theyx27re certainly not substitutable, they lack well-defined classes... I think they fall a long way short of x22OOPx22.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHave you ever created a window using WinAPI? Then you should know that you define a class (x3Ccodex3ERegisterClassx3C/codex3E), create an instance of it (x3Ccodex3ECreateWindowx3C/codex3E), call virtual methods (x3Ccodex3EWndProcx3C/codex3E) and base-class methods (x3Ccodex3EDefWindowProcx3C/codex3E) and so on. WinAPI even takes the nomenclature from SmallTalk OOP, calling the methods “messages” (Window Messages).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHandles may not be inheritable but then, therex27s x3Ccodex3Efinalx3C/codex3E in Java. They donx27t lack a class, they x3Cemx3Earex3C/emx3E a placeholder for the class: Thatx27s what the word “handle” means. Looking at architectures like MFC or .NET WinForms itx27s immediately obvious that except for the syntax, nothing much is different from the WinAPI.x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-23 20:42:13'),(39910,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EBen, Almost all seasoned programmers are still students in programming. You never stops learning anything when you are a developer. But if you are really starting off on your career then you should be least worried about the specialization thing. All APIs, frameworks and skills that you expect that gives you a long term existence in the field is not going to happen. Technology seems changing a lot and you should be versatile and flexible enough to learn anything. The knowledge you acquire on one platform/api/framework doesnx27t die off. You can apply the skills to the next greatest platform/api/framework. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat being said you should just stop worrying about the future and concentrate on the basics. DataStructures, Algorithm Analysis and Design, Compiler Design, Operating system design are the bare minimum stuff you need.  And further you should be willing to go back and read tho books in those field any time in your career. Thats all is required. Good luck. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESorry if I sounded like a big ass advisor; but thats what I think. :-)x3C/px3E',20,0,'2008-08-20 06:20:32'),(39910,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EI agree that scripting everything is the best way to go and is what I advocate at work.  You should script everything from DB and object creation to populating your lookup tables.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAnything you do in UI only wonx27t translate (especially for changes... not so much for first deployments) and will end up requiring a tools like what Redgate offers.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-03 05:38:02'),(39910,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EYou sound as if youx27re looking for three major things: code templates, refactoring tools, and auto-completion.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe good news is that Xcode 3 and later come with superb auto-completion and template support.  By default, you have to explicitly request completion by hitting the escape key.  (This actually works in all x3Ccodex3ENSTextViewx3C/codex3Es; try it!)  If you want to have the completions appear automatically, you can go to x3Cstrongx3EPreferencesx3C/strongx3E -x3E x3Cstrongx3ECode Sensex3C/strongx3E and set the pop-up to appear automatically after a few seconds.  You should find good completions for C and Objective-C code, and pretty good completions for C++.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EXcode also has a solid template/skeleton system that you can use.  You can see what templates are available by default by going to Edit -x3E Insert Text Macro.  Of course, you donx27t want to insert text macros with the mouse; that defeats the point.  Instead, you have two options:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3EBack in x3Cstrongx3EPreferencesx3C/strongx3E,go to x3Cstrongx3EKey Bindingsx3C/strongx3E, and then, under x3Cstrongx3EMenu Key Bindingsx3C/strongx3E, assign a specific shortcut to macros you use often.  I personally donx27t bother doing this, but I know plenty of great Mac devs who dox3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EUse the x3Ccodex3ECompletionPrefixx3C/codex3E.  By default, nearly all of the templates have a special prefix that, if you type and then hit the escape key, will result in the template being inserted.  You can use Control-/ to move between the completion fields.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can see x3Ca href=x22http://crookedspin.com/2005/06/10/xcode-macros/x22x3Ea full list of Xcodex27s default macros and their associated x3Ccodex3ECompletionPrefixx3C/codex3Eesx3C/ax3E at x3Ca href=x22http://crookedspin.comx22x3ECrooked Spinx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can also add your own macros, or modify the defaults.  To do so, edit the file x3Ccodex3E/Developer/Library/Xcode/Specifications/{C,HTML}.xctxtmacrox3C/codex3E.  The syntax should be self-explanatory, if not terribly friendly.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUnfortunately, if youx27re addicted to R#, you will be disappointed by your refactoring options.  Basic refactoring is provided within Xcode through the context menu or by hitting Shift-Apple-J.  From there, you can extract and rename methods, promote and demote them through the class hierarchy, and a few other common operations.  Unfortunately, neither Xcode nor any third-party utilities offer anything approaching Resharper, so on that front, youx27re currently out of luck.  Thankfully, Apple has already demonstrated versions of Xcode in the works that have vastly improved refactoring capabilities, so hopefully you wonx27t have to wait too long before the situation starts to improve.x3C/px3E',39,0,'2008-08-22 00:33:18'),(39960,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EIx27d say that this is ok but should only be reserved for forms where the email is essential. If you mistype your email for your flight booking then you have severed the two-way link between yourself and the other party and risk not getting the confirmation number, here on StackOverflow it would only mean your Gravatar would not be loaded ...x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27d consider myself fairly techie but I always fill in both fields /wo cut-paste if I regard it to be important enough.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 20:16:37'),(39960,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EIt is the cost of setting up the connection, transferring the data and then tearing it down.  It will eat up your performance.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEvidence is harder to come by but consider the following...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ELetx27s say it takes x microseconds to make a connection. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow you want to make several requests and get data back and forth.  Letx27s say that the difference in transport time is negligable between one connection and many (just ofr the sake of argument).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENow letx27s say it takes y microseconds to close the connection.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOpening one connection will take x+y microseconds of overhead.  Opening many will take n * (x+y).  That will delay your execution.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-26 20:56:22'),(39960,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EAt a former job we had a cluster of web servers with an F5 load balancer in front of them.  We had a very similar problem in that our applications allowed users to upload content which might include photox27s and such.  These were legacy applications and we did not want to edit them to use a database and a SAN solution was too expensive for our situation.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWe ended up using a file replication service on the two clustered servers. This ran as a service on both machines using an account that had network access to paths on the opposite server.  When a file was uploaded, this backend service syncx27d the data in the file system folders making it available to be served from either web server.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETwo of the products we reviewed were x3Ca href=x22http://www.tgrmn.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EViceVersax3C/ax3E and x3Ca href=x22http://www.peersoftware.com/products/peersync/peersync.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EPeerSyncx3C/ax3E.  I think we ended up using PeerSync.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Chr /x3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 19:20:19'),(39960,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EYou could apply some x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviationsx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EStandard Devisionx3C/ax3E to your logic and take notice of peaks over x%.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-06 15:17:29'),(40090,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EIf youx27re running on IIS 7, you can simply delete the Default.aspx file that comes with ASP.NET MVC (assuming youx27re running on Preview 3 or higher). That file was needed due to an issue with Cassini that was fixed in .NET 3.5 SP1. For more details check out:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://haacked.com/archive/2008/04/10/upcoming-changes-in-routing.aspxx22x3Ehttp://haacked.com/archive/2008/04/10/upcoming-changes-in-routing.aspxx3C/ax3E\nand\nx3Ca href=x22http://haacked.com/archive/2008/05/12/sp1-beta-and-its-effect-on-mvc.aspxx22x3Ehttp://haacked.com/archive/2008/05/12/sp1-beta-and-its-effect-on-mvc.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-21 02:55:03'),(40090,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EIs your existing application monolithic or tiered in seperate processes/layers?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf tiered, you can convert the middle/app-tier to run in an OSGi container.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIn my teamx27s experience, wex27ve found trying to do web-stuff in OSGi painful.  Other pain points are Hibernate and Jakarta Commons Logging.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI find the OSGi specs pretty readable and I recommend you print out the flowchart that shows the algorithm for class loading.  Ix27ll guarantee youx27ll have moments of, x22why am I getting a NoClassDefFoundError?x22: the flowchart will tell you why.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 01:51:54'),(40090,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EHow about the x3Ca href=x22http://www.asp.net/mvc/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EASP.NET MVC frameworkx3C/ax3E?  Itx27s what this site is running on.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAnother more mature option is x3Ca href=x22http://www.castleproject.org/projects/monorail/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECastle MonoRailx3C/ax3E.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think ASP.NET MVC is probably the best choice in the long run.  A year from now, it will be far easier to hire someone who knows ASP.NET MVC than someone who knows MonoRail.x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-23 22:20:10'),(40230,'aauger2','x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;form autocomplete=x22offx22 ...x3Cbrx3Ex3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3Ewas a none standard way to do this (I think mozilla and IE still support it) but messing with the users expectations is normally a bad idea.  x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf the user enters their credit card details into a form and then letx27s someone else use that browser itx27s not your concern :)x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-05 20:26:26'),(40230,'cleatham18','x3Cpx3EHow about if you are not sure about the interface yet and donx27t want any other code depending on the present interface? [Thatx27s off the top of my head, but Ix27d be interested in other reasons as well!]x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit:\nA bit of googling gave the following:\nx3Ca href=x22http://codebetter.com/blogs/patricksmacchia/archive/2008/01/05/rambling-on-the-sealed-keyword.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://codebetter.com/blogs/patricksmacchia/archive/2008/01/05/rambling-on-the-sealed-keyword.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://codebetter.com/blogs/patricksmacchia/archive/2008/01/05/rambling-on-the-sealed-keyword.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EQuoting:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are three reasons why a sealed class is better than an unsealed class:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EVersioningx3C/strongx3E: When a class is originally sealed, it can change to unsealed in the future without breaking compatibility. (…)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3EPerformancex3C/strongx3E: (…) if the JIT compiler sees a call to a virtual method using a sealed types, the JIT compiler can produce more efficient code by calling the method non-virtually.(…)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cstrongx3ESecurity and Predictabilityx3C/strongx3E: A class must protect its own state and not allow itself to ever become corrupted. When a class is unsealed, a derived class can access and manipulate the base class’s state if any data fields or methods that internally manipulate fields are accessible and not private.(…)x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',9,0,'2008-08-24 01:37:29'),(40230,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3ETo reduce the risk you can also associate the originating IP with the session. That way an attacker has to be within the same private network to be able to use the session.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EChecking referer headers can also be an option but those are more easily spoofed.x3C/px3E',-1,0,'2008-08-22 21:04:53'),(40480,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EWhy not just make something up?  An unknown attribute would surely break the build.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E[MyMadeUpAttributeThatBreaksTheBuildForSure]\npublic class NotDoneYet {}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',-1,0,'2008-08-26 18:28:08'),(40480,'prihak','x3Cpx3EThe seminal resource for this are chapters 28-30 of x3Ca href=x22http://rads.stackoverflow.com/amzn/click/1558605762x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESQL for Smartiesx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Ix27ve recommended this book so much I figure Celko owes me royalties by now!)x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 18:35:13'),(40590,'hschade12','x3Cpx3E@Silas The sanity checking is a good idea. However, the regex doesnx27t cover all DOIs. The first element must (currently) be 10, and the second element must (currently) be numeric, but the third element is barely restricted at all:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3Ex22Legal characters are the legal graphic characters of Unicode. This specifically excludes the control character ranges 0x00-0x1F and 0x80-0x9F...x22  x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eand thatx27s where the real problem lies. In practice, Ix27ve never seen whitespace used, but the spec specifically allows for it. Basically, there doesnx27t seem to be a sensible way of detecting the x3Cemx3Eendx3C/emx3E of a DOI.x3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-27 13:04:36'),(40590,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EWhy not set up a Wiki?x3Cbr /x3E\nIf you are on windows, i know that x3Ca href=x22http://www.screwturn.eu/Default.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EScrewTurn wikix3C/ax3E is pretty simple to deploy on a desktop/laptop.  No database to fuss around with.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-20 15:34:07'),(40680,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EYou can use x3Ccodex3Ethe Row_Number()x3C/codex3E function.\nIts used as follows:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT Row_Number() OVER(ORDER BY UserName) As RowID, UserFirstName, UserLastName\nFROM Users\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFrom which it will yield a result set with a x3Ccodex3ERowIDx3C/codex3E field which you can use to page between.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT * \nFROM \n    ( SELECT Row_Number() OVER(ORDER BY UserName) As RowID, UserFirstName, UserLastName\n      FROM Users \n    ) As RowResults\nWHERE RowID Between 5 AND 10\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eetcx3C/px3E',32,0,'2008-08-06 00:59:21'),(40730,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EI tend to underscore fields with _ so donx27t really ever need to use this. Also R# tends to refactor them away anyway...x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 23:23:16'),(40730,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EI would use a hidden RichTextBox, set the Rtf member, then retrieve the Text member to sanitize the RTF in a well-supported way.  Then I would use manually inject the desired formatting afterwards.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-21 21:39:40'),(40730,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EPlace the x3Ccodex3ECASEx3C/codex3E and x3Ccodex3EISDATEx3C/codex3E inside the x3Ccodex3ECONVERT()x3C/codex3E function.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ccodex3E\nSELECT COUNT(*) FROM MyTable\nWHERE\n    DATEDIFF(dd, CONVERT(DATETIME, CASE IsDate(lastUpdate) when 1 then lastUpdate ELSE  x2712-30-1899x27 end), getDate()) x26lt; 31\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EReplace x27x3Ccodex3E12-30-1899x3C/codex3Ex27 with the default date of your choice.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-26 18:27:08'),(40840,'clawrence3','x3Ch1x3EJavascript:x3C/h1x3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efactorial = function( n )\n{\n   return n x26gt; 0 ? n * factorial( n - 1 ) : 1;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m not sure what a Factorial is but that does what the other programs do in javascript.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 08:10:43'),(40840,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EI think you should look at Silverlight as a long-term play, just as Microsoft seems to be doing. Therex27s an obvious balance on when to use Silverlight vs. Flash when youx27re concerned about reach and install base, but here are some reasons Silverlight is a good direction to move in:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ESecond mover advantage - Just as Microsoft built a x22better Javax22 with .NET, theyx27re able to look at how youx27d design a RIA plugin from scratch, today. They have the advantage of knowing how people use the web today, something the inventors of Flash could never have accurately guessed. Flash can add features, but they canx27t realistically chuck the platform and start over.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EDeveloper familiarity - While Silverlight is a new model, itx27s not entirely unfamiliar to developers. Theyx27ll x22getx22 the way Silverlight works a lot more quickly than theyx27ll understand firing up a new development environment with a new scripting language and new event paradigms.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EBeing rid of the timeline model in Flash - Flash was originally built for keyframe based animations, and while there are ways to abstract this away, itx27s at the core of how Flash works. Silverlight ditches that for an application-centric model. x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EScottGu - ScottGu is fired up about Silverlight. Nuff said.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ECool new features - While Silverlight still has some catching up to do with Flash on some obvious features (like webcam / mic integration, or 3d / graphics acceleration), there are some slick new technologies built in to Silverlight - Deep Zoom is one example. Ix27m seeing more x22revolutionaryx22 technologies on the Silverlight side, while Flash seems to be in maintenance mode at this point.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E',52,0,'2008-08-22 00:11:17'),(41010,'aalandg','x3Cpx3EYou could try signal averaging, i.e. for each point, average the value with the surrounding 3 or more points. If the noise blips are huge, then even this may not help.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EI realise that this was language agnostic, but guessing that you are using LabView, there are lots of pre-packaged signal processing VIs that come with LabView that you can use to do smoothing and noise reduction. The x3Ca href=x22http://forums.ni.com/x22x3ENI forumsx3C/ax3E are a great place to get more specialised help on this sort of thing.x3C/px3E',8,0,'2008-08-06 15:12:48'),(41010,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EIt depends on the coding standard Ix27m working under.  If we are using _ to denote an instance variable then x22thisx22 becomes redundant. If we are not using _ then I tend to use this to denote instance variable.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 23:30:42'),(41010,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EA complete rebuild will delete that file forcing the linker to create it, hence the reason it gets a new creation date.  You could try disabling incremental linking under project properties (Linker | General).  If that doesnx27t do it you could add a build event to delete the exe file and force it to create a new file each time.  Both of these things could increase your build time.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 20:02:52'),(41220,'awrefford16','x3Cpx3EYou can use the LogonUser property of Windows Installer as a condition to the action launching the EXE.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-27 13:18:24'),(41220,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EPrint out the records. Give the hardcopy to the idiot who decided to use a varchar(50) and ask them to find the problem record.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ENext time they might just see the point of choosing an appropriate data type.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 18:14:09'),(41220,'wscreen1b','x3Cpx3EA nightly build of x3Ca href=x22http://www.jetbrains.com/resharper/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EResharperx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 01:09:44'),(41290,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EWe do that at work, its just easier to find stuff if the class and files have the same name. As for performance, you really shouldnx27t have 5000 classes in a single project. If you do, some refactoring might be in order.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said, there are instances when we have multiple classes in one file. And that is when itx27s just a private helper class for the main class of the file.x3C/px3E',9,0,'2008-08-26 18:23:12'),(41300,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EIf youx27re working within a single method (or even in a single class or assembly in some cases) and no one outside is going to see what youx27re doing, use the fullness of a List. But if youx27re interacting with outside code, like when youx27re returning a list from a method, then you only want to declare the interface without necessarily tying yourself to a specific implementation, especially if you have no control over who compiles against your code afterward. If you started with a concrete type and you decided to change to another one, even if it uses the same interface, youx27re going to break someone elsex27s code unless you started off with an interface or abstract base type. x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-20 03:20:12'),(41320,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EIn most firewall setups, the TCP connection will be torn down by the firewall if it is idle to conserve resources. The idle timeout is probably not something you can control. Some will tear them down if they are idle and a resource limit is being hit.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMost corp environments wonx27t allow any machines to make an outbound TCP connection anyway.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, using this mechanism means you are going to have scaling problems. I think more reliable solution is to queue up information and have your clients poll for them regularly. Utilize caching if possible such that a subsequent client poll will get the cached data from the customers proxy cache, if they are using one.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you have to push data in a timely manner, in sub-second land (i.e. financial services), then consider some messaging infrastructure such an NServiceBus distributor on client side, but that will require a customer install...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo have you tried using Toredo? Having read that it would appear there it is prob too complicated for a user to setup.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 20:47:52'),(41460,'chenburyh','x3CPx3EThe typical method is as follows. Youx27ve said you want to do this in C# so here goes...x3C/Px3E\n\nx3COLx3E\n\nx3CLIx3EIf you donx27t know which process has the file locked, youx27ll need to examine each processx27s handle list, and query each handle to determine if it identifies the locked file. Doing this in C# will likely require P/Invoke or an intermediary C++/CLI to call the native APIs youx27ll need.x3C/LIx3E\n\nx3CLIx3EOnce youx27ve figured out which process(es) have the file locked, youx27ll need to safely inject a small native DLL into the process (you can also inject a managed DLL, but this is messier, as you then have to start or attach to the .NET runtime).x3C/LIx3E\n\nx3CLIx3EThat bootstrap DLL then closes the handle using CloseHandle etc.x3C/LIx3Ex3C/OLx3E\n\nx3CPx3EEssentially: the way to unlock a x22lockedx22 file is to inject a DLL into the offending processx27s address space and close it yourself. You can do this using native or managed code. No matter what, youx27re going to need a small amount of native code or at least P/Invoke into the same.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EHelpful links:x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CULx3E\n\nx3CLIx3Ex3CA href=x22http://www.codeproject.com/KB/threads/winspy.aspxx22x3Ehttp://www.codeproject.com/KB/threads/winspy.aspxx3C/Ax3Ex3C/LIx3E\n\nx3CLIx3Ex3CA href=x22http://damianblog.com/2008/07/02/net-code-injection/x22x3Ehttp://damianblog.com/2008/07/02/net-code-injection/x3C/Ax3Ex3C/LIx3Ex3C/ULx3E\n\nx3CPx3EGood luck!x3C/Px3E',11,0,'2008-08-04 10:15:30'),(41460,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3EWhen dealing with indexes, you have to determine what your table is going to be used for.  If you are primarily inserting 1000 rows a second and not doing any querying, then a clustered index is a hit to performance.  If you are doing 1000 queries a second, then not having an index will lead to very bad performance.  The best thing to do when trying to tune queries/indexes is to use the Query Plan Analyzer and SQL Profiler in SQL Server.  This will show you where you are running into costly table scans or other performance blockers.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAs for the GUID vs ID argument, you can find people online that swear by both.  I have always been taught to use GUIDs unless I have a really good reason not to.  Jeff has a good post that talks about the reasons for using GUIDs: x3Ca href=x22http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/000817.htmlx22x3Ehttp://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/000817.htmlx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAs with most anything development related, if you are looking to improve performance there is not one, single right answer.  It really depends on what you are trying to accomplish and how you are implementing the solution.  The only true answer is to test, test, and test again against performance metrics to ensure that you are meeting your goals.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3E[Edit]\n\n@Matt, after doing some more research on the GUID/ID debate I came across this post.  Like I mentioned before, there is not a true right or wrong answer.  It depends on your specific implementation needs.  But these are some pretty valid reasons to use GUIDs as the primary key:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n\n  x3Cpx3EFor example, there is an issue known as a x22hotspotx22, where certain pages of data in a table are under relatively high currency contention. Basically, what happens is most of the traffic on a table (and hence page-level locks) occurs on a small area of the table, towards the end. New records will always go to this hotspot, because IDENTITY is a sequential number generator. These inserts are troublesome because they require Exlusive page lock on the page they are added to (the hotspot). This effectively serializes all inserts to a table thanks to the page locking mechanism. NewID() on the other hand does not suffer from hotspots. Values generated using the NewID() function are only sequential for short bursts of inserts (where the function is being called very quickly, such as during a multi-row insert), which causes the inserted rows to spread randomly throughout the tablex27s data pages instead of all at the end - thus eliminating a hotspot from inserts.x3C/px3E\n\n  \n\n  x3Cpx3EAlso, because the inserts are randomly distributed, the chance of page splits is greatly reduced. While a page split here and there isnt too bad, the effects do add up quickly. With IDENTITY, page Fill Factor is pretty useless as a tuning mechanism and might as well be set to 100% - rows will never be inserted in any page but the last one. With NewID(), you can actually make use of Fill Factor as a performance-enabling tool. You can set Fill Factor to a level that approximates estimated volume growth between index rebuilds, and then schedule the rebuilds during off-peak hours using dbcc reindex. This effectively delays the performance hits of page splits until off-peak times.x3C/px3E\n\n  \n\n  x3Cpx3EIf you even x3Cemx3Ethinkx3C/emx3E you might need to enable replication for the table in question - then you might as well make the PK a uniqueidentifier and flag the guid field as ROWGUIDCOL. Replication will require a uniquely valued guid field with this attribute, and it will add one if none exists. If a suitable field exists, then it will just use the one thats there.x3C/px3E\n\n  \n\n  x3Cpx3EYet another huge benefit for using GUIDs for PKs is the fact that the value is indeed guaranteed unique - not just among all values generated by x3Cemx3Ethisx3C/emx3E server, but all values generated by x3Cemx3Eallx3C/emx3E computers - whether it be your db server, web server, app server, or client machine. Pretty much every modern language has the capability of generating a valid guid now - in .NET you can use System.Guid.NewGuid. This is VERY handy when dealing with cached master-detail datasets in particular. You dont have to employ crazy temporary keying schemes just to relate your records together before they are committed. You just fetch a perfectly valid new Guid from the operating system for each new recordx27s permanent key value at the time the record is created. x3C/px3E\n\n  \n\n  x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://forums.asp.net/t/264350.aspxx22x3Ehttp://forums.asp.net/t/264350.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3C/blockquotex3E',31,0,'2008-08-08 07:04:29'),(41580,'sdally1','x3Cpx3EI would imagine then if you have an application with some 3rd party components you may be stuffed.  I doubt a lot of vendors will develop with Mono in mindx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EExample: x3Ca href=x22http://community.devexpress.com/forums/p/55085/185853.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://community.devexpress.com/forums/p/55085/185853.aspxx3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 22:38:48'),(41580,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EI like x3Ca href=x22http://www.mbunit.com/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMbUnitx3C/ax3E, er, x3Ca href=x22http://www.gallio.org/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGalliox3C/ax3E.  Most importantly to me is having good tools support inside Visual Studio.  For that I use x3Ca href=x22http://www.jetbrains.com/resharper/index.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EResharperx3C/ax3E, which has an x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/mbunit-resharper/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMbUnit test runnerx3C/ax3E.  A lot of folks seem to like x3Ca href=x22http://www.testdriven.net/overview.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ETestDriven.NETx3C/ax3E as their test runner as well.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-05 04:57:48'),(41590,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3ESet a short timeout?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDoes x3Ccodex3EisOutputShutdown()x3C/codex3E not get you what you want?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou could always build a x3Ccodex3ESocketWatcherx3C/codex3E class that spins up in its own x3Ccodex3EThreadx3C/codex3E and repeatedly tries to write empty strings to the x3Ccodex3ESocketx3C/codex3E until that raises a x3Ccodex3ESocketClosedExceptionx3C/codex3E.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 20:33:13'),(41630,'sdally1','x3Cpx3EWith MS Sql Server 2005, try the Service Broker and/or CLR stored procedures.  I donx27t think therex27s anything built directly into TSQL.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-25 04:35:41'),(41630,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.databasejournal.com/features/mssql/article.php/3391761x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBCPx3C/ax3E - itx27s a pain to set up, but itx27s been around since the dawn of DBs and itx27s very very quick.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EUnless youx27re inserting data in that order the 3-part index will really slow things.  Applying it later will really slow things too, but will be in a second step.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ECompound keys in Sql are always quite slow, the bigger the key the slower.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-23 22:14:25'),(41640,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EIx27ve worked with Word documents in SVN. With x3Ca href=x22http://tortoisesvn.tigris.org/x22x3ETortoiseSVNx3C/ax3E, you can easily diff Word documents (between working copy and repository, or between two repository revisions). Itx27s really slick and definitely recommended.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe other thing to do if youx27re using Word documents in SVN is to add the x3Ca href=x22http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.2/svn.advanced.locking.htmlx22x3Esvn:needs-lockx3C/ax3E property to the Word documents. This will prevent two people from trying to edit the same document at the same time, since unfortunately therex27s no good way to merge Word documents.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWith the above two things, handling revision controlled Word documents is at least tolerable. It certainly beats the alternative of using a shared folder and track-changes.x3C/px3E',59,0,'2008-08-27 14:37:06'),(41640,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EIn my experience of reviewing code and design of projects I have been through, the value of OOP is not fully realised because alot of developers have x3Cstrongx3Enot properly conceptualised the object-oriented modelx3C/strongx3E in their minds. Thus they do not program with OO design, very often continuing to write top-down procedural code making the classes a pretty x3Cemx3Eflatx3C/emx3E design. (if you can even call that x22designx22 in the first place)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIt is pretty scary to observe how little colleagues know about what an abstract class or interface are, let alone properly design an inheritance hierarchy to suit the business needs.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever, when good OO design is present, it is just sheer joy reading the code and seeing the code naturally fall into place into intuitive components/classes. I have always perceived system architecture and design like designing the various departments and staff jobs in a company - all are there to accomplish a certain piece of work in the grand scheme of things, emitting the synergy required to propel the organisation/system forward.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat, of course, is quite x3Cemx3Erarex3C/emx3E unfortunately. Like the ratio of beautifully-designed versus horrendously-designed physical objects in the world, the same can pretty much be said about software engineering and design. Having the good tools at onex27s disposal does not necessarily confer good practices and results.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-24 18:57:43'),(41640,'srm4902','x3Cpx3EI use x3Ca href=x22http://code.google.com/p/msysgit/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Emsys-gitx3C/ax3E on windows every single day. Works fast and flawlessly.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAlthough the newer build has some problems with git-svn, x3Ca href=x22http://msysgit.googlecode.com/files/Git-1.5.5-preview20080413.exex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethis build (Git-1.5.5-preview20080413.exe)x3C/ax3E has a working git-svn.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-07 17:13:37'),(41970,'civakhnop','x3Cpx3EScott Hanselmann has blogged extensively about his experience in learning WPF by creating his x27BabySmashx27 windows application. All the source code is on codeplex and he has many blog articles describing his progress.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.hanselman.com/blog/IntroducingBabySmashAWPFExperiment.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EInitial BabySmash articlex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.codeplex.com/babysmash/SourceControl/ListDownloadableCommits.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECodeplex sourcex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.hanselman.com/babysmash/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBabySmash websitex3C/ax3Ex3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-27 12:10:30'),(41970,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3EIf I understand correctly, you want to sum all values in the cross section defined at each x22binx22 along 1 dimension.  I suggest making a 1D array for your destination, then looping through each element in your array adding the value to the destination with the index of the dimension of interest.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you are using arbitrary number of dimensions, you must have a way of addressing elements (I would be curious how you are implementing this).  Your implementation of this will affect how you set the destination index.  But an obvious way would be with if statements checked in the iteration loops.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-23 00:16:57'),(41970,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EIf you consider a warning (which is what [Obsolete] throws up) build-breaking, then just use the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/963th5x3.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E#warningx3C/ax3E compiler directive.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: Ix27ve never used it, but x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/x5hedts0.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E#errorx3C/ax3E is also available.x3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-26 18:19:36'),(41970,'prihak','x3Cpx3EBasically, only the GPL requires that the whole product is GPL, and LGPL implies that the parts specific to that library be open sourced. But, for both, the problem arises only when you distribute the application.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor all the other open source licenses, the only common requirement is the publicity (ie. show at some point to the user what open source component / library is used).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAfter that you have the x22no competing commercial productx22 licenses...x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAll in all, the most acknowledged business friendly license are IMHO the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/apache2.0.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EApache Licensex3C/ax3E, the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/artistic-license-2.0.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EArtistic Licensex3C/ax3E and the x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mozilla1.1.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMozilla Public licensex3C/ax3E. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFurthermore, even if x3Ca href=x22http://creativecommons.org/about/license/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ECreative Commonsx3C/ax3E is not widely used for software development, some options are business friendly.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit: forgot x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/bsd-license.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EBSDx3C/ax3E (which is more a license-template than a license) and x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/licenses/mit-license.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMITx3C/ax3E mentionned by Daniel. It seems to me that their usages are fading away, but there is some license tropism to take in account according to the development language / open source sub-community.x3C/px3E',11,0,'2008-08-26 20:42:44'),(42070,'rtomeo0','x3Cpx3EI like x3Ca href=