8-1-1 22:00x27\nif @date1=@date2\n    print x27Equalx27\nelse\n    print x27Not equalx27\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor SQL 2005 and earlier what you can do is convert the date to a varchar in a format that does not have the time component. For instance the following returns 2008.08.22x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eselect convert(varchar,x272008-08-22 18:11:14.133x27,102)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe 102 part specifies the formatting (Books online can list for you all the available formats)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo, what you can do is write a function that takes a datetime and extracts the date element and discards the time. Like so:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ecreate function MakeDate (@InputDate datetime) returns datetime as\nbegin\n    return cast(convert(varchar,@InputDate,102) as datetime);\nend\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can then use the function for companionsx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESelect * from Orders where dbo.MakeDate(OrderDate) = dbo.MakeDate(DeliveryDate)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 19:22:51'),(42200,'enewberryf','x3Cpx3EThe class that you have is not a real class in OO terms - its just been contructed to take the space of the instance variables.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said - there propably isnt much issue with speed - its just a style thing in your example.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe intresting bit - is if you contsrtucted the object to be a real x22personx22 class - and thinkng about the other attributes and actions that you may want of the person class - then you would notice not only a style performance - writting code - but also speed performance.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-23 16:12:18'),(42200,'erowcliffe1d','x3Cpx3EI donx27t see where this lets them do anything that they couldnx27t do already by calling eval.  If therex27s a security hole being introduced here, I donx27t see it.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-21 21:19:03'),(42200,'hschade12','x3Cpx3EI suppose it is an ovbious answer:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMake a requisite for the classes stored in the collection to be cloneable. You could check that at insertion time or at retrieval time, whatever makes more sense, and throw an exception.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOr if the item is not cloneable, just fail back to the return by reference option.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-27 13:53:26'),(42460,'cgaweno','x3Cpx3EI use:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://notebook.google.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EGoogle Notebookx3C/ax3E - I take notes for projects, books Ix27m reading, etcx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://delicious.comx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EDeliciousx3C/ax3E + Firefox plug in - Every time I see a good page I mark it.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Journalx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EWindows Journalx3C/ax3E (in tablet pc) - When I need to draw something and then copy/cut/paste it. I have more distractions here, the web is always very close :)x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ESmall x3Ca href=x22http://www.moleskine.com/eng/_interni/catalogo/Cat_int/catalogo_notebooks.htmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMoleskinex3C/ax3E paper notebook - Its always with me.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EBig paper notebook - When I need more space to write and less distractions.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EObviously these are for all useful information, not just for snippets or tips and tricks.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-20 17:07:52'),(42550,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EVerging on religious but I would say that youx27re painting an overly grim picture of the state of modern OOP. I would argue that it actually x3Cstrongx3Ehasx3C/strongx3E reduced costs, made large software projects manageable, and so forth. That doesnx27t mean itx27s solved the fundamental problem of software messiness, and it doesnx27t mean the average developer is an OOP expert. But the modularization of function into object-components has certainly reduced the amount of spaghetti code out there in the world.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI can think of dozens of libraries off the top of my head which are beautifully reusable and which have saved time and money that can never be calculated.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBut to the extent that OOP has been a waste of time, Ix27d say itx27s because of lack of programmer training, compounded by the steep learning curve of learning a language specific OOP mapping. Some people x22getx22 OOP and others never will.x3C/px3E',28,0,'2008-08-23 18:45:23'),(42690,'tplumsteadj','x3Cpx3EOne way of deciding whether or not to use nested classes is to think whether or not this class plays a supporting role or itx27s own part.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EIf it exists solely for the purpose of helping another class then I generally make it a nested class. There are a whole load of caveats to that, some of which seem contradictory but it all comes down to experience and gut-feeling.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-05 12:29:13'),(42710,'srm9547','x3Cpx3EIIRC, the browser pops the auth dialog when the following comes back in the request stream:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EHttp status of 401x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EWWW-Authenticate headerx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI would guess that youx27d need to suppress one or both of those. The easy way to do that is to have a login method thatx27ll take a Base64 username and password (you are using HTTPS, right?) and return 200 with a valid/invalid status. Once the password has been validated, you can use it with XHR.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-27 15:10:36'),(42770,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EI think Silverlight is most advantageous for companies that have .NET developers but noone with designer experience.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESkill sets will be easier to find as far as finding C# or VB developers vs finding ActionScript gurux27s.  However there is the trade off:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EDesign experience is an investment not only in Designers with artistic skill, but also in the knowledge and tools provided by Adobe.  You can nearly guarantee that a professional designer uses a mac and has experience with Adobe tools.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERight now the Silverlight designer tools are half baked and can be a headache.  For instance Blend errors when trying to render any xaml containing an IValueConverter, this is problematic.  I have no idea what the Adobe developer experience is, Ix27m sure it is as hairy.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo at this stage of the game it comes down to human resources:  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you have .NET experience and little invested in Design skills go Silverlight. Programming skills/tools will be transferable.\nIf you have Design experience and skill set go with Flex.  Designer skills/tools will be transferable.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEither way both client platforms require communication with services to get data, so you will always leverage your existing programing expertise on the back end. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EParaphrased x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/users/5/jon-gallowayx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EJonx27sx3C/ax3E opinion from a different point of view:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI think you should look at Flex as a long-term play, just as Adobe seems to be doing. Therex27s an obvious balance on when to use Silverlight vs. Flex when youx27re concerned about reach and install base, but here are more reasons Flex is a good direction to move in:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ESecond mover advantage - Just as\nAdobe built a x22better Java Appletx22\nwith Flash, theyx27re able to look at\nhow youx27d design a runtime from\nscratch, today. They have the\nadvantage of knowing how people use\nthe web today, something the\ninventors of existing client\nplatforms could never have\naccurately guessed. .NET can add\nfeatures, but they canx27t\nrealistically chuck the platform and\nstart over.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EDesigner familiarity - While\nFlex/AIR is a new programing model,\nitx27s not entirely unfamiliar to\ndesigners. Theyx27ll x22getx22 the way\nFlex works a lot more quickly than\ntheyx27ll understand firing up a new\ndesign environment with new feature\npoor tools and new animation\nparadigms.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EBeing rid of the RGB color model in\nSilverlight- .NET was originally\nbuilt for windows and it is at the\ncore of how it works. Flex ditched a\nlong time ago for an design-centric\nmodel.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3EAll your tools run on your mac. Nuff\nsaid.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3ECool features - Silverlight still\nhas some catching up to do with\nFlash on some obvious features (like\nwebcam / mic integration, or 3d /\ngraphics acceleration).x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E',22,0,'2008-08-22 00:00:19'),(42950,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EI am in agreement with jjnguy... I think the reasons to seal a class are few and far between.  Quite the contrary, I have been in the situation more than once where I want to extend a class, but couldnx27t because it was sealed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs a perfect example, I was recently creating a small package (Java, not C#, but same principles) to wrap functionality around the memcached tool.  I wanted an interface so in tests I could mock away the memcached client API I was using, and also so we could switch clients if the need arose (there are 2 clients listed on the memcached homepage).  Additionally, I wanted to have the opportunity to replace the functionality altogether if the need or desire arose (such as if the memcached servers are down for some reason, we could potentially hot swap with a local cache implementation instead).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI exposed a minimal interface to interact with the client API, and it would have been awesome to extend the client API class and then just add an implements clause with my new interface.  The methods that I had in the interface that matched the actual interface would then need no further details and so I wouldnx27t have to explicitly implement them.  However, the class was sealed, so I had to instead proxy calls to an internal reference to this class.  The result: more work and a lot more code for no real good reason.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said, I think there are potential times when you might want to make a class sealed... and the best thing I can think of is an API that you will invoke directly, but allow clients to implement.  For example, a game where you can program against the game... if your classes were not sealed, then the players who are adding features could potentially exploit the API to their advantage.  This is a very narrow case though, and I think any time you have full control over the codebase, there really is little if any reason to make a class sealed.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis is one reason I really like the Ruby programming language... even the core classes are open, not just to extend but to ADD AND CHANGE functionality dynamically, TO THE CLASS ITSELF!  Itx27s called monkeypatching and can be a nightmare if abused, but itx27s damn fun to play with!x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 01:57:11'),(42950,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3E+1 for separation.  I just came onto a project where some classes are in files with a different name, or lumped in with another class, and it is impossible to find these in a quick and efficient manner.  You can throw more resources at a build - you canx27t make up lost programmer time because (s)he canx27t find the right file to edit.x3C/px3E',6,0,'2008-08-26 18:28:28'),(42980,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29580/why-is-pagination-so-resource-expensive#29588x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ELubosx3C/ax3E is right, the problem is not the fact that you are paging (which takes a HUGE amount of data off the wire), but that you need to figure out what is actually going on the page..x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe fact that you need to page implies there is a lot of data. A lot of data takes a long time to sort :)x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-27 09:47:48'),(42990,'hbuxcy1c','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/23310/source-control-beginners#23353x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E@Ian Nelsonx3C/ax3E:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EI agree with you that Source Safe is bad as a source control system, but keep in mind that using Source Safe is a lot better than x22carrying around floppy disksx22 as Joel Spolsky said.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor a beginner it might not be a bad idea, since the cost of having no source control at all is a lot higher.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-24 00:55:44'),(42990,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3ESimplest way: navigate to the directory containing the solution or project file, and run x3Ccodex3Emsbuildx3C/codex3E (assuming you have Visual Studio 2005 or newer).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EMore flexible ways:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3ERead up on x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/0k6kkbsd.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethe MSBuild\nreferencex3C/ax3E. There are tons of\ncustomization, especially once\nyoux27ve installed the x3Ca href=x22https://github.com/loresoft/msbuildtasksx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSBuild Community Tasks Projectx3C/ax3E.  x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EUse x3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NAntx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ENAntx3C/ax3E. It has existed\nfor longer than MSBuild and has more\ncommunity support, but requires you\nto start a project file from\nscratch, rather than extending the\nexisting, Visual Studio-created one.x3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',4,0,'2008-08-24 00:44:58'),(43180,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EOpenID seems to be a very good alternative to writing your own user management/authentication piece.  Ix27m seeing more and more sites using OpenID these days, so the barrier to entry for your users should be relatively low.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 19:42:21'),(43290,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3EThe following (C#) code should do the trickx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EUri uri = new Uri(x22http://www.mywebsite.com:80/pages/page1.aspxx22);\nstring requested = uri.Scheme + Uri.SchemeDelimiter + uri.Host + x22:x22 + uri.Port;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',101,0,'2008-08-22 17:35:39'),(43290,'fbrizellc','x3Cpx3EItx27s always best to use the lowest base type possible. This gives the implementer of your interface, or consumer of your method, the opportunity to use whatever they like behind the scenes.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EFor collections you should aim to use IEnumerable where possible. This gives the most flexibility but is not always suited.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-20 03:41:13'),(43290,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EAs with anything abstraction creates complexity, and so the complexity of doing N-tiered should be properly justified, e.g., does N-tiered actually benefit the system? There x3Cemx3Ewillx3C/emx3E be small systems that will work best with N-tiered, although a lot of them will not.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso, even if your system is small at the moment, you might want to add more features to it later -- not going N-tiered x3Cemx3Emightx3C/emx3E consitute a sort of technical debt on your part, so you have to be careful.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-08 17:58:59'),(43320,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EWith a six word character password, he may have been brute forced.  That is more likely than his ftp being intercepted, but it could be that too.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EStart with a stronger password. (8 characters is still fairly weak)x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ESee if this link to an internet x3Ca href=x22http://blog.modsecurity.org/2008/01/is-your-website.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Esecurity blogx3C/ax3E is helpful.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-06 04:00:22'),(43500,'msmallpeacex','x3Cpx3EAs far as local, static html goes, unless you specify it, most browsers will take the location of the html file you are viewing as the root. So any css put in there can just be referenced by itx27s name only. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe lazy way to get the correct reference for your css file is to open it in your browser. Then just grab the url that you see there - something like: x3Cprex3Efile:///blah/test.cssx3C/prex3E and copy that into your stylesheet link on your html: x3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;link href=x22file:///blah/test.cssx22 rel=x22stylesheetx22 type=x22text/cssx22x26gt;x3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEither that or you can just take the url for the html file and amend it to refer to the stylesheet.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen your local page should load fine with the local stylesheet.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 14:42:52'),(43580,'rdowdellz','x3CPx3EIt sounds like youx27re talking about C#x27s Extension Methods. You add functionality to existing classes by inserting the x22thisx22 keyword before the first parameter. The method has to be a static method in a static class. Strings in .NET already have a x22Trimx22 method, so Ix27ll use another example.x3C/Px3Ex3CPREx3Ex3CCODEx3Epublic static class MyStringEtensions\n\n{\n\n    public static bool ContainsMabster(this string s)\n\n    {\n\n        return s.Contains(x22Mabsterx22);\n\n    }\n\n}\n\nx3C/CODEx3Ex3C/PREx3E\n\nx3CPx3ESo now every string has a tremendously useful ContainsMabster method, which I can use like this:x3C/Px3Ex3CPREx3Ex3CCODEx3Eif (x22Why hello there, Mabster!x22.ContainsMabster()) { /* ... */ }\n\nx3C/CODEx3Ex3C/PREx3E\n\nx3CPx3ENote that you can also add extension methods to interfaces (eg IList), which means that any class implementing that interface will also pick up that new method.x3C/Px3E\n\nx3CPx3EAny extra parameters you declare in the extension method (after the first x22thisx22 parameter) are treated as normal parameters.x3C/Px3E',4,0,'2008-08-07 16:09:02'),(43870,'osilley7','x3Cpx3EAs Kibbee hinted at above, the argument of leveraging existing .Net developers doesnx27t hold much water.  It is impossible to be an expert in all facets of .Net development.  The platform is just too big.  The same goes for Java.  The only thing Silverlight has going for it from a skills perspective is that you can code in your favorite .Net language.  That advantage is fairly small if you are already doing any significant web development that utilizes JavaScript since Action script is a variation.  So really to convert a programmer to either Flex or Silverlight is all about learning the platformx27s API.    x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-21 23:58:15'),(43870,'scurraghy','x3Cpx3EThe OSI has a number of good resources with x3Ca href=x22http://www.opensource.org/advocacy/case_for_business.phpx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ehttp://www.opensource.org/advocacy/case_for_business.phpx3C/ax3E probably being the most relevant for you.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are loads of open source projects and when popular, the best advantage in my opinion is having bug fixes and enhancements contributed back into the project. You tend to only develop the necessary features for the use case at your job (exceptions do exist of course) and itx27s good to have other people work on other areas of the project.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThat said, people will usually only do that if they have a use for the project themselves and raising awareness can be just as hard as marketing a commercial project - you will probably find only a few people use it having stumbled upon the project through an obscure Google search!x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAs such, whilst there are a lot of development oriented advantages, even if there arenx27t many (or any) actual users, it looks very good from a business/company perspective that your organisation is supporting the release of internal projects under open source licenses. This shows good things to prospective employees about the openess of the organisation.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo whilst you only get the big open source advantages with scale, there are less obvious ones that start working immediately, namely building a good name for your company.x3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-21 00:14:45'),(43890,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EThere are two rules I follow:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3EAccept the most basic type that will workx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3EReturn the richest type your user will needx3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo when writing a function or method that takes a collection, write it not to take a List, but an IListx26lt;Tx26gt;, an ICollectionx26lt;Tx26gt;, or IEnumerablex26lt;Tx26gt;.  The generic interfaces will still work even for heterogenous lists because System.Object can be a T too.  Doing this will save you headache if you decide to use a Stack or some other data structure further down the road.  If all you need to do in the function is foreach through it, IEnumerablex26lt;Tx26gt; is really all you should be asking for.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOn the other hand, when returning an object out of a function, you want to give the user the richest possible set of operations without them having to cast around.  So in that case, if itx27s a Listx26lt;Tx26gt; internally, return a copy as a Listx26lt;Tx26gt;.x3C/px3E',119,0,'2008-08-20 05:33:16'),(43920,'aillidges','x3Cpx3EAre they participating in the stand-up meetings?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou could propose to have a representative at each (or some) of them, to ask them for input before the end of the sprintx3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-26 22:57:22'),(43920,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EThere are several usages of x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/dk1507sz.aspxx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E keyword in C#.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/vstudio/dk1507sz%28v=vs.100%29.aspxx22x3ETo qualify members hidden by similar namex3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/vstudio/dk1507sz%28v=vs.100%29.aspxx22x3ETo have an object pass itself as a parameter to other methodsx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETo have an object return itself from a methodx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/6x16t2tx.aspxx22x3ETo declare indexersx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb383977.aspxx22x3ETo declare extension methodsx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/7011/An-Intro-to-Constructors-in-C%29x22x3ETo pass parameters between constructorsx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/194484/whats-the-strangest-corner-case-youve-seen-in-c-or-net/1800162#1800162x22x3ETo internally reassign value type (struct) valuex3C/ax3E.x3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETo invoke an extension method on the current instancex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ETo cast itself to another typex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1814953/c-sharp-constructor-chaining-how-to-do-itx22x3ETo chain constructors defined in the same classx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EYou can avoid the first usage by not having member and local variables with the same name in scope, for example by following common naming conventions and using properties (Pascal case) instead of fields (camel case) to avoid colliding with local variables (also camel case). In C# 3.0 fields can be converted to properties easily by using x3Ca href=x22https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb384054.aspxx22x3Eauto-implemented propertiesx3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E',166,0,'2008-08-23 01:12:48'),(43940,'prihak','x3Cpx3EI canx27t find any documentation that says you shouldnx27t use those methods directly, but I havenx27t looked very long.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EAlso you refer to the EditorVisibleAttribute, which doesnx27t exist. According to Reflector itx27s the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/system.componentmodel.editorbrowsableattribute.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EEditorBrowsableAttributex3C/ax3E.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EReflector disassembly:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3E[EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]\npublic bool CheckAccess()\n{\n//CODE\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 11:22:02'),(43960,'dsizland14','x3Cpx3EDespite what the x3Ca href=x22http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/x6kd89c5%28VS.80%29.aspxx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EMSDN articlex3C/ax3E  says about User/Machine Hive, it doesnx27t write to HKEY_USERS. Rather it writes to HKCU if you select Just Me and HKLM if you select Everyone.x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3ESo my solution is going to be to use the User/Machine Hive, and then in the application it checks if the registry entries are in HKCU and if not, copies them from HKLM. I know this probably isnx27t the most ideal way of doing it, but it has the least amount of changes.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-04 02:34:06'),(43970,'ajan8','x3Cpx3EEric Z Beard:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EI do store all dates in GMT. Herex27s the use case: something happened at 11:00 PM EST on the 1st, which is the 2nd GMT. I want to see activity for the 1st, and I am in EST so I will want to see the 11PM activity. If I just compared raw GMT datetimes, I would miss things. Each row in the report can represent an activity from a different time zone.x3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ERight, but when you say youx27re interested in activity for Jan 1st 2008 EST:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT @activityDateMidnight = x271/1/2008x27, @activityDateTZ = x27ESTx27\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eyou just need to convert x3Cemx3Ethatx3C/emx3E to GMT (Ix27m ignoring the complication of querying for the day before EST goes to EDT, or vice versa):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ETable: TimeZone\nFields: TimeZone, Offset\nValues: EST, -4\n\n--Multiply by -1, since wex27re converting EST to GMT.\n--Offsets are to go from GMT to EST.\nSELECT @activityGmtBegin = DATEADD(hh, Offset * -1, @activityDateMidnight)\nFROM TimeZone\nWHERE TimeZone = @activityDateTZ\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ewhich should give you x271/1/2008 4:00 AMx27. Then, you can just search in GMT:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3ESELECT * FROM EventTable\nWHERE \n   EventTime x26gt;= @activityGmtBegin --1/1/2008 4:00 AM\n   AND EventTime x26lt; (@activityGmtBegin + 1) --1/2/2008 4:00 AM\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe event in question is stored with a GMT EventTime of 1/2/2008 3:00 AM. You donx27t even need the TimeZone in the EventTable (for this purpose, at least). x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESince EventTime is not in a function, this is a straight index scan - which should be pretty efficient. Make EventTime your clustered index, and itx27ll fly. ;)x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EPersonally, Ix27d have the app convert the search time into GMT before running the query.x3C/px3E',2,0,'2008-08-22 20:33:13'),(43970,'hginglell13','x3Cpx3EYou pretty much have to keep the left side of your where clause clean. So, normally, youx27d do something like:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EWHERE MyDateTime x26gt;= @activityDateMidnight \n      AND MyDateTime x26lt; (@activityDateMidnight + 1)\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Some folks prefer DATEADD(d, 1, @activityDateMidnight) instead - but itx27s the same thing).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThe TimeZone table complicates matter a bit though. Itx27s a little unclear from your snippet, but it looks like t.TheDateInTable is in GMT with a Time Zone identifier, and that youx27re then adding the offset to compare against @activityDateMidnight - which is in local time. Ix27m not sure what ds.LocalTimeZone is, though.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf thatx27s the case, then you need to get @activityDateMidnight into GMT instead.x3C/px3E',10,0,'2008-08-22 19:16:00'),(43970,'srm9547','x3Cpx3ESubscribe in Google Reader and then search later.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-20 16:14:25'),(43970,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3ESubversion + TortoiseSVNx3C/px3E',4,0,'2008-08-23 01:21:20'),(43970,'tvallentint','x3Cpx3EDelete the executable as part of a pre-link event.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit:\nHah, I forgot about Explorer resetting the creation date if you name a file exactly the same as a file that was recently deleted.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhy are you keying off the creation date anyway?x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-20 20:02:34'),(44080,'ofaircloughi','x3Cpx3EJavascript offers 3 modal boxes.  Prompt, confirm and alert.  None of those satisfy your request.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are a plethora of js modal popup solutions.  Herex27s an example.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.wildbit.com/labs/modalbox/x22x3EModalBoxx3C/ax3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',6,0,'2008-08-21 07:31:16'),(44080,'sfitzhenryv','x3Cpx3EWithout doing detailed analysis, Ix27d guess that itx27s faster because of the question marks. These allow the regular expression to be x22lazy,x22 and stop as soon as they have enough to match, rather than checking if the rest of the input matches.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27m not entirely happy with this answer though, because this mostly applies to question marks after * or +. If I were more familiar with the input, it might make more sense to me.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E(Also, for the code formatting, you can select all of your code and press x3Ckbdx3ECtrlx3C/kbdx3E+x3Ckbdx3EKx3C/kbdx3E to have it add the four spaces required.)x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-07 19:57:16'),(44080,'tyurkiewicz19','x3Cpx3EThe following will workx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;%= Post.find_unread_by(current_user).size %x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Eorx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;%= Post.find_unread_by(current_user).length %x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHowever if you check your development.log you should see that it gets the unread count by x3C/px3E\n\nx3Colx3E\nx3Clix3ERetrieving all the postsx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ERetrieving all the posts read by the userx3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3ERemoving all of 2. from 1. in rubyx3C/lix3E\nx3C/olx3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis will be very bad performance wise with lots of posts. x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EA better way would be to retrieve the posts read by the current user and then use ActiveRecord::Calculations to get a count without retrieving all the posts in the databasex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3EPost.count(:conditions =x26gt; [ x22id NOT IN (?)x22, Post.find_read_by(current_user)])\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThis should go into your Post model to follow best practices of not having finders in the view  or controller x3C/px3E\n\nx3Ch2x3EPost.rbx3C/h2x3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Edef self.unread_post_count_for_user(user)\n  count(:conditions =x26gt; [ x22id NOT IN (?)x22, Post.find_read_by(user)])\nend\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThen your view will just bex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;%= Post.unread_post_count_for_user(current-user) %x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E',10,0,'2008-08-22 22:33:33'),(44100,'eburnyaten','x3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EC/C++x3C/strongx3E: Proceduralx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eunsigned long factorial(int n)\n{\n    unsigned long factorial = 1;\n    int i;\n\n    for (i = 2; i x26lt;= n; i++)\n    	factorial *= i;\n\n    return factorial;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EPHPx3C/strongx3E: Proceduralx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Efunction factorial($n)\n{\n    for ($factorial = 1, $i = 2; $i x26lt;= $n; $i++)\n    	$factorial *= $i;\n\n    return $factorial;\n}\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/23930/factorial-algorithms-in-different-languages#23979x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3E@Niyazx3C/ax3E: You didnx27t specify return type for the functionx3C/px3E',5,0,'2008-08-23 08:32:03'),(44100,'idevey11','x3Cpx3EIt suppose to be a x3Ca href=x22http://www.microsoft.com/technet/prodtechnol/windows2000serv/reskit/regentry/55200.mspx?mfr=truex22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Eregistry changex3C/ax3E  that helps with this type of situations (mentioned in x3Ca href=x22http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001011.htmlx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3Ethisx3C/ax3E Coding Horror post about the subject of x22focus stealingx22). I try it, it doesnx27t work with x3Cemx3Eallx3C/emx3E popups but helps with some of them, causing the offending application to flash in the taskbar instead of gain focus.x3C/px3E',0,0,'2008-08-22 03:54:07'),(44220,'astarmoreq','x3Cpx3EI work the same way Karl does, by keeping all of my SQL scripts for creating and altering tables in a text file that I keep in source control.  In fact, to avoid the problem of having to have a script examine the live database to determine what ALTERs to run, I usually work like this:x3C/px3E\n\n\n\nx3Culx3E\n\nx3Clix3EOn the first version, I place everything during testing into one SQL script, and treat all tables as a CREATE.  This means I end up dropping and readding tables a lot during testing, but thatx27s not a big deal early into the project (since Ix27m usually hacking the data Ix27m using at that point anyway).x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EOn all subsequent versions, I do two things: I make a new text file to hold the upgrade SQL scripts, that contain just the ALTERs for that version.  And I make the changes to the original, create a fresh database script as well.  This way an upgrade just runs the upgrade script, but if we have to recreate the DB we donx27t need to run 100 scripts to get there.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3Clix3EDepending on how Ix27m deploying the DB changes, Ix27ll also usually put a version table in the DB that holds the version of the DB.  Then, rather than make any human decisions about which scripts to run, whatever code I have running the create/upgrade scripts uses the version to determine what to run.x3C/lix3E\n\nx3C/ulx3E\n\n\n\nx3Cpx3EThe one thing this will not do is help if part of what youx27re moving from test to production is data, but if you want to manage structure and not pay for a nice, but expensive DB management package, is really not very difficult.  Ix27ve also found itx27s a pretty good way of keeping mental track of your DB.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-03 04:37:03'),(44220,'jsorel9','x3Cblockquotex3E\n  x3Cpx3EThe real world isnx27t x22OOx22, and the idea implicit in OO--that we can model things with some class taxonomy--seems to me very fundamentally flawedx3C/px3E\nx3C/blockquotex3E\n\nx3Cpx3EWhile this is true and has been observed by other people (take Stepanov, inventor of the STL), the rest is nonsense. OOP may be flawed and it certainly is no silver bullet but it makes large-scale applications much simpler because itx27s a great way to reduce dependencies. Of course, this is only true for “good” OOP design. Sloppy design wonx27t give any advantage. But good, decoupled design can be modelled very well using OOP and not well using other techniques.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EThere are much better, more universal models (x3Ca href=x22http://stackoverflow.com/questions/16770/haskells-algebraic-data-typesx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EHaskellx27s type modelx3C/ax3E comes to mind) but these are also often more complicated and/or difficult to implement efficiently. OOP is a good trade-off between extremes.x3C/px3E',119,0,'2008-08-23 18:48:10'),(44220,'mbeckinsale1a','x3Cpx3EIf most of your customers are mostly businesses then I think that using anything other than email creates problems for your customers. Most people are comfortable with email address login and since they are a business customer will likely want to use their work email rather than a personal account. OpenID creates a situation where there is a third party involved and many businesses donx27t like a third party involved.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-08 19:54:51'),(44260,'chenburyh','x3Cpx3EThe DataGrid was originally in .NET 1.0.  The GridView was introduced (and replaced the DataGrid) in .NET 2.0.  They provide nearly identical functionality.x3C/px3E',7,0,'2008-08-07 05:05:56'),(44630,'aillidges','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://toadworld.com/x22x3ETOAD for MS SQLx3C/ax3E looks pretty good.  Ix27ve never used it personally but I have used Questx27s other products and theyx27re solid.x3C/px3E',16,0,'2008-08-07 23:17:11'),(44630,'jsorel9','x3Cpx3EOne strategy you could use is MVCC, Multi-Value Concurrency Control.  In this scheme, you never do updates to any of your tables, you just do inserts, maintaining version numbers for each record.  This has the advantage of providing an exact snapshot from any point in time, and it also completely sidesteps the update lock problems that plague many databases.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBut it makes for a huge database, and selects all require an extra clause to select the current version of a record.x3C/px3E',17,0,'2008-08-23 04:14:00'),(44630,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EI havenx27t looked up the whole thing, but the problem lies somewhere in the style sheets.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you copy out only the table part of it, it is displaying the map correctly.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIf you remove the final x3Ccodex3Ex26lt;/spanx26gt;x3C/codex3E tag from this part, it is also working (however the page gets mixed):x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Ex26lt;div class=x22innerx22x26gt;x26lt;span class=x22corners-topx22x26gt;x26lt;spanx26gt;x26lt;/spanx26gt;x26lt;/spanx26gt;\nx26lt;div class=x22contentx22 style=x22font-size: 1.1em;x22x26gt;\n\nx26lt;!-- Stackoverflow findy thingy --x26gt;\nx26lt;table border=x220x22 cellspacing=x220x22 cellpadding=x220x22x26gt;\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3ESo either try from the beginning with the css or try to remove one-by-one them, to see, which is causing the problem.x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-22 14:09:20'),(44660,'dmatuszinski15','x3Cpx3Ex3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf#printf_format_placeholdersx22x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf#printf_format_placeholdersx22x3Ehttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Printf#printf_format_placeholdersx3C/ax3Ex3C/ax3E is Wikipediax27s reference for format placeholders in printf. x3Ca href=x22http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/clibrary/cstdio/printf.htmlx22x3Ex3Ca href=x22http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/clibrary/cstdio/printf.htmlx22x3Ehttp://www.cplusplus.com/reference/clibrary/cstdio/printf.htmlx3C/ax3Ex3C/ax3E is also helpfulx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EBasically in a simple form itx27s %[width].[precision][type]. Width allows you to make sure that the variable which is being printed is at least a certain length (useful for tables etc). Precision allows you to specify the precision a number is printed to (eg. decimal places etc) and the informs C/C++ what the variable youx27ve given it is (character, integer, double etc).x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHope this helpsx3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EUPDATE:x3C/strongx3Ex3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3ETo clarify using your examples:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cprex3Ex3Ccodex3Eprintf( x22%10.1f     %10.2\\nx22, radius, area );\nx3C/codex3Ex3C/prex3E\n\nx3Cpx3E%10.1f (referring to the first argument: radius) means make it 10 characters long (ie. pad with spaces), and print it as a float with one decimal place.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3E%10.2 (referring to the second argument: area) means make it 10 character long (as above) and print with two decimal places.x3C/px3E',15,0,'2008-08-20 17:50:05'),(44660,'dperrenl','x3Cpx3EIf youx27re after things like server data, would x3Ca href=x22http://oss.oetiker.ch/rrdtool/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ERRDToolx3C/ax3E be something youx27re after?\nItx27s not really a webserver type stats program though, I have no idea how it would scale.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EEdit:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EIx27ve also just found x3Ca href=x22http://wiki.splunk.com/Splunk_swarmx22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3ESplunk Swarmx3C/ax3E, if youx27re interested in something that looks x22coolx22.x3C/px3E',3,0,'2008-08-21 12:59:13'),(44660,'srm4902','Something regex',0,0,'2022-05-07 14:04:02'),(44760,'sspindlerw','x3Cpx3EIdeally I looked for components licensed under the x3Ca href=x22http://www.apache.org/licenses/x22 rel=x22nofollowx22x3EApache Software Licensex3C/ax3E. After that LGPL, BSD and Artistic License are my next preferences. x3C/px3E',1,0,'2008-08-26 20:47:20');
