x3E',1,4,'ofaircloughi','2008-08-11 09:24:33'),(7720,'Packaging Java apps for the Windows/Linux desktop','x3Cpx3EI am writing an application in Java for the desktop using the Eclipse SWT library for GUI rendering.  I think SWT helps Java get over the biggest hurdle for acceptance on the desktop: namely providing a Java application with a consistent, responsive interface that looks like that belonging to any other app on your desktop.  However, I feel that packaging an application is still an issue.  x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EOS X natively provides an easy mechanism for wrapping Java apps in native application bundles, but producing an app for Windows/Linux that doesnx27t require the user to run an ugly batch file or click on a .jar is still a hassle.  Possibly thatx27s not such an issue on Linux, where the user is likely to be a little more tech-savvy, but on Windows Ix27d like to have a regular .exe for him/her to run.x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3EHas anyone had any experience with any of the .exe generation tools for Java that are out there?  Ix27ve tried JSmooth but had various issues with it.  Is there a better solution before I crack out Visual Studio and roll my own?x3C/px3E\n\nx3Cpx3Ex3Cstrongx3EEdit:x3C/strongx3E  I should perhaps mention that I am unable to spend a lot of money on a commercial solution.x3C/px3E',1,5,'nivakhnov17','2008-08-11 16:37:50'),(7880,'How do you open a file in C++?','x3Cpx3EI want to open a file for reading, the C++ way. I need to be able to do it for:x3C/px3E\n\nx3Culx3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Etext files, which would involve some sort of read line function.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3Clix3Ex3Cpx3Ebinary files, which would provide a way to read raw data into a x3Ccodex3Echar*x3C/codex3E buffer.x3C/px3Ex3C/lix3E\nx3C/ulx3E',1,11,'clawrence3','2008-08-11 19:50:51'),(7940,'How important is W3C XHTML/CSS validation when finalizing work?','x3Cpx3EEven though I always strive for complete validation these days, I often wonder if itx27s a waste of time.  If the code runs 